1
00:00:31,008 --> 00:00:33,211
All right, on Undercover Chef,

2
00:00:33,211 --> 00:00:35,847
we asked viewers to vote in advance.

3
00:00:35,847 --> 00:00:36,948
- Right.
- We did.

4
00:00:36,948 --> 00:00:41,819
They had to pick the new rookie
from these three chefs.

5
00:00:41,819 --> 00:00:43,688
Who would they choose?

6
00:00:43,688 --> 00:00:47,024
- Right.
- Who do you think got the most votes?

7
00:00:47,024 --> 00:00:49,794
I'm sure it wasn't Chef Kwon Sung Jun.

8
00:00:49,794 --> 00:00:50,795
You don't think it's Sung Jun.

9
00:00:50,795 --> 00:00:52,336
- I don't think it's me either.
- Same.

10
00:00:52,336 --> 00:00:54,599
- Me neither. I don't think it's him.
- I wouldn't pick me.

11
00:00:54,599 --> 00:00:56,200
So you think it's not him.

12
00:00:56,200 --> 00:00:58,269
[Sam Kim's guess]
I think Chef Jung Ji Sun won.

13
00:00:58,269 --> 00:01:00,605
- As first place? The most votes?
- Yes.

14
00:01:00,605 --> 00:01:02,206
- If she came in as the rookie...
- Well...

15
00:01:02,206 --> 00:01:04,075
- She looks sharp right away.
- Right.

16
00:01:04,075 --> 00:01:05,743
[Chef Jung Ji Sun review]
She seems so on top of it.

17
00:01:05,743 --> 00:01:07,778
- She'd do well.
- She'd read the room fast.

18
00:01:07,778 --> 00:01:09,080
- No talking back.
- Exactly.

19
00:01:09,080 --> 00:01:11,382
Then, what about you, Ji Sun?

20
00:01:11,382 --> 00:01:13,518
I thought it would be Chef Sam Kim.

21
00:01:13,518 --> 00:01:14,819
I picked Chef Sam Kim too.

22
00:01:14,819 --> 00:01:16,654
Really?

23
00:01:16,654 --> 00:01:18,155
He'd be careful and good...

24
00:01:18,155 --> 00:01:21,158
He seems like he'd be a good listener.

25
00:01:21,158 --> 00:01:23,728
- I feel like we'd vibe well.
- I think...

26
00:01:23,728 --> 00:01:25,496
Then who do you think came second?

27
00:01:25,496 --> 00:01:26,864
- What about you?
- Me.

28
00:01:26,864 --> 00:01:28,853
- You think it's you? Second place.
- Yes.

29
00:01:28,853 --> 00:01:30,635
[Jung Ji Sun's guess]
I also thought it might be me.

30
00:01:30,635 --> 00:01:32,537
- For second place.
- Really? Maybe it's actually me.

31
00:01:32,537 --> 00:01:34,831
- Really?
- That could happen.

32
00:01:34,831 --> 00:01:37,909
First place feels like too much pressure,
and it probably isn't last either,

33
00:01:37,909 --> 00:01:39,944
- but nobody thinks you're last either,
- Right.

34
00:01:39,944 --> 00:01:42,246
so you all think
you're somewhere in the middle.

35
00:01:42,246 --> 00:01:44,549
[Who's the #2 rookie?]
All right, let's see. The answer is...

36
00:01:44,549 --> 00:01:46,384
- Chef Kwon Sung Jun.
- Really?

37
00:01:46,384 --> 00:01:47,418
[Shock]
I knew it.

38
00:01:47,418 --> 00:01:49,520
Second place goes to Chef Kwon Sung Jun.

39
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,355
- Hold on, that's surprising.
- Wait... this result is unexpected.

40
00:01:51,355 --> 00:01:52,757
That means one of us is in last place.

41
00:01:52,757 --> 00:01:56,027
- So, one of you two is dead last?
- No way.

42
00:01:56,027 --> 00:01:57,161
That's strange.

43
00:01:57,161 --> 00:01:59,196
[Sudden honest take]
I think Chef Jung Ji Sun is last.

44
00:01:59,196 --> 00:02:02,366
- Why?
- Why?

45
00:02:02,366 --> 00:02:04,035
- Why?
- She seems a little scary.

46
00:02:04,035 --> 00:02:05,154
Oh, because she's scary?

47
00:02:05,154 --> 00:02:06,404
- Come on.
- If she came in as the rookie...

48
00:02:06,404 --> 00:02:07,471
- Oh, even as a rookie?
- I'd work hard.

49
00:02:07,471 --> 00:02:09,473
- It feels like I'd just get eaten alive.
- Who voted for this?

50
00:02:09,473 --> 00:02:10,608
So,

51
00:02:10,608 --> 00:02:13,878
[Who's the last-place rookie? Who's #1?]
between Chef Sam Kim and Chef Jung Ji Sun,

52
00:02:13,878 --> 00:02:16,814
who is the number one?

53
00:02:16,814 --> 00:02:17,874
First place is...

54
00:02:17,874 --> 00:02:20,251
Drumroll please...

55
00:02:20,251 --> 00:02:23,086
- I knew it.
- Chef Sam Kim.

56
00:02:24,221 --> 00:02:26,123
[Modest Hee Tae]
This is kind of unexpected.

57
00:02:26,123 --> 00:02:27,291
Do they show the reasons?

58
00:02:27,291 --> 00:02:28,793
[Heh]
Hold on.

59
00:02:28,793 --> 00:02:30,094
- Wait a sec.
- There's no reason?

60
00:02:30,094 --> 00:02:31,329
[He looks the kindest]

61
00:02:31,329 --> 00:02:36,200
[A rookie who works hard and has good manners]
[#Kind #Reads the room #Picks things up fast]

62
00:02:36,200 --> 00:02:38,681
[Sam Kim. He'd do exactly what he's told]

63
00:02:38,681 --> 00:02:40,738
[Plenty of people agree with Ji Sun]

64
00:02:40,738 --> 00:02:45,443
I read the public's view exactly right.
First place, second place, third place.

65
00:02:45,443 --> 00:02:47,211
True.

66
00:02:47,211 --> 00:02:48,988
- That's true.
- So the rookie...

67
00:02:48,988 --> 00:02:51,689
- What's the actual reason?
- Ji Sun, you're not upset, are you?

68
00:02:51,689 --> 00:02:53,826
It's just that
you can look a little intimidating.

69
00:02:53,826 --> 00:02:55,353
[Of course, there are people
who picked Chef Ji Sun as the #1 rookie!]

70
00:02:55,353 --> 00:02:56,899
[One reason in particular stands out...]

71
00:02:56,899 --> 00:03:00,057
[A rookie with strong opinions
changes the team]

72
00:03:00,057 --> 00:03:02,293
The thing is, this was a pre-broadcast vote.

73
00:03:02,293 --> 00:03:03,761
If they'd seen the show,
I'd be dead last for sure.

74
00:03:03,761 --> 00:03:05,529
Right.

75
00:03:05,529 --> 00:03:06,864
[Belated reassurance for big sis]
So people just didn't know yet.

76
00:03:06,864 --> 00:03:10,254
- They don't know.
- They don't know who Kwon Sung Jun really is.

77
00:03:10,254 --> 00:03:11,435
[Teach Kwon one thing, he'll do ten]

78
00:03:11,435 --> 00:03:12,637
[We'll see if he's really that rookie]
All right.

79
00:03:12,637 --> 00:03:15,906
He always claims he can win over
palates from all over the world.

80
00:03:15,906 --> 00:03:18,476
[Can he win over the Naples sisters too?]
Let's watch Chef Kwon Sung Jun's footage.

81
00:03:18,476 --> 00:03:20,477
This'll be fun.

82
00:03:21,112 --> 00:03:22,525
[Naples, Italy. Not Kwon, but Sam Kwon]

83
00:03:22,525 --> 00:03:24,515
[Undercover Rookie, Day 1]

84
00:03:24,515 --> 00:03:26,525
- Kwon, see you later.
- Yes, see you then.

85
00:03:26,525 --> 00:03:29,186
[Break time 3:00 PM]
Have a good evening.

86
00:03:29,186 --> 00:03:32,757
[Return by 6:30 PM]

87
00:03:32,757 --> 00:03:35,773
[Riposo: Rest]
[A full three hours off]

88
00:03:36,727 --> 00:03:39,030
[Italian restaurant break times]

89
00:03:39,030 --> 00:03:41,966
[Usually three to five hours]
They get a three-hour break? Until six?

90
00:03:41,966 --> 00:03:44,634
- Service starts late, so...
- Right.

91
00:03:44,634 --> 00:03:46,237
The further south, the later it starts.

92
00:03:46,237 --> 00:03:49,073
[Dinner starts around 8 PM and runs late]

93
00:03:49,073 --> 00:03:52,843
[Most staff head home for a short rest]

94
00:03:52,843 --> 00:03:55,301
[Our Kwon heads home too...]

95
00:03:56,981 --> 00:03:59,884
[His first service was pretty spicy]
[Why?]

96
00:03:59,884 --> 00:04:03,054
[He was on antipasto duty next to Antonio...]
They are the same thing.

97
00:04:03,054 --> 00:04:06,524
You can't walk in or out
of the kitchen empty-handed.

98
00:04:06,524 --> 00:04:08,626
Don't toss it in the oil.

99
00:04:08,626 --> 00:04:11,495
Don't pull out all the trays like that.

100
00:04:11,495 --> 00:04:12,596
I'm asking if you put it in before the oven.

101
00:04:12,596 --> 00:04:13,431
[Brain freeze]

102
00:04:13,431 --> 00:04:16,634
- No.
- You do it before the oven.

103
00:04:16,634 --> 00:04:18,559
[Senior An's close care drained Kwon's face]
The station must stay clean.

104
00:04:18,559 --> 00:04:19,579
Okay.

105
00:04:19,579 --> 00:04:22,339
[He even started swaying...]

106
00:04:22,339 --> 00:04:25,409
[Exhausted]

107
00:04:25,409 --> 00:04:28,879
[Kwon's place, 3:15 PM. After that storm]

108
00:04:28,879 --> 00:04:32,183
[Trudge]

109
00:04:32,183 --> 00:04:33,651
[Once home, Kwon's choice was...]

110
00:04:33,651 --> 00:04:35,386
He should catch some sleep.

111
00:04:35,386 --> 00:04:36,921
[Asleep]

112
00:04:36,921 --> 00:04:39,990
<i>When you fill the center with cream,</i>

113
00:04:39,990 --> 00:04:43,026
[He still hears Senior An's voice]
<i>the pastry bag can go deep in.</i>

114
00:04:43,761 --> 00:04:47,665
[Heartbreaking...]
[Kwon collapsed after the brutal first service]

115
00:04:47,665 --> 00:04:50,835
[But]

116
00:04:50,835 --> 00:04:53,069
- What?
- Huh?

117
00:04:53,069 --> 00:04:54,138
Is he not going to wake up?

118
00:04:54,138 --> 00:04:55,439
Seriously?

119
00:04:55,439 --> 00:04:57,808
20 minutes before return.

120
00:04:57,808 --> 00:04:59,577
[Alarm goes off]

121
00:04:59,577 --> 00:05:01,871
Alarm. He'll wake up to the alarm, right?

122
00:05:01,871 --> 00:05:04,749
[Bolts up]
He set the alarm for 20 minutes before?

123
00:05:04,749 --> 00:05:06,250
[Nerves of steel, respect]
That's something else.

124
00:05:06,250 --> 00:05:08,385
[Wait... the time...]
Seriously?

125
00:05:11,506 --> 00:05:14,391
[20 minutes until evening shift!]
He's got to get there in 20 minutes.

126
00:05:14,391 --> 00:05:16,761
[Throws on clothes and heads to work]

127
00:05:16,761 --> 00:05:17,895
- Hold on.
- Really?

128
00:05:17,895 --> 00:05:20,030
Sung Jun's legs are short, so...

129
00:05:20,030 --> 00:05:23,968
- The seniors who got there first...
- His limbs are short, so he's got to run fast.

130
00:05:23,968 --> 00:05:26,804
No way... you've got some nerve too.

131
00:05:26,804 --> 00:05:28,105
[About a ten-minute walk, fairly close]

132
00:05:28,105 --> 00:05:29,873
Such a Gen Z move.

133
00:05:30,674 --> 00:05:33,706
[Dusk falls over Naples as Kwon rushes in]

134
00:05:35,079 --> 00:05:36,747
[But...]

135
00:05:36,747 --> 00:05:38,549
Where are you going?

136
00:05:38,549 --> 00:05:41,452
[Setting up the stoves]
The seniors got there first.

137
00:05:41,452 --> 00:05:42,486
[Current time 6:20 PM]

138
00:05:42,486 --> 00:05:44,221
[He's not late, though]

139
00:05:44,221 --> 00:05:45,990
Ten minutes before the shift.
He's the last one in.

140
00:05:45,990 --> 00:05:47,792
Ten minutes before.

141
00:05:47,792 --> 00:05:49,693
- Hello.
- Hey, good evening.

142
00:05:49,693 --> 00:05:50,828
Hello.

143
00:05:50,828 --> 00:05:53,364
- Who's the newcomer?
- The new chef.

144
00:05:53,364 --> 00:05:54,498
[He makes it to the kitchen, safe]

145
00:05:54,498 --> 00:05:56,267
Is he the last one in right now?

146
00:05:56,267 --> 00:05:59,537
- Why did I come in that early?
- The rookie's the last one in right now.

147
00:05:59,537 --> 00:06:02,206
- He's different.
- That'd be really awkward...

148
00:06:02,206 --> 00:06:04,809
But they told me to come by 6:30,
so I showed up at 6:30.

149
00:06:04,809 --> 00:06:06,544
I've never seen this before.

150
00:06:06,544 --> 00:06:07,878
[Sung Jun, you really are something]

151
00:06:07,878 --> 00:06:09,713
- That's MZ for you.
- That's MZ.

152
00:06:09,713 --> 00:06:11,882
- Totally different.
- This is tough.

153
00:06:11,882 --> 00:06:15,653
[Looks around]

154
00:06:15,653 --> 00:06:16,887
[Freezes]

155
00:06:16,887 --> 00:06:18,290
My bandana...

156
00:06:20,090 --> 00:06:22,126
[Bandana lost?]
Where did the hat go?

157
00:06:22,126 --> 00:06:23,994
I took the hat off and left it here.

158
00:06:23,994 --> 00:06:25,796
[He's got to work fast, but no bandana...]

159
00:06:25,796 --> 00:06:27,531
You didn't take it home, did you?

160
00:06:27,531 --> 00:06:28,866
No.

161
00:06:28,866 --> 00:06:31,435
[The missing bandana]

162
00:06:31,435 --> 00:06:33,204
[Subs in another hat for now]

163
00:06:33,204 --> 00:06:36,406
[A bit of a letdown, but...]

164
00:06:36,406 --> 00:06:37,875
[Prep for dinner service begins]
Let's start.

165
00:06:37,875 --> 00:06:39,243
- Two starters.
- Okay.

166
00:06:39,243 --> 00:06:43,013
[Antipasto prep again for dinner]

167
00:06:43,013 --> 00:06:47,051
[The rookie feeling rushed for no reason]

168
00:06:47,051 --> 00:06:49,453
[And someone else in a hurry?]
Yeah, Paolo.

169
00:06:49,453 --> 00:06:50,821
What are we eating tonight?

170
00:06:50,821 --> 00:06:53,257
Roasted chicken.

171
00:06:53,257 --> 00:06:54,558
[Senior Paolo is making the staff dinner]

172
00:06:54,558 --> 00:06:55,559
- Chicken?
- Yeah.

173
00:06:55,559 --> 00:07:00,331
[Italian eating habits]
Carbs during the day, protein for dinner.

174
00:07:00,331 --> 00:07:03,267
[Flour-coated, protein-rich chicken]

175
00:07:03,267 --> 00:07:05,369
[Lemon and wine]

176
00:07:05,369 --> 00:07:08,072
[Two flavors done in a flash]
Chicken with lemon sauce.

177
00:07:08,072 --> 00:07:09,773
It's a common dinner dish here.

178
00:07:09,773 --> 00:07:11,975
- Kwon.
- Yes?

179
00:07:12,776 --> 00:07:15,546
The roasted chicken comes in lemon or wine.

180
00:07:15,546 --> 00:07:17,882
Which one do you want?

181
00:07:17,882 --> 00:07:19,950
Me? I'll go with lemon.

182
00:07:19,950 --> 00:07:21,118
- Lemon?
- Yes.

183
00:07:21,118 --> 00:07:23,087
[Lemon order received]
Okay.

184
00:07:23,087 --> 00:07:25,122
[Looks delicious]
Let's bring these to Antonio.

185
00:07:25,122 --> 00:07:29,426
Kwon! We always eat dinner standing up.

186
00:07:29,426 --> 00:07:31,528
Standing up?

187
00:07:31,528 --> 00:07:32,930
[Less time than at lunch]
You eat standing up?

188
00:07:32,930 --> 00:07:35,933
[Eat and prep all within an hour!]
Cooks usually eat dinner standing.

189
00:07:35,933 --> 00:07:37,034
Just quick and simple.

190
00:07:37,034 --> 00:07:39,803
[Kwon eats standing too, like the rest]

191
00:07:39,803 --> 00:07:42,072
[Big first bite of the chicken]

192
00:07:42,072 --> 00:07:44,208
[Then a taste of the salad]

193
00:07:44,875 --> 00:07:46,644
[Picks up the bowl and digs in]
It's chicken breast and salad.

194
00:07:46,644 --> 00:07:49,213
- Right.
- You'd lose weight eating like this.

195
00:07:49,213 --> 00:07:52,148
[Standing feast]
Looks like I got some good sleep.

196
00:07:52,764 --> 00:07:53,851
I look refreshed, right?

197
00:07:53,851 --> 00:07:55,386
[The nap brought his appetite back]

198
00:07:55,386 --> 00:07:56,976
I'd say so.

199
00:07:59,223 --> 00:08:01,125
[Staring]

200
00:08:01,125 --> 00:08:03,693
Why is he staring?

201
00:08:04,395 --> 00:08:05,896
[Because he's eating impressively well?]

202
00:08:05,896 --> 00:08:07,264
I have a massive appetite.

203
00:08:07,264 --> 00:08:08,565
[Intense gaze]

204
00:08:08,565 --> 00:08:11,267
Why does he keep staring like that?

205
00:08:12,202 --> 00:08:16,373
He's curious
if I like eating the food he makes.

206
00:08:16,373 --> 00:08:18,042
Kwon, is it good?

207
00:08:18,909 --> 00:08:20,577
[Good?]

208
00:08:20,577 --> 00:08:22,345
It's really good.

209
00:08:22,980 --> 00:08:24,848
[Pleased]

210
00:08:24,848 --> 00:08:26,617
Look how happy he is.

211
00:08:26,617 --> 00:08:29,153
You're supposed to say
it's good before he has to ask.

212
00:08:29,153 --> 00:08:30,554
- You should normally say it's good.
- That's how it goes.

213
00:08:30,554 --> 00:08:31,689
He kept staring
because Kwon didn't say anything.

214
00:08:31,689 --> 00:08:33,991
[Right]
He just cooked it for him,

215
00:08:33,991 --> 00:08:36,527
[The writer and amateur chef getting fired up]
so normally you'd give him a reaction.

216
00:08:36,527 --> 00:08:39,296
You're a chef, so how do you not get that?

217
00:08:39,296 --> 00:08:41,492
[Lesson from the writer]
I'm learning something new.

218
00:08:43,467 --> 00:08:45,301
[Chomp]
It was delicious.

219
00:08:46,103 --> 00:08:50,074
[While his cheeks are stuffed full]

220
00:08:50,074 --> 00:08:51,141
[Senior An takes the seat next to him]

221
00:08:51,141 --> 00:08:53,344
[Bringing him water]
Thank you.

222
00:08:53,344 --> 00:08:57,398
[Dinner round two, side by side]

223
00:08:57,398 --> 00:09:00,668
[Their first face-to-face since lunch service]

224
00:09:03,220 --> 00:09:06,757
[Just eating in silence...]

225
00:09:06,757 --> 00:09:07,858
[Glance]

226
00:09:07,858 --> 00:09:09,393
So awkward.

227
00:09:09,393 --> 00:09:11,228
[Glance]
[Just a mound of rice]

228
00:09:11,228 --> 00:09:13,897
- Just rice?
- There's chicken too.

229
00:09:13,897 --> 00:09:17,801
[Conversation over]

230
00:09:17,801 --> 00:09:20,571
- That's awkward.
- Look at his face!

231
00:09:20,571 --> 00:09:21,572
[Blank face]

232
00:09:21,572 --> 00:09:23,907
So awkward.

233
00:09:23,907 --> 00:09:26,377
[Hmph]

234
00:09:26,377 --> 00:09:28,712
You said people from Naples loved small talk!

235
00:09:28,712 --> 00:09:30,547
- I'm trying right now.
- So you're doing it now?

236
00:09:30,547 --> 00:09:31,915
- I'm trying here.
- You're just starting?

237
00:09:31,915 --> 00:09:33,117
I'm working on it.

238
00:09:33,117 --> 00:09:37,254
[Silence falls again...]

239
00:09:37,254 --> 00:09:39,289
You like soccer?

240
00:09:40,274 --> 00:09:41,319
[Second attempt at conversation]

241
00:09:41,319 --> 00:09:42,726
A little.

242
00:09:42,726 --> 00:09:44,228
Do you like it too?

243
00:09:44,228 --> 00:09:46,030
[Staying undercover]
I used to play baseball, remember?

244
00:09:46,030 --> 00:09:47,831
- Baseball player?
- Yeah.

245
00:09:48,799 --> 00:09:49,800
The American one, right?

246
00:09:49,800 --> 00:09:52,436
[Right, Kwon was a baseball player...]
What?

247
00:09:52,436 --> 00:09:55,773
[Finally the conversation is taking off]

248
00:09:55,773 --> 00:09:58,942
[Don't know baseball]
What soccer team do you root for?

249
00:09:58,942 --> 00:10:01,045
Soccer, obviously, since this is Italy.

250
00:10:01,045 --> 00:10:02,679
Team Napoli.

251
00:10:02,679 --> 00:10:04,982
[Slightly excited]
[Pivots to soccer]

252
00:10:04,982 --> 00:10:08,318
- He likes the Napoli FC.
- You know that Korean guy?

253
00:10:08,318 --> 00:10:09,720
- Kim Min Jae.
- Yes.

254
00:10:09,720 --> 00:10:12,256
[Proud]
Kim Min Jae. He knew right away.

255
00:10:12,256 --> 00:10:15,092
[Silence the second the words leave his mouth]

256
00:10:15,092 --> 00:10:16,627
[Dinner and conversation over]

257
00:10:16,627 --> 00:10:18,529
Awkwardness. End.

258
00:10:18,529 --> 00:10:21,165
- That really is small talk.
- Listen, it's day one. Day one!

259
00:10:21,165 --> 00:10:22,366
- Day one.
- They probably hold back

260
00:10:22,366 --> 00:10:24,101
- so it doesn't turn into big talk.
- Day one.

261
00:10:24,101 --> 00:10:26,837
He started talking about soccer
but worries it'll become big talk.

262
00:10:28,305 --> 00:10:30,073
[Right on cue!]
- Hey, good evening. - Good evening.

263
00:10:30,707 --> 00:10:32,776
[The owner sisters arrive at work, too]
From underneath.

264
00:10:34,311 --> 00:10:36,413
Take this to the back, please.

265
00:10:36,413 --> 00:10:38,549
Okay.

266
00:10:38,549 --> 00:10:42,019
- Bring it here so you can fill it up.
- Okay.

267
00:10:42,019 --> 00:10:43,754
Finally, day one dinner service!

268
00:10:43,754 --> 00:10:45,022
It's still day one.

269
00:10:45,022 --> 00:10:48,092
[The kitchen buzzes with dinner prep]

270
00:10:48,092 --> 00:10:52,196
[For dinner too,
he's on appetizers and desserts]

271
00:10:52,196 --> 00:10:54,932
[The dizzying first run between the two]
- Are you closing from the top? - Yes.

272
00:10:54,932 --> 00:10:58,869
[The antipasto platter
with way too much to memorize]

273
00:10:58,869 --> 00:11:01,572
- Tomato sauce goes on the meatballs, right?
- Okay.

274
00:11:01,572 --> 00:11:05,209
- Some grease comes out as they bake.
- Okay.

275
00:11:05,209 --> 00:11:07,244
Rice on artichokes.

276
00:11:07,244 --> 00:11:08,879
[Senior An's mind-numbing nitpicks
all at once...]

277
00:11:08,879 --> 00:11:12,783
[Kwon and An, how will dinner go?]
A cheese and salami platter.

278
00:11:12,783 --> 00:11:16,053
[Current time: 8:00 PM]

279
00:11:16,053 --> 00:11:21,610
[Customers start pouring in at eight]

280
00:11:22,926 --> 00:11:24,094
[After the first order]

281
00:11:24,094 --> 00:11:26,630
[The second order arrives]

282
00:11:26,630 --> 00:11:30,801
After the antipasti, two half-portions of pasta
with potatoes. Genovese style.

283
00:11:30,801 --> 00:11:32,736
[Kwon checks the ticket sharply]

284
00:11:32,736 --> 00:11:35,172
It's finally my time to shine.

285
00:11:35,172 --> 00:11:39,176
[Inching closer]
[Nagging starts up?]

286
00:11:39,176 --> 00:11:42,027
[Grabs a spoon]
[Suddenly]

287
00:11:44,715 --> 00:11:46,083
[Startled]

288
00:11:46,083 --> 00:11:48,185
He just went and...

289
00:11:48,185 --> 00:11:51,054
[Tastes it without Senior An on his own?]

290
00:11:51,054 --> 00:11:53,891
[Salts it without Senior An's say-so]

291
00:11:53,891 --> 00:11:55,159
- Hold up.
- What's wrong?

292
00:11:55,159 --> 00:11:56,293
Why on earth?

293
00:11:56,293 --> 00:11:58,395
- A rookie shouldn't be doing that.
- It's literally day one.

294
00:11:58,395 --> 00:11:59,963
[Cover at risk]
The rookie pulling that move...

295
00:11:59,963 --> 00:12:03,600
- Why on earth?
- Hey, stick to the concept here.

296
00:12:03,600 --> 00:12:05,869
It's just... Senior An looks...

297
00:12:05,869 --> 00:12:07,237
- a little thrown by it, right?
- Why?

298
00:12:07,237 --> 00:12:08,705
The senior is just standing there,

299
00:12:08,705 --> 00:12:11,575
- and the rookie...
- It's obvious.

300
00:12:11,575 --> 00:12:13,043
What does undercover mean?

301
00:12:13,043 --> 00:12:14,845
- I kind of...
- It means stay under cover.

302
00:12:14,845 --> 00:12:16,780
I took a different approach than the other two.

303
00:12:16,780 --> 00:12:17,848
What was it?

304
00:12:17,848 --> 00:12:20,350
I worked at an Italian place for a year or two.

305
00:12:20,350 --> 00:12:22,853
That was the concept, because honestly
it would be too obvious otherwise.

306
00:12:22,853 --> 00:12:23,987
Sung Jun came prepared.

307
00:12:23,987 --> 00:12:26,390
Pretending I've never done this
would be pushing it.

308
00:12:26,390 --> 00:12:30,494
[Even Senior An is taken aback]

309
00:12:30,494 --> 00:12:34,298
[He checks the seasoning]

310
00:12:34,298 --> 00:12:36,333
The seasoning is spot on.

311
00:12:36,333 --> 00:12:37,868
I'm a master at it.

312
00:12:37,868 --> 00:12:40,270
[True to his rep, salt is perfect]
Sung Jun nails the seasoning every time.

313
00:12:40,270 --> 00:12:42,005
I've got the gift.

314
00:12:42,839 --> 00:12:45,008
[Senior An's lead] [Lunch]
A turn of oil.

315
00:12:45,008 --> 00:12:47,644
[Kwon's lead] [Dinner]
Okay.

316
00:12:47,644 --> 00:12:48,679
[Kwon takes the lead?]

317
00:12:48,679 --> 00:12:50,781
[Already in the back]

318
00:12:50,781 --> 00:12:52,916
- Table two.
- Thank you.

319
00:12:52,916 --> 00:12:54,117
[Cool, but...]
Please.

320
00:12:54,117 --> 00:12:57,454
What? He sleeps and wakes up, and now this?

321
00:12:57,454 --> 00:13:00,123
[Our Kwon, who slept so deeply...]
I was just sleep-deprived.

322
00:13:00,123 --> 00:13:03,927
[Recalling Senior An's words]
Don't walk through empty-handed.

323
00:13:05,462 --> 00:13:06,730
He'd love this too.

324
00:13:06,730 --> 00:13:08,966
[Grabs plates while dumping trash]

325
00:13:08,966 --> 00:13:11,634
[Out of nowhere]
"Our Kwon is a new man."

326
00:13:12,469 --> 00:13:15,647
[Why the sudden change?]
- What's with the switch? - What's the reason?

327
00:13:17,808 --> 00:13:20,877
[The result of hard work!]

328
00:13:20,877 --> 00:13:24,281
[After the brutal lunch shift, back home]

329
00:13:24,281 --> 00:13:26,717
[He didn't head straight to bed]

330
00:13:26,717 --> 00:13:29,294
[Settles onto the couch]

331
00:13:30,654 --> 00:13:32,990
[Muttering and memorizing...]

332
00:13:32,990 --> 00:13:34,024
What is it?

333
00:13:34,024 --> 00:13:37,127
[Drilling the notebook he carries]

334
00:13:37,127 --> 00:13:38,395
You studied?

335
00:13:38,395 --> 00:13:39,796
I studied.

336
00:13:39,796 --> 00:13:41,598
[Of course he did]

337
00:13:41,598 --> 00:13:43,767
I wrote everything that I couldn't forget
in the notebook,

338
00:13:43,767 --> 00:13:45,636
[Sam Kwon / Studying was easy]
then went over it at home.

339
00:13:45,636 --> 00:13:47,638
During my break.

340
00:13:47,638 --> 00:13:49,373
[Stifled laugh]

341
00:13:49,373 --> 00:13:52,209
- I look beat too.
- He's wiped.

342
00:13:52,209 --> 00:13:55,412
[Puffy]
His face is super puffy.

343
00:13:55,412 --> 00:13:57,914
[Proud but bittersweet]

344
00:13:57,914 --> 00:14:01,318
[Recalling Senior An's drills, memorizing on]

345
00:14:01,318 --> 00:14:02,352
He has to do it.

346
00:14:02,352 --> 00:14:05,811
[So his nap was only 30 minutes...]

347
00:14:07,024 --> 00:14:09,092
[Fully prepped for service two]

348
00:14:09,092 --> 00:14:10,327
Okay.

349
00:14:10,327 --> 00:14:12,629
Antipasto platter for two ready?

350
00:14:12,629 --> 00:14:14,564
Two? Okay.

351
00:14:14,564 --> 00:14:15,699
Here we go.

352
00:14:15,699 --> 00:14:17,234
[Time to get into the antipasto]

353
00:14:17,234 --> 00:14:21,238
[Starts plating on his own]

354
00:14:21,238 --> 00:14:22,339
[Rice cake, potato cake]

355
00:14:22,339 --> 00:14:24,308
Rice cake.

356
00:14:24,308 --> 00:14:25,409
Potato cake.

357
00:14:25,409 --> 00:14:27,311
[Remembered every detail!]

358
00:14:27,311 --> 00:14:29,346
[Glance]

359
00:14:29,346 --> 00:14:32,916
[Meatballs too!]

360
00:14:32,916 --> 00:14:34,651
He wrote it all down.

361
00:14:34,651 --> 00:14:36,953
[Plenty of sauce on it]
I wrote it all down.

362
00:14:36,953 --> 00:14:37,988
That's right.

363
00:14:37,988 --> 00:14:39,890
[Cheese on the rice and potato cakes]

364
00:14:39,890 --> 00:14:43,193
[Not bad!]

365
00:14:43,193 --> 00:14:44,494
A satisfied look.

366
00:14:44,494 --> 00:14:47,364
[Strict on oven timing]

367
00:14:47,364 --> 00:14:50,834
[Cruising through without Senior An!]

368
00:14:50,834 --> 00:14:52,495
[Side glance]

369
00:14:53,428 --> 00:14:56,940
[While Kwon plows through in the zone]

370
00:14:56,940 --> 00:14:59,843
[Not just Antonio]

371
00:14:59,843 --> 00:15:01,178
[Onlooker 1] [Onlooker 2] [Onlooker 3]

372
00:15:01,178 --> 00:15:03,180
- Everyone...
- Why is everyone staring?

373
00:15:03,180 --> 00:15:04,481
- They were all watching.
- That's a lot of pressure.

374
00:15:04,481 --> 00:15:06,683
[All eyes on the new rookie]
Did you know? That they were watching?

375
00:15:06,683 --> 00:15:07,751
I don't think I noticed.

376
00:15:07,751 --> 00:15:10,053
[Missing the buzz, he nails cold beef rolls]
You don't think you noticed?

377
00:15:10,053 --> 00:15:11,388
[How to not forget?]
Don't forget.

378
00:15:11,388 --> 00:15:13,590
[Fried polenta (don't forget)]
Three stars.

379
00:15:13,590 --> 00:15:14,925
[Cute]

380
00:15:14,925 --> 00:15:18,228
If you miss the timing on fried food,
it's ruined.

381
00:15:18,228 --> 00:15:22,299
[Pulling it from memory, smooth]

382
00:15:22,299 --> 00:15:24,368
[Still under hawk eyes now and then]

383
00:15:24,368 --> 00:15:28,038
[Kwon's plating was too crowded at lunch]
- Move it there. - Okay.

384
00:15:28,038 --> 00:15:31,208
[Now every dish is well-spaced]

385
00:15:31,208 --> 00:15:33,176
[Space keeps look and taste intact]
Right, if it's all crammed together,

386
00:15:33,176 --> 00:15:35,512
[Lunch / Dinner (now)]
the flavors can blur, sauces and all.

387
00:15:35,512 --> 00:15:38,048
[Proud of Kwon]
Everyone looks happy.

388
00:15:38,048 --> 00:15:39,449
Which table is it going to?

389
00:15:39,449 --> 00:15:41,518
[He even passes the table number!]
Nine.

390
00:15:41,518 --> 00:15:43,186
- Clean work.
- Here.

391
00:15:43,186 --> 00:15:44,722
[Pass and move, ticket toss is perfect!]

392
00:15:48,125 --> 00:15:50,569
[Slides in]

393
00:15:52,763 --> 00:15:56,233
Seriously. He's watching him with sharp eyes.

394
00:15:56,233 --> 00:15:57,968
[Hawk eyes, but keeping quiet this time]

395
00:15:57,968 --> 00:16:01,638
Kwon moves really fast,

396
00:16:01,638 --> 00:16:04,908
and he cleans up neatly.

397
00:16:04,908 --> 00:16:07,744
So far, he's looking great.

398
00:16:07,744 --> 00:16:09,246
That's Antonio for me.

399
00:16:09,246 --> 00:16:11,982
You have to do the job well
before you can sell yourself.

400
00:16:11,982 --> 00:16:15,627
I'll focus on mastering my station first.

401
00:16:15,627 --> 00:16:18,121
[Chomp]
And tomorrow

402
00:16:18,121 --> 00:16:19,956
I'm thinking of trying the staff meal.

403
00:16:19,956 --> 00:16:22,559
[Brimming with confidence]

404
00:16:22,559 --> 00:16:24,127
- While he's eating?
- Pizza.

405
00:16:24,127 --> 00:16:25,562
- He eats a lot.
- Pizza?

406
00:16:25,562 --> 00:16:27,798
[Appetite matches confidence]
Pizza.

407
00:16:28,850 --> 00:16:30,676
Do the job first, then move on to other stuff.

408
00:16:30,676 --> 00:16:32,566
[Kwon believes chances follow good work]

409
00:16:33,203 --> 00:16:34,838
[Plowing through antipasto without a break]

410
00:16:34,838 --> 00:16:36,873
You have to do the job first.

411
00:16:36,873 --> 00:16:41,178
[Handling the order rush smoothly]

412
00:16:41,178 --> 00:16:43,747
[A little drained]

413
00:16:43,747 --> 00:16:46,415
[Glance]
It's normal.

414
00:16:48,185 --> 00:16:51,288
[Luisa, the owner, stares at Kwon]

415
00:16:51,288 --> 00:16:54,925
[Looks deep in thought]

416
00:16:54,925 --> 00:16:57,494
[Glance]

417
00:16:57,494 --> 00:17:00,430
[Another glance]

418
00:17:00,430 --> 00:17:04,134
[What's she thinking about him?]

419
00:17:04,134 --> 00:17:06,536
[Pondering]

420
00:17:06,536 --> 00:17:07,604
Kwon!

421
00:17:07,604 --> 00:17:09,406
Kwon!

422
00:17:09,406 --> 00:17:11,875
Want to try the potato pasta?

423
00:17:11,875 --> 00:17:14,911
Want to try the potato pasta?

424
00:17:14,911 --> 00:17:16,746
[Pasta already?]

425
00:17:16,746 --> 00:17:18,608
Out of nowhere?

426
00:17:18,608 --> 00:17:22,319
Kwon did pretty well.

427
00:17:22,319 --> 00:17:26,323
It felt like he already knew

428
00:17:26,323 --> 00:17:30,660
what he was supposed to do.

429
00:17:30,660 --> 00:17:34,798
- He didn't seem like a beginner at all.
- Right. He's not green.

430
00:17:34,798 --> 00:17:38,869
[Luisa's note 1. Wipes and clears tables fast]
I said he had to clean his station.

431
00:17:38,869 --> 00:17:40,604
[A rookie who knows the basics]

432
00:17:40,604 --> 00:17:42,038
Here.

433
00:17:42,038 --> 00:17:44,207
[Luisa's note 2. Acts on what he learns]
He would look, listen,

434
00:17:44,207 --> 00:17:46,309
he tried to have it done right away.

435
00:17:46,309 --> 00:17:48,345
[The rookie picks things up fast]

436
00:17:48,345 --> 00:17:51,581
[Luisa's note 3. Drive and hunger for the work]
So actually,

437
00:17:51,581 --> 00:17:53,850
he's talented.

438
00:17:53,850 --> 00:17:59,356
That kind of attitude matters in the kitchen.

439
00:17:59,356 --> 00:18:02,459
[A pasta shot after one day?]
Want to try the potato pasta?

440
00:18:02,459 --> 00:18:04,193
Pasta right off the bat?

441
00:18:05,996 --> 00:18:07,631
His face says it all.

442
00:18:07,631 --> 00:18:09,633
[Our Sung Jun was floored by the offer]

443
00:18:09,633 --> 00:18:12,202
I mean, in most kitchens,

444
00:18:12,202 --> 00:18:17,774
handing a main dish
to a rookie like that isn't easy, right?

445
00:18:17,774 --> 00:18:20,076
[Every owner-chef agrees]
- It's not easy. - Not easy.

446
00:18:20,076 --> 00:18:21,077
Right?

447
00:18:21,077 --> 00:18:23,446
- You only get a shot if you're sharp.
- Exactly.

448
00:18:23,446 --> 00:18:27,851
When the owner said try the potato pasta,
how did you feel?

449
00:18:27,851 --> 00:18:31,021
I said I'd wrap this up in three days.

450
00:18:31,021 --> 00:18:33,789
Like, am I going home tomorrow?

451
00:18:34,424 --> 00:18:36,760
The show can't capture all of it,

452
00:18:36,760 --> 00:18:37,761
[Choked up remembering that]

453
00:18:37,761 --> 00:18:39,396
but my feet were a blur out there.

454
00:18:39,396 --> 00:18:42,265
Aren't your legs just too short to see?

455
00:18:42,265 --> 00:18:46,111
I worked so hard my feet were a blur,
so she gave me a fair shake. I appreciate that.

456
00:18:46,111 --> 00:18:47,116
You're grateful.

457
00:18:47,116 --> 00:18:49,120
[Stove in one day?
Can Kwon hit his 3-day mark?]

458
00:18:50,240 --> 00:18:52,542
[Parma, Italy]
A rookie with 27 years of experience.

459
00:18:52,542 --> 00:18:54,177
[Hee Tae, not Sam Kim]
How much of a new side

460
00:18:54,177 --> 00:18:56,379
[Day one undercover, prepping dinner]
will Chef Sam Kim show us?

461
00:18:56,379 --> 00:18:59,648
[Current time: 7:20 PM]

462
00:19:00,617 --> 00:19:04,254
[Hee Tae and the fresh-pasta charmer Sorem]

463
00:19:04,254 --> 00:19:07,300
[Senior Lu is helping with the staff meal]

464
00:19:08,191 --> 00:19:09,859
[Tonight's menu?]
[Arancini, fried rice ball] [Roast chicken]

465
00:19:09,859 --> 00:19:13,530
[Roast chicken]
The staff dinner is pretty solid here.

466
00:19:13,530 --> 00:19:15,966
[A big arancini fills them up before service]
All of it tasted great.

467
00:19:15,966 --> 00:19:19,069
So they have arancini for the staff meal.

468
00:19:19,069 --> 00:19:21,371
I've never seen arancini for staff meal before.

469
00:19:21,371 --> 00:19:22,639
- Really?
- Yeah.

470
00:19:22,639 --> 00:19:24,174
- It takes a lot of work.
- A lot of work...

471
00:19:24,174 --> 00:19:26,112
- That's something special.
- Right.

472
00:19:26,777 --> 00:19:29,989
[Takes off the hat before digging in]
He's taking the hat off.

473
00:19:30,814 --> 00:19:33,750
[Tries the carefully made arancini first]

474
00:19:33,750 --> 00:19:35,516
[Eyebrows up]

475
00:19:37,153 --> 00:19:40,423
Is this your first time at an Italian place?

476
00:19:40,423 --> 00:19:41,491
First time.

477
00:19:41,491 --> 00:19:42,826
[Boss's surprise question]
First time?

478
00:19:42,826 --> 00:19:44,361
Here come the questions.

479
00:19:44,361 --> 00:19:46,162
He has to sell it.

480
00:19:46,162 --> 00:19:47,597
First time working at an Italian place?

481
00:19:47,597 --> 00:19:49,531
- To work?
- Yes.

482
00:19:50,233 --> 00:19:51,868
Do you like Italy?

483
00:19:51,868 --> 00:19:53,570
- Do you like Italy?
- Yes, I love it!

484
00:19:53,570 --> 00:19:54,971
And the Italian people?

485
00:19:54,971 --> 00:19:56,673
The Italian people?

486
00:19:56,673 --> 00:19:57,841
"Italian people."

487
00:19:57,841 --> 00:19:59,242
[Tch...]

488
00:19:59,242 --> 00:20:01,777
I love Italy too, but Italians...

489
00:20:04,714 --> 00:20:06,916
It's a whole other story.

490
00:20:08,051 --> 00:20:10,420
[Suddenly]
Hello, this is Pla*ni.

491
00:20:10,420 --> 00:20:12,555
- What?
- Out of nowhere?

492
00:20:12,555 --> 00:20:14,457
- What?
- Out of nowhere?

493
00:20:14,457 --> 00:20:16,826
- He's on the phone?
- In the middle of dinner.

494
00:20:16,826 --> 00:20:17,961
That guy is a true...

495
00:20:17,961 --> 00:20:19,205
He's professional.

496
00:20:19,205 --> 00:20:20,932
He just picked up.

497
00:20:25,101 --> 00:20:27,871
[Amazing]

498
00:20:27,871 --> 00:20:32,042
[After the tough dinner with the boss]

499
00:20:32,042 --> 00:20:35,545
[30 minutes to service, Hee Tae's in first]

500
00:20:35,545 --> 00:20:38,548
[Rookie bread hat back on]
That hat actually suits him.

501
00:20:38,548 --> 00:20:40,349
- It looks good.
- Yeah.

502
00:20:41,551 --> 00:20:45,055
[Then No.4 Sorem walks in]

503
00:20:45,055 --> 00:20:48,124
[Naturally settles at the fresh-pasta station]

504
00:20:48,124 --> 00:20:49,926
What should you do? Wipe stuff down, I guess.

505
00:20:49,926 --> 00:20:52,455
[Pointless wiping...]

506
00:20:54,397 --> 00:20:59,202
[Staring hard...]

507
00:20:59,202 --> 00:21:02,861
[His goal: get back to the pasta station]

508
00:21:03,606 --> 00:21:05,208
- He shaped the pasta wrong.
- Sorry.

509
00:21:05,208 --> 00:21:07,149
[Fallout from the pasta-trashing disaster]
- Right. - Yeah.

510
00:21:07,811 --> 00:21:11,948
[Hard to step back into the pasta zone]

511
00:21:11,948 --> 00:21:13,950
Is your spot here today?

512
00:21:13,950 --> 00:21:15,651
Yes.

513
00:21:16,262 --> 00:21:19,914
[No.3 Senior Lu is off doing urgent prep]

514
00:21:21,039 --> 00:21:23,993
[No.4 Sorem runs pasta tonight]
So he's working with Sorem.

515
00:21:23,993 --> 00:21:26,129
We're making tortelli.

516
00:21:26,129 --> 00:21:27,330
Got it.

517
00:21:27,330 --> 00:21:30,366
[So what do I do?]

518
00:21:30,366 --> 00:21:33,203
[Hmm...]

519
00:21:33,203 --> 00:21:36,473
Let Hee Tae make the tortelli.
Don't do it all yourself.

520
00:21:36,473 --> 00:21:39,209
- Yes, understood.
- Did he do it?

521
00:21:39,209 --> 00:21:41,845
[I get to make dinner tortelli?]
Make him try.

522
00:21:41,845 --> 00:21:43,146
He can do a couple of dishes.

523
00:21:43,146 --> 00:21:46,149
[No.1 head chef gives him another shot]
They give a lot of chances.

524
00:21:46,149 --> 00:21:47,917
[Why give him another shot
after the lunch slip?]

525
00:21:47,917 --> 00:21:52,689
His hands are skilled,
and he works the dough well.

526
00:21:52,689 --> 00:21:56,726
His movements have no hesitation.

527
00:21:56,726 --> 00:21:59,062
He's pretty intuitive

528
00:21:59,062 --> 00:22:03,166
[Hee Tae's good]
and knows what needs doing.

529
00:22:03,166 --> 00:22:04,734
[Even after the slip, he handled his job]
How to handle the dough

530
00:22:04,734 --> 00:22:06,436
- in the right way.
- Perfect.

531
00:22:06,436 --> 00:22:07,504
Now, put it here...

532
00:22:07,504 --> 00:22:09,506
- He picks things up fast.
- Right.

533
00:22:09,506 --> 00:22:11,608
[Hee Tae's potential confirmed]

534
00:22:11,608 --> 00:22:12,809
[Sorem steps aside without a fuss]

535
00:22:12,809 --> 00:22:14,043
- Shall I try?
- Yes.

536
00:22:14,043 --> 00:22:15,278
Okay.

537
00:22:15,278 --> 00:22:16,446
[Back at the fresh-pasta station]

538
00:22:16,446 --> 00:22:19,115
- He'll do well, right?
- He'll do fine.

539
00:22:19,115 --> 00:22:21,317
Besides, he's got it all in his head now.

540
00:22:21,317 --> 00:22:25,555
[Skipped his break to drill pasta recipes]
He's done fresh pasta for like 20, 30 years.

541
00:22:25,555 --> 00:22:30,059
[Tortelli, agnolotti, tagliatelle,
all different]

542
00:22:30,059 --> 00:22:31,261
It's not easy.

543
00:22:31,261 --> 00:22:33,096
[Parma's fresh pasta and fried bread]

544
00:22:33,096 --> 00:22:34,464
That was...

545
00:22:34,464 --> 00:22:36,733
[He has to recall everything Senior Lu taught]

546
00:22:36,733 --> 00:22:40,003
[Back to the real thing!]

547
00:22:40,003 --> 00:22:41,037
[First up: potato tortelli]
Potato.

548
00:22:41,037 --> 00:22:43,038
Got it.

549
00:22:43,850 --> 00:22:45,617
I'll try.

550
00:22:47,177 --> 00:22:49,145
[So the trashed-batch nightmare doesn't repeat]

551
00:22:49,145 --> 00:22:50,847
Sorry.

552
00:22:50,847 --> 00:22:55,318
Trusting a guy with fresh pasta
on day one isn't easy.

553
00:22:55,318 --> 00:22:59,388
Even I was thinking,
am I supposed to be doing this?

554
00:23:00,590 --> 00:23:02,858
- Yeah...
- Huh?

555
00:23:04,661 --> 00:23:06,529
[The dough clumped up]
Huh? Hold on.

556
00:23:06,529 --> 00:23:09,098
- Huh?
- Wait a sec.

557
00:23:09,098 --> 00:23:10,967
[A mistake right off the bat]
Why is it sticking together?

558
00:23:10,967 --> 00:23:12,035
Again?

559
00:23:12,035 --> 00:23:13,703
[Quick fix]

560
00:23:13,703 --> 00:23:16,972
If Lu comes back,
is she going to toss it again?

561
00:23:17,740 --> 00:23:19,926
- It was wetter than I expected,
- Too wet?

562
00:23:19,926 --> 00:23:24,080
and it was sitting out
at room temperature too long.

563
00:23:24,080 --> 00:23:25,849
So the dough was off?

564
00:23:25,849 --> 00:23:28,512
The dough was a little too wet.

565
00:23:29,586 --> 00:23:32,021
[Reading the room]

566
00:23:32,021 --> 00:23:35,758
[Luckily no one saw it]

567
00:23:35,758 --> 00:23:36,860
[Folds it as if nothing happened]

568
00:23:36,860 --> 00:23:39,057
[Nervous]

569
00:23:39,863 --> 00:23:43,766
[Quietly revives the dough]

570
00:23:43,766 --> 00:23:46,936
[Refocuses]

571
00:23:46,936 --> 00:23:51,341
[About to pipe the potato filling]

572
00:23:51,341 --> 00:23:53,576
[Glance]

573
00:23:53,576 --> 00:23:55,291
- Hee Tae!
- Yeah.

574
00:23:55,291 --> 00:23:57,113
[Straighten your back]
Okay.

575
00:23:57,113 --> 00:23:59,015
- I'm watching everything!
- Okay.

576
00:23:59,015 --> 00:24:00,950
- Stand up straight.
- He's saying straighten up.

577
00:24:01,651 --> 00:24:05,149
[But the dough isn't the only problem]

578
00:24:07,724 --> 00:24:11,356
[Six-month senior Sorem shoots a sharp look]

579
00:24:12,795 --> 00:24:15,076
[Note 1]
Space them out more, and fill them more!

580
00:24:15,076 --> 00:24:16,799
More?

581
00:24:18,134 --> 00:24:19,869
[More potato]
Yeah.

582
00:24:19,869 --> 00:24:21,504
[More potato]

583
00:24:21,504 --> 00:24:23,005
[More potato]

584
00:24:24,073 --> 00:24:25,241
[More potato]

585
00:24:25,241 --> 00:24:27,242
[Note 2]
More here too!

586
00:24:28,244 --> 00:24:30,146
[More than this?]
More here too!

587
00:24:30,146 --> 00:24:33,349
[More?]

588
00:24:33,349 --> 00:24:35,752
[Looks like plenty already...]
- More. - Okay.

589
00:24:35,752 --> 00:24:37,370
More?

590
00:24:38,821 --> 00:24:41,299
[He just follows his current senior
and adds more]

591
00:24:41,299 --> 00:24:42,926
[Hmm...]

592
00:24:42,926 --> 00:24:45,094
- But Lu taught you that.
- Yes.

593
00:24:45,094 --> 00:24:49,032
But two people are sharing this one station,

594
00:24:49,032 --> 00:24:50,433
so they each do it a little differently.

595
00:24:50,433 --> 00:24:51,334
- All right, let's watch.
- They're different.

596
00:24:51,334 --> 00:24:52,835
- Sorem...
- Their styles are different.

597
00:24:52,835 --> 00:24:54,104
[Who's actually right?]
Yeah.

598
00:24:54,104 --> 00:24:56,372
[Just then]
Sorry, guys.

599
00:24:56,372 --> 00:24:58,941
Can I grab those?

600
00:24:59,642 --> 00:25:01,945
[Hmm...]

601
00:25:01,945 --> 00:25:05,715
Tonight it's king-size tortelli.

602
00:25:05,715 --> 00:25:08,851
[King-size?]
Tonight it's king-size tortelli.

603
00:25:08,851 --> 00:25:12,109
If you boil them like that,
they'll blow up this big.

604
00:25:13,122 --> 00:25:14,891
[Lunch service senior]
Those two have completely different styles.

605
00:25:14,891 --> 00:25:16,826
[Dinner senior (almost giant dumplings)]
- So the styles are different. - I can see.

606
00:25:16,826 --> 00:25:18,560
I can see.

607
00:25:20,196 --> 00:25:23,066
[The 6-month teacher feels awkward]
Sorem has a heavy hand.

608
00:25:23,066 --> 00:25:24,534
[A little confusion, but...]

609
00:25:24,534 --> 00:25:27,899
[Keeps his cool]

610
00:25:28,938 --> 00:25:30,306
All right, fold it in half.

611
00:25:30,306 --> 00:25:34,577
[Giant-dumpling style, but he finishes them]

612
00:25:34,577 --> 00:25:36,212
[Now he's about to dust on some flour]

613
00:25:36,212 --> 00:25:37,714
Just a moment. We don't use flour.

614
00:25:37,714 --> 00:25:38,915
- No flour?
- No.

615
00:25:38,915 --> 00:25:40,984
- Just a moment. We don't use flour.
- No flour?

616
00:25:40,984 --> 00:25:42,852
[Round two of confusion]
No.

617
00:25:42,852 --> 00:25:45,408
Didn't they put flour on it? I think they did.

618
00:25:45,408 --> 00:25:47,690
- The styles are...
- The head chef said to dust it earlier.

619
00:25:47,690 --> 00:25:48,858
You dust it so it doesn't stick.

620
00:25:48,858 --> 00:25:50,626
This is confusing.

621
00:25:50,626 --> 00:25:52,228
What do you do in this case?

622
00:25:52,228 --> 00:25:54,297
Personally, I think dusting is the right call.

623
00:25:54,297 --> 00:25:57,000
- The head chef said to dust it!
- Right.

624
00:25:57,000 --> 00:25:59,736
You always have to dust it with flour.

625
00:25:59,736 --> 00:26:02,805
[At lunch he learned to dust it...]
You take it and pinch it.

626
00:26:02,805 --> 00:26:04,240
Push and pinch.

627
00:26:04,240 --> 00:26:05,641
Just a moment. We don't use flour.

628
00:26:05,641 --> 00:26:06,743
- No flour?
- No.

629
00:26:06,743 --> 00:26:10,913
Because if you do it this way,

630
00:26:10,913 --> 00:26:13,249
[Confusion]
- it won't seal properly. - Okay.

631
00:26:13,249 --> 00:26:14,717
- Okay.
- Okay.

632
00:26:14,717 --> 00:26:16,886
- So...
- Pull the dough tight,

633
00:26:16,886 --> 00:26:19,822
and have him dust plenty of flour on top!

634
00:26:21,424 --> 00:26:23,159
At that very moment...

635
00:26:23,159 --> 00:26:24,861
I told him to dust it later.

636
00:26:24,861 --> 00:26:26,320
[Shakes head]
Otherwise, when you go to seal it...

637
00:26:26,320 --> 00:26:28,231
Right now, don't wait.

638
00:26:28,231 --> 00:26:29,766
Okay, please dust it.

639
00:26:29,766 --> 00:26:32,668
This kind of thing gets
a little embarrassing for Sorem.

640
00:26:32,668 --> 00:26:34,058
Right.

641
00:26:35,138 --> 00:26:38,241
This was really not easy.

642
00:26:38,241 --> 00:26:43,846
Use plenty of flour.

643
00:26:43,846 --> 00:26:45,048
[Dust]

644
00:26:45,048 --> 00:26:47,050
Okay.

645
00:26:47,050 --> 00:26:49,564
The flour sticks while you grab and press.

646
00:26:49,564 --> 00:26:50,920
Keep going.

647
00:26:50,920 --> 00:26:54,557
Or it doesn't make sense,
the pasta stays smooth.

648
00:26:54,557 --> 00:26:56,559
[Sorem, got it?]

649
00:26:56,559 --> 00:27:00,530
[Sharp lesson, warm finish]

650
00:27:00,530 --> 00:27:02,598
[The rookie alone is left confused]

651
00:27:02,598 --> 00:27:05,268
[Poor thing...]

652
00:27:05,268 --> 00:27:07,370
[Hands fight to survive the chaos]

653
00:27:07,370 --> 00:27:10,640
[Full focus]

654
00:27:10,640 --> 00:27:13,376
[Barely seals and cuts without a slip]

655
00:27:13,376 --> 00:27:14,410
[Next step: shaping]

656
00:27:14,410 --> 00:27:17,646
Huh? He has to shape it now.

657
00:27:19,582 --> 00:27:21,717
[Tries to do it the way Lu showed him]
Move it in this way.

658
00:27:22,452 --> 00:27:23,886
[Press]

659
00:27:23,886 --> 00:27:25,254
- Right?
- No.

660
00:27:25,254 --> 00:27:26,922
Like this.

661
00:27:26,922 --> 00:27:29,459
[Now what? Round three of confusion]

662
00:27:29,459 --> 00:27:32,644
- Okay. I'm confused...
- This way.

663
00:27:34,097 --> 00:27:38,267
Grab, twist, and pinch.

664
00:27:38,267 --> 00:27:39,569
- That looks different from before.
- Is Sorem's way right?

665
00:27:39,569 --> 00:27:41,282
Like... what we did at lunch

666
00:27:41,282 --> 00:27:43,238
- is different again.
- It's different?

667
00:27:44,040 --> 00:27:46,709
You should do it like this.

668
00:27:46,709 --> 00:27:49,645
[No.3 senior's way: press both sides]

669
00:27:49,645 --> 00:27:51,714
So... this way.

670
00:27:51,714 --> 00:27:55,918
[No.4 senior's way: twist then pinch]

671
00:27:55,918 --> 00:27:59,722
[Kind of more complicated]

672
00:27:59,722 --> 00:28:01,624
It was a bit confusing.

673
00:28:01,624 --> 00:28:04,427
Who am I supposed to follow on this?

674
00:28:04,427 --> 00:28:08,397
But Lu has more years at this place,

675
00:28:08,397 --> 00:28:13,602
and Sorem's running dinner,
so I have to match him now.

676
00:28:14,570 --> 00:28:16,806
[Senior with more years vs. current boss]
What do you do here?

677
00:28:16,806 --> 00:28:18,708
- What do you do?
- You read the room.

678
00:28:18,708 --> 00:28:20,710
For now, follow whoever's teaching you.

679
00:28:20,710 --> 00:28:23,079
- Go with the one next to you.
- Right.

680
00:28:23,079 --> 00:28:24,080
- That's the move.
- Yeah.

681
00:28:24,080 --> 00:28:25,348
That's correct.

682
00:28:25,348 --> 00:28:28,718
The senior is the one responsible,

683
00:28:28,718 --> 00:28:30,853
so you usually just do what they say.

684
00:28:31,454 --> 00:28:33,322
[After weighing what to do]

685
00:28:33,322 --> 00:28:35,091
[Glance]

686
00:28:37,026 --> 00:28:40,062
[Twists and pinches]

687
00:28:40,062 --> 00:28:43,666
[Ends up copying his current senior]

688
00:28:43,666 --> 00:28:47,703
Then a light dusting of flour,
and set them over there.

689
00:28:47,703 --> 00:28:51,307
[Working the pasta with an unsure look]

690
00:28:51,307 --> 00:28:53,009
[Current time: 8:00 PM]
Good evening.

691
00:28:53,009 --> 00:28:54,177
[Dinner service begins]
At 8 o'clock.

692
00:28:54,177 --> 00:28:56,746
So, the dinner rush starts around 8 PM.

693
00:28:56,746 --> 00:29:00,524
[Customers pour in as soon as they open]

694
00:29:01,984 --> 00:29:03,853
In Korea, by 7 PM,

695
00:29:03,853 --> 00:29:06,756
[Packed with Italians out for a late dinner]
dinner service is in full swing.

696
00:29:06,756 --> 00:29:09,158
Italians usually come at 8 or 8:30.

697
00:29:09,158 --> 00:29:12,128
[I'm hungry, feed me!]

698
00:29:12,128 --> 00:29:14,786
[The boss arrives with the ticket]
Look here if they're done.

699
00:29:16,132 --> 00:29:20,770
[Listen up]
Order: mixed salami, pie, polenta, one egg.

700
00:29:20,770 --> 00:29:22,838
Next, it's easy.

701
00:29:22,838 --> 00:29:25,220
One potato tortelli, one duck tagliatelle.

702
00:29:25,220 --> 00:29:27,676
One agnolotto, one brasato.

703
00:29:28,419 --> 00:29:30,012
Order: one tortelli...

704
00:29:30,012 --> 00:29:31,080
How do you even catch all that?

705
00:29:31,080 --> 00:29:32,515
One salami, one pie,

706
00:29:32,515 --> 00:29:35,051
[Order flood]
then three grilled veggies.

707
00:29:35,051 --> 00:29:38,154
[Tense]

708
00:29:38,154 --> 00:29:40,289
Okay. Now let's make agnolotti.

709
00:29:40,289 --> 00:29:41,557
Agnolotti...

710
00:29:41,557 --> 00:29:42,959
- Have you made them before?
- No.

711
00:29:42,959 --> 00:29:44,281
Okay.

712
00:29:45,428 --> 00:29:49,599
[Didn't I learn this?]
There are new menu items at dinner too.

713
00:29:49,599 --> 00:29:52,735
[Watching Sorem pull out the filling]

714
00:29:52,735 --> 00:29:54,403
[Remembers]
Nine fillings, right?

715
00:29:54,403 --> 00:29:56,405
- Nine?
- Right.

716
00:29:56,405 --> 00:29:57,506
That looks good.

717
00:29:57,506 --> 00:29:59,942
It's pheasant. A pheasant dish.

718
00:29:59,942 --> 00:30:01,043
What's agnolotti?

719
00:30:01,043 --> 00:30:02,845
[Parma's signature stuffed pasta]
A type of stuffed pasta.

720
00:30:02,845 --> 00:30:05,014
It's one of the filled-pasta varieties.

721
00:30:05,014 --> 00:30:08,050
[What Senior Lu showed at lunch]
Pheasant agnolotti.

722
00:30:08,050 --> 00:30:10,274
[Pheasant agnolotti is green pasta]
The same.

723
00:30:11,187 --> 00:30:12,989
- Fagiano.
- Fagiano.

724
00:30:12,989 --> 00:30:15,625
[Fagiano: pheasant]
Is that color just from the pheasant?

725
00:30:15,625 --> 00:30:17,360
- Cook the pheasant and grind it.
- Ground?

726
00:30:17,360 --> 00:30:20,595
- Oh, you grind it cooked?
- You cook it and grind it?

727
00:30:21,564 --> 00:30:24,700
[Place nine dollops of pheasant filling]

728
00:30:24,700 --> 00:30:26,400
[Nine logged]
Nine.

729
00:30:27,203 --> 00:30:30,239
The way you wrap it is the same as tortelli.

730
00:30:30,239 --> 00:30:33,342
[So far, almost the same as tortelli]
Be careful, no air inside.

731
00:30:33,342 --> 00:30:34,543
Exactly.

732
00:30:34,543 --> 00:30:36,445
Okay.

733
00:30:36,445 --> 00:30:37,813
What's different from tortelli?

734
00:30:37,813 --> 00:30:38,848
The shapes are all different.

735
00:30:38,848 --> 00:30:40,249
The name changes with the shape?

736
00:30:40,249 --> 00:30:41,917
On the side.

737
00:30:41,917 --> 00:30:45,488
[Cut round with a round cutter]

738
00:30:45,488 --> 00:30:47,957
[Edges get cut into a round shape]

739
00:30:47,957 --> 00:30:51,494
[Finally, pinch the ends like a dumpling]

740
00:30:51,494 --> 00:30:54,452
[Can Hee Tae nail the agnolotti?]

741
00:30:55,231 --> 00:30:59,268
[Heads back to the pasta station, all smiles]

742
00:30:59,268 --> 00:31:04,006
[Full focus]

743
00:31:04,006 --> 00:31:06,342
[Nine dollops of pheasant filling first]
They do it all live here.

744
00:31:06,342 --> 00:31:08,144
- It's actually nuts.
- I know.

745
00:31:08,144 --> 00:31:10,440
[Hee Tae lays them out fast]
Most places freeze them ahead.

746
00:31:12,014 --> 00:31:16,497
[He picks it up this fast?]

747
00:31:20,122 --> 00:31:23,548
[Today is his first time making it]

748
00:31:24,960 --> 00:31:29,432
[Can't hide that 27-year chef instinct]

749
00:31:29,432 --> 00:31:32,883
[Now he just needs
to cut with the round cutter]

750
00:31:35,004 --> 00:31:37,039
- Huh?
- Wasn't it cut with the round mold?

751
00:31:37,039 --> 00:31:38,607
[Why? What's wrong?]

752
00:31:38,607 --> 00:31:40,009
- Huh?
- What?

753
00:31:40,009 --> 00:31:41,477
- Huh?
- Did you forget?

754
00:31:41,477 --> 00:31:43,045
No, the method's different.

755
00:31:43,045 --> 00:31:44,222
Wait, that's not it.

756
00:31:44,222 --> 00:31:45,281
- Hold on.
- Hang on.

757
00:31:45,281 --> 00:31:46,915
[Oh no]
He messed up.

758
00:31:46,915 --> 00:31:50,074
- He just realized.
- No, wait, I remember now.

759
00:31:51,153 --> 00:31:54,924
[Oh no!]

760
00:31:54,924 --> 00:31:57,093
[Too square]

761
00:31:57,093 --> 00:31:59,328
[What now?]
What does he do?

762
00:31:59,328 --> 00:32:00,963
[The 27-year veteran rookie goes pale]
He's hiding it.

763
00:32:00,963 --> 00:32:02,331
- He hid it.
- Hold on.

764
00:32:02,331 --> 00:32:03,833
- Hidden.
- What does he do?

765
00:32:03,833 --> 00:32:05,589
[Ruined?]

766
00:32:07,570 --> 00:32:10,272
Sorem saw it.

767
00:32:10,272 --> 00:32:12,507
Sorem saw it.

768
00:32:14,810 --> 00:32:15,978
[Sorem's sharp eye catches it right away]
This one, right?

769
00:32:15,978 --> 00:32:17,713
- Busted.
- Yes.

770
00:32:17,713 --> 00:32:18,798
Okay.

771
00:32:18,798 --> 00:32:21,917
[Another batch of pasta in the trash?]

772
00:32:21,917 --> 00:32:25,421
[Sorem takes the ruined dough]

773
00:32:25,421 --> 00:32:28,357
It's fine. Keep going.

774
00:32:28,357 --> 00:32:32,528
[Kind senior?]
But Sorem is helping too.

775
00:32:32,528 --> 00:32:33,877
[Glance]

776
00:32:34,830 --> 00:32:37,299
[Glance]
He's being stealthy about it.

777
00:32:37,299 --> 00:32:39,168
He's looking around.

778
00:32:39,168 --> 00:32:42,371
[Sorem's fix 1: rescue the pheasant filling]

779
00:32:42,371 --> 00:32:45,908
- So like this... Hold on.
- So he cuts another piece,

780
00:32:45,908 --> 00:32:48,811
[Fix 2: wrap the pheasant in the scrap dough]
and brings it back, just like that.

781
00:32:48,811 --> 00:32:50,579
He's made this slip before.

782
00:32:50,579 --> 00:32:52,314
[Fix 3: clean it up with the round mold]

783
00:32:52,314 --> 00:32:54,984
He must have made this mistake
plenty of times himself.

784
00:32:54,984 --> 00:32:57,987
That's why he knows how to wing it.

785
00:32:57,987 --> 00:32:59,855
- Sorem's a sweetheart.
- He really is.

786
00:32:59,855 --> 00:33:01,590
- They're all sweet, all of them.
- So sweet.

787
00:33:01,590 --> 00:33:03,259
[Sorem turns out to be his savior]

788
00:33:03,259 --> 00:33:06,242
[Thank you, senior]

789
00:33:07,263 --> 00:33:10,633
[From rivals to partners at the pasta station]

790
00:33:10,633 --> 00:33:11,867
No.

791
00:33:11,867 --> 00:33:14,837
[Sorem also coaches him on agnolotti shape]
It's another kind of thing.

792
00:33:14,837 --> 00:33:16,639
It should look like a ring.

793
00:33:16,639 --> 00:33:18,974
A ring? Like this?

794
00:33:18,974 --> 00:33:21,844
Yes, much better.

795
00:33:21,844 --> 00:33:25,247
[Thank goodness]

796
00:33:25,247 --> 00:33:27,850
[Shaped round as if nothing had happened]

797
00:33:27,850 --> 00:33:30,152
[Thanks to him, pheasant agnolotti done]

798
00:33:30,152 --> 00:33:31,821
Next I need the torta fritters.

799
00:33:31,821 --> 00:33:33,521
Yes!

800
00:33:34,490 --> 00:33:37,626
Have you made torta fritters before?

801
00:33:37,626 --> 00:33:39,762
- Torta?
- Yes.

802
00:33:39,762 --> 00:33:43,198
- Fried bread.
- Yes, I'll try it.

803
00:33:44,133 --> 00:33:46,113
[Roll out a thin, neat square of dough]
On top of that, I had to cut these fritters too

804
00:33:46,113 --> 00:33:47,303
and hand them off.

805
00:33:47,303 --> 00:33:48,671
- That's right.
- In the middle of making the dough.

806
00:33:48,671 --> 00:33:50,172
[Like this shape]
- Those look delicious. - They are.

807
00:33:50,172 --> 00:33:53,175
[Once fried, they puff up beautifully]
- They're really good. - Super nutty.

808
00:33:53,175 --> 00:33:57,646
[Hee Tae adjusts the roller on his own]

809
00:33:57,646 --> 00:34:00,716
[Flatten]

810
00:34:00,716 --> 00:34:04,820
[Fold, repeat]

811
00:34:04,820 --> 00:34:07,623
[The step that makes the dough even and thin]

812
00:34:07,623 --> 00:34:09,325
Nice.

813
00:34:09,325 --> 00:34:11,955
[Checks by hand]

814
00:34:12,761 --> 00:34:15,664
[Adjusts thinner]

815
00:34:15,664 --> 00:34:19,969
[27 years of instinct says
it needs to be thinner]

816
00:34:19,969 --> 00:34:22,805
[No.2 sous chef is waiting]

817
00:34:22,805 --> 00:34:24,940
[Where's the dough?]

818
00:34:24,940 --> 00:34:27,443
[Sneaks a glance]

819
00:34:27,443 --> 00:34:31,330
[Sam Kim mode on, to speed it up]

820
00:34:32,348 --> 00:34:36,685
[Trims off the rough edges]

821
00:34:37,453 --> 00:34:41,657
[Starts cutting without hesitation]

822
00:34:41,657 --> 00:34:43,559
[Quick, even, clean cuts]

823
00:34:43,559 --> 00:34:45,493
The sizes have to match too.

824
00:34:47,229 --> 00:34:50,199
[He memorized the fritters in half a day?]

825
00:34:50,199 --> 00:34:51,636
- Is it five pieces?
- Four pieces.

826
00:34:51,636 --> 00:34:54,036
- Four pieces?
- Yes.

827
00:34:54,036 --> 00:34:55,838
[One-handed]
One, two.

828
00:34:55,838 --> 00:34:58,240
You can go faster if you use both hands.

829
00:34:58,240 --> 00:34:59,375
Yes.

830
00:34:59,375 --> 00:35:01,210
[Speeds up with both hands]

831
00:35:01,210 --> 00:35:03,345
He's saying, use both hands.

832
00:35:05,381 --> 00:35:08,172
[Two hands, four pieces each, done]

833
00:35:09,418 --> 00:35:13,422
[Hands off straight to the fryer]

834
00:35:13,422 --> 00:35:17,626
[Right into the hot oil with a plop]

835
00:35:17,626 --> 00:35:20,663
It kind of reminds me of tofu crackers.

836
00:35:20,663 --> 00:35:23,566
But inside it's actually really soft.

837
00:35:23,566 --> 00:35:25,634
[While Hee Tae's torta fritters fry up]

838
00:35:25,634 --> 00:35:29,004
- Next, tagliatelle for two.
- Tagliatelle.

839
00:35:29,004 --> 00:35:31,740
[Rushing into the next dish]
So the fact that this is day one dinner,

840
00:35:31,740 --> 00:35:34,009
- I still can't believe it watching now.
- You're right.

841
00:35:34,009 --> 00:35:36,845
[Straight to dough prep]
So day one was crazy busy.

842
00:35:36,845 --> 00:35:39,248
- Use the mixer first.
- Setting six?

843
00:35:39,248 --> 00:35:40,382
That's right.

844
00:35:40,382 --> 00:35:43,919
[He knows the dough setting right away?]

845
00:35:43,919 --> 00:35:48,791
[Eyes go wide]

846
00:35:48,791 --> 00:35:53,596
[The secret behind Hee Tae's confidence]

847
00:35:53,596 --> 00:35:56,465
[Recipes drilled into his notebook!]
Tagliatelle, thickness 6.

848
00:35:56,465 --> 00:35:57,967
- Exactly.
- Yes.

849
00:35:57,967 --> 00:36:00,069
- Pecorino.
- Okay.

850
00:36:00,069 --> 00:36:02,338
[Here they dust on pecorino first]
Pecorino is a little

851
00:36:02,338 --> 00:36:03,606
funkier-smelling than regular cheese.

852
00:36:03,606 --> 00:36:05,174
That's the sheep's milk for you.

853
00:36:05,174 --> 00:36:09,911
[Rolls thin again]
A bit funkier and saltier than parmesan.

854
00:36:10,813 --> 00:36:13,962
[Cuts the pasta almost like kalguksu]

855
00:36:15,684 --> 00:36:16,819
[Toss with duck ragu]
That looks good, right?

856
00:36:16,819 --> 00:36:18,454
- That looks amazing.
- Duck ragu?

857
00:36:18,454 --> 00:36:20,155
The food here is all great.

858
00:36:20,155 --> 00:36:22,091
[Duck tagliatelle]
The colors are beautiful too.

859
00:36:22,091 --> 00:36:23,792
The colors really pop.

860
00:36:23,792 --> 00:36:28,697
[But to Sorem he's just a chef-savvy farmer]

861
00:36:28,697 --> 00:36:30,544
Two tagliatelle, one asparagus.

862
00:36:30,544 --> 00:36:33,601
[Two more orders of tagliatelle come in]
Two pigeons, one brasato, one grilled veggies.

863
00:36:35,004 --> 00:36:36,271
[Missed the order]

864
00:36:36,271 --> 00:36:39,352
Catching those orders is not easy.

865
00:36:39,352 --> 00:36:41,543
[Total of four servings with the add-ons]
Four servings.

866
00:36:41,543 --> 00:36:42,778
Four servings.

867
00:36:42,778 --> 00:36:44,713
Four servings, got it.

868
00:36:48,052 --> 00:36:51,742
[Quickly adds two more dough balls]

869
00:36:53,255 --> 00:36:58,227
[First time doing a bigger batch]

870
00:36:58,227 --> 00:37:01,866
[Nervous]

871
00:37:03,732 --> 00:37:05,134
A little less.

872
00:37:05,134 --> 00:37:06,456
Yes.

873
00:37:07,378 --> 00:37:10,606
[Applies the feedback right away]
Honestly, they have to be a little suspicious.

874
00:37:10,606 --> 00:37:12,808
[Hee Tae rolls it to the right thickness]
How is he doing this much on day one?

875
00:37:12,808 --> 00:37:13,809
Right, he's all good.

876
00:37:13,809 --> 00:37:16,111
- You can just tell.
- These are good.

877
00:37:17,813 --> 00:37:21,338
[His torta fritters fried up in the meantime]

878
00:37:22,317 --> 00:37:24,486
He's better than you, Sorem.

879
00:37:26,422 --> 00:37:28,823
There Simone goes again.

880
00:37:29,658 --> 00:37:30,893
[Hehe]
Why is he like...

881
00:37:30,893 --> 00:37:33,729
- But it's true.
- Don't you think?

882
00:37:33,729 --> 00:37:36,131
Sorem, watch Hee Tae and learn.

883
00:37:36,131 --> 00:37:37,332
Learn from him.

884
00:37:37,332 --> 00:37:38,434
Hee Tae.

885
00:37:38,434 --> 00:37:40,995
When that happens, it's hard to get close.

886
00:37:40,995 --> 00:37:44,373
That kind of thing stings the ego.

887
00:37:44,373 --> 00:37:46,508
- Hee Tae!
- Yes.

888
00:37:46,508 --> 00:37:48,677
- Hee Tae!
- Yes.

889
00:37:48,677 --> 00:37:51,379
[Your torta fritters are perfect]
- Good. Perfect. - Thank you.

890
00:37:55,384 --> 00:37:56,351
Good.

891
00:37:56,351 --> 00:37:58,520
- Perfect.
- Thank you.

892
00:37:58,520 --> 00:38:02,191
[Hee Tae just basks in the praise]

893
00:38:02,191 --> 00:38:04,326
[His fritters came out too well, oblivious]

894
00:38:04,326 --> 00:38:08,263
[Puffed up beautifully]

895
00:38:08,263 --> 00:38:12,868
[He really nailed it]
Sorem started off smiling,

896
00:38:12,868 --> 00:38:14,503
then his face slowly froze.

897
00:38:14,503 --> 00:38:17,506
I was behind him, so I couldn't see his face.

898
00:38:17,506 --> 00:38:20,575
- His face does not look good.
- Not good.

899
00:38:21,410 --> 00:38:24,580
[Glance]

900
00:38:24,580 --> 00:38:26,915
It's true, Hee Tae is actually better.

901
00:38:26,915 --> 00:38:30,084
I told you, I wasn't kidding.

902
00:38:30,686 --> 00:38:33,322
You told me I was good too, and now this...

903
00:38:33,322 --> 00:38:35,524
Sorem is sulking.

904
00:38:35,524 --> 00:38:39,194
- You think it's beginner's luck?
- I don't know.

905
00:38:39,194 --> 00:38:42,765
He's writing it off as beginner's luck.

906
00:38:42,765 --> 00:38:46,335
[No.4 Sorem's spot in danger?]
[The actual rookie]

907
00:38:46,335 --> 00:38:50,472
[He's really better than me?]
Sorem's about to lose his turf.

908
00:38:50,472 --> 00:38:51,707
[The situation is...]
Oh, really?

909
00:38:51,707 --> 00:38:56,011
When this happened,
he thought he came in under him,

910
00:38:56,011 --> 00:38:58,881
but he's better and gets more praise?

911
00:38:58,881 --> 00:39:00,816
- No way he's happy about that.
- Yeah, that's rough.

912
00:39:00,816 --> 00:39:02,084
He'd be jealous.

913
00:39:02,084 --> 00:39:04,553
I'm dying to hear his interview after this.

914
00:39:04,553 --> 00:39:06,822
What everyone really thinks.

915
00:39:06,822 --> 00:39:09,267
[Sorem's true feelings revealed]

916
00:39:11,560 --> 00:39:13,729
I was floored.

917
00:39:13,729 --> 00:39:17,132
He did say this morning
that he had done it before.

918
00:39:17,132 --> 00:39:19,647
[Praise]
When I say something,

919
00:39:19,647 --> 00:39:21,970
[Oh, Sorem...]
Hee Tae gets it right away.

920
00:39:21,970 --> 00:39:23,038
He understands right away.

921
00:39:23,038 --> 00:39:24,840
And he actually puts it into action.

922
00:39:24,840 --> 00:39:28,977
Hee Tae has real hand skills and potential.

923
00:39:28,977 --> 00:39:30,078
[Thumbs up]

924
00:39:30,078 --> 00:39:31,647
That thumbs-up is the real deal.

925
00:39:31,647 --> 00:39:34,583
He wasn't even looking
when his thumb went up on its own.

926
00:39:34,583 --> 00:39:36,718
[Earned]

927
00:39:36,718 --> 00:39:38,320
[Still, as the senior, he checks closely]

928
00:39:38,320 --> 00:39:40,188
Sorem is such a sweetheart.

929
00:39:41,790 --> 00:39:44,560
[Quietly dusts on flour without a word]

930
00:39:44,560 --> 00:39:48,530
[He gives him props and teaches him more]

931
00:39:48,530 --> 00:39:51,969
[Tagliatelle for four, done]

932
00:39:52,868 --> 00:39:54,703
Send out two tagliatelle.

933
00:39:54,703 --> 00:39:56,038
Send out two tagliatelle.

934
00:39:56,038 --> 00:39:57,939
- Got it.
- Understood.

935
00:40:00,887 --> 00:40:02,655
Thanks.

936
00:40:06,915 --> 00:40:08,483
[Nice work]

937
00:40:08,483 --> 00:40:10,754
[Proud]
Thank you.

938
00:40:13,822 --> 00:40:17,626
[So how are the diners reacting?]

939
00:40:17,626 --> 00:40:19,261
Cheese on your tagliatelle?

940
00:40:19,261 --> 00:40:23,599
I never get to see people
actually eat what I made.

941
00:40:23,599 --> 00:40:27,101
- How does it look?
- Feels totally new.

942
00:40:29,004 --> 00:40:31,935
[Hopeful]

943
00:40:38,447 --> 00:40:40,315
This is really good!

944
00:40:40,315 --> 00:40:42,251
[Proud]

945
00:40:42,251 --> 00:40:44,353
[Smiles all around]

946
00:40:44,353 --> 00:40:48,357
[The taste is just fantastic]
Smiling, eating with that satisfied look.

947
00:40:48,357 --> 00:40:50,892
[How about the other table?]

948
00:40:53,161 --> 00:40:55,029
Bravo.

949
00:40:56,265 --> 00:40:59,635
Something's different.
Is there mascarpone in this?

950
00:40:59,635 --> 00:41:03,538
[The best tortelli in Parma]
The thing about Italians at meals...

951
00:41:03,538 --> 00:41:06,308
They talk a lot.
They talk about the food a ton.

952
00:41:06,308 --> 00:41:09,378
[Yum]

953
00:41:09,378 --> 00:41:13,877
[Every guest is enjoying it]

954
00:41:16,485 --> 00:41:21,892
[Come back to the pasta station, total win]

955
00:41:25,160 --> 00:41:28,163
[But then...]

956
00:41:28,163 --> 00:41:29,998
One tenderloin, three guinea fowl,

957
00:41:29,998 --> 00:41:33,869
one roasted rabbit, one pheasant agnolotti,
and one roasted potato.

958
00:41:33,869 --> 00:41:35,170
[Order hell]

959
00:41:35,170 --> 00:41:36,938
This is not easy.

960
00:41:38,307 --> 00:41:44,002
[Still plenty of main dishes to send out]

961
00:41:46,815 --> 00:41:48,850
I was really eyeing that station.

962
00:41:48,850 --> 00:41:49,918
The mains.

963
00:41:49,918 --> 00:41:51,608
[The stove zone is just getting started]

964
00:41:53,722 --> 00:41:55,891
[Just then, Sorem heads for the stove]

965
00:41:55,891 --> 00:41:57,693
- Sorem.
- Sorem.

966
00:41:57,693 --> 00:42:00,128
- I'll hand you what you need. Stay back.
- Okay.

967
00:42:00,829 --> 00:42:02,597
This place is kind of

968
00:42:02,597 --> 00:42:05,834
[Even getting near the stove gets you scolded]
sacred ground.

969
00:42:05,834 --> 00:42:09,271
It's hot stuff, and only two people cook there.

970
00:42:09,271 --> 00:42:11,740
[Once his pasta station work was done]
So just those two do it.

971
00:42:11,740 --> 00:42:14,276
- Once the pasta is wrapped up,
- It's done now.

972
00:42:14,276 --> 00:42:17,145
the mains are with nothing else to do,

973
00:42:17,145 --> 00:42:20,248
- It's like...
- I really wanted in.

974
00:42:20,248 --> 00:42:21,350
[Watches the plating]

975
00:42:21,350 --> 00:42:24,252
So what the rest of us can do is plating.

976
00:42:24,252 --> 00:42:25,838
[Glances at the cooking side too, busy]

977
00:42:26,888 --> 00:42:29,558
- Plate the steak.
- Yes.

978
00:42:29,558 --> 00:42:30,759
Yes!

979
00:42:30,759 --> 00:42:32,995
Lu came in to help with plating too.

980
00:42:32,995 --> 00:42:35,364
[Plating?]

981
00:42:35,364 --> 00:42:38,584
It's day one,
so I don't even know how they plate.

982
00:42:38,584 --> 00:42:39,801
The style is bound to be different too.

983
00:42:39,801 --> 00:42:40,936
[The two seniors start plating
on the chef's word]

984
00:42:40,936 --> 00:42:43,698
[Veal tenderloin]

985
00:42:44,639 --> 00:42:48,176
[Watching closely]

986
00:42:48,176 --> 00:42:50,879
[Picking it up by sight]
I'm memorizing it.

987
00:42:50,879 --> 00:42:54,678
[Sorem too]

988
00:42:56,018 --> 00:42:58,487
[Tuna sauce]
In Korea, would we call that tuna mayo?

989
00:42:58,487 --> 00:42:59,521
- It tastes almost the same.
- Like fancy tuna mayo.

990
00:42:59,521 --> 00:43:01,323
- Similar?
- Yeah, pretty close.

991
00:43:01,323 --> 00:43:02,924
[Plating the garnish for the veal tenderloin]

992
00:43:02,924 --> 00:43:05,861
[A touch of veggies too]

993
00:43:05,861 --> 00:43:09,231
I had the same thought
running all through dinner.

994
00:43:09,231 --> 00:43:12,034
What can I do over by the mains?

995
00:43:12,034 --> 00:43:15,504
I was wondering if there was a way in.

996
00:43:15,504 --> 00:43:19,474
I kept thinking,
can I slip into that cooking line?

997
00:43:19,474 --> 00:43:24,079
I got over to this side, but...
there was another mountain.

998
00:43:24,079 --> 00:43:25,080
One peak after another.

999
00:43:25,080 --> 00:43:27,320
[Wondering]

1000
00:43:28,417 --> 00:43:32,870
Maybe stick close to the main plating?

1001
00:43:33,855 --> 00:43:38,660
[Plan: start with what the seniors are plating]

1002
00:43:38,660 --> 00:43:40,862
Getting your hands on it is the hard part...

1003
00:43:40,862 --> 00:43:42,464
- When it's slammed...
- It's not easy.

1004
00:43:42,464 --> 00:43:44,499
There's a moment of hesitation.

1005
00:43:44,499 --> 00:43:45,967
Should I touch it, or should I not?

1006
00:43:45,967 --> 00:43:48,770
- You could end up in the way.
- Right.

1007
00:43:48,770 --> 00:43:51,640
[Wrestling with it on his own]

1008
00:43:51,640 --> 00:43:54,843
[Mind made up]

1009
00:43:54,843 --> 00:43:58,447
- "I'll help out too."
- I'll just go for it, even if I don't know.

1010
00:43:58,447 --> 00:44:00,815
- "At least let me line them up first."
- Yes.

1011
00:44:01,683 --> 00:44:05,954
[Right then the head chef is prepping garnish]

1012
00:44:05,954 --> 00:44:06,964
Yes.

1013
00:44:06,964 --> 00:44:08,812
[Spots it]

1014
00:44:09,691 --> 00:44:12,127
[That's...]

1015
00:44:12,127 --> 00:44:17,440
[The veal garnish Sorem just plated]

1016
00:44:18,467 --> 00:44:22,804
[Hee Tae remembers it]

1017
00:44:22,804 --> 00:44:24,306
Hold on.

1018
00:44:24,306 --> 00:44:26,341
[Reaches straight for the garnish]

1019
00:44:29,744 --> 00:44:31,554
[Nods]

1020
00:44:32,614 --> 00:44:34,382
[Snags the garnish in a flash]

1021
00:44:34,382 --> 00:44:36,918
[Quick]
Right, that kind of attitude matters.

1022
00:44:45,060 --> 00:44:48,230
As you know, I'm a guy who uses tweezers.

1023
00:44:48,230 --> 00:44:50,699
- Right, just with their hands like that.
- Doing it by hand

1024
00:44:50,699 --> 00:44:53,301
- was really not easy.
- That's unusual.

1025
00:44:53,301 --> 00:44:57,506
It feels like an old-school joint,
that plating style.

1026
00:44:57,506 --> 00:44:58,707
By hand.

1027
00:44:58,707 --> 00:45:01,243
It was a salad.

1028
00:45:01,243 --> 00:45:03,979
Tossed in lemon dressing before it goes out.

1029
00:45:03,979 --> 00:45:05,914
[Hee Tae's first plating]

1030
00:45:05,914 --> 00:45:09,492
They never say, "Come over and do this."

1031
00:45:09,492 --> 00:45:12,587
If you don't reach in, you don't get the shot.

1032
00:45:12,587 --> 00:45:17,325
So even for one plating,
you have to slip right in.

1033
00:45:17,325 --> 00:45:20,477
[A quiet but bold move]

1034
00:45:21,997 --> 00:45:24,966
[Plates with confidence]

1035
00:45:24,966 --> 00:45:29,671
My thinking was, after this,
I'm getting into the mains.

1036
00:45:29,671 --> 00:45:31,740
[Veal tenderloin done]
You're really going for it.

1037
00:45:31,740 --> 00:45:33,841
- On day one.
- Right out the gate.

1038
00:45:34,929 --> 00:45:39,606
[Hands it off fast so service can roll]

1039
00:45:41,082 --> 00:45:42,450
When a dish goes out,

1040
00:45:42,450 --> 00:45:46,121
the boss checks
pretty much everything at the front.

1041
00:45:46,121 --> 00:45:49,291
He's really picky.

1042
00:45:49,291 --> 00:45:53,364
[Confidence way up]

1043
00:45:53,364 --> 00:45:57,953
[The sous chef is plating another dish]

1044
00:45:59,334 --> 00:46:01,903
[Slips in again]

1045
00:46:01,903 --> 00:46:04,906
[Hee Tae sidles right up again]

1046
00:46:04,906 --> 00:46:07,208
[Breast]
Pigeon.

1047
00:46:09,110 --> 00:46:11,446
- And the pigeon leg meat.
- The pigeon was good too.

1048
00:46:11,446 --> 00:46:14,149
What does pigeon taste like?

1049
00:46:14,149 --> 00:46:16,251
- It's a little chewy.
- Chewy and dense.

1050
00:46:16,251 --> 00:46:18,987
[Sous chef shows him pigeon meatball plating]
So it's that chewy, dense flavor.

1051
00:46:18,987 --> 00:46:22,452
[Focuses harder since it's unfamiliar]

1052
00:46:23,391 --> 00:46:25,836
Mustard sprouts.

1053
00:46:27,929 --> 00:46:30,098
[The sous chef names every ingredient]

1054
00:46:30,098 --> 00:46:32,166
That looks good.

1055
00:46:34,436 --> 00:46:36,237
Perfect.

1056
00:46:37,172 --> 00:46:41,743
Even without the seniors telling you to,
you jumped right into the plating yourself.

1057
00:46:41,743 --> 00:46:42,744
Yes.

1058
00:46:42,744 --> 00:46:45,614
They like that kind of thing in the kitchen.

1059
00:46:45,614 --> 00:46:47,816
[Wipes things down without missing a beat]

1060
00:46:47,816 --> 00:46:49,884
Okay, Hee Tae.

1061
00:46:50,986 --> 00:46:54,923
- Always smell it.
- Okay.

1062
00:46:54,923 --> 00:46:57,025
[Smell it?]
Smell.

1063
00:46:57,025 --> 00:47:00,128
[Sniff]

1064
00:47:00,128 --> 00:47:02,597
[Not the towel]
Look, smell, and taste the food.

1065
00:47:02,597 --> 00:47:04,799
Yes, thank you.

1066
00:47:06,101 --> 00:47:07,702
What he meant was, smell the food.

1067
00:47:07,702 --> 00:47:09,471
Why are you smelling the dish towel?

1068
00:47:09,471 --> 00:47:11,985
He said to smell something,
but it wasn't said over food,

1069
00:47:11,985 --> 00:47:14,242
[Sniffs it dead seriously too]
so I thought, the towel...

1070
00:47:14,242 --> 00:47:15,844
- Towel smell.
- Right now,

1071
00:47:15,844 --> 00:47:18,246
[Awkward all alone]
sniffing a towel...

1072
00:47:18,246 --> 00:47:19,581
[Fidgets with the bread hat]

1073
00:47:19,581 --> 00:47:22,117
I'll fatten Hee Tae up.
He's going to taste everything.

1074
00:47:22,117 --> 00:47:25,720
He said he'd put five kilos
on him in five days.

1075
00:47:25,720 --> 00:47:28,290
That's right!

1076
00:47:28,290 --> 00:47:30,859
[Bulking up thanks to senior love?]
Gosh, five kilos in five days.

1077
00:47:30,859 --> 00:47:33,943
[Hee Tae, get ready, hehe]

1078
00:47:34,788 --> 00:47:37,214
[Grabbing things]

1079
00:47:38,199 --> 00:47:42,742
[This time Hee Tae hands him
a garnish unprompted]

1080
00:47:44,239 --> 00:47:46,340
That's right.

1081
00:47:48,009 --> 00:47:50,145
I showed him the plating once,

1082
00:47:50,145 --> 00:47:55,298
then handed him a pigeon,
and he knew right away what to do.

1083
00:47:56,718 --> 00:48:00,322
[Proud]
I don't have to explain it twice.

1084
00:48:00,322 --> 00:48:03,658
He picks it up fast
and runs with it after one go.

1085
00:48:03,658 --> 00:48:06,995
If they need something,
they love it when you slide it over,

1086
00:48:06,995 --> 00:48:08,763
so I did it on purpose.

1087
00:48:08,763 --> 00:48:12,200
[A long buildup to break into the stove zone]
Naturally toward the stove zone...

1088
00:48:12,200 --> 00:48:15,169
Naturally toward the stove zone...

1089
00:48:16,137 --> 00:48:19,442
[Quietly getting closer and closer]

1090
00:48:20,241 --> 00:48:21,810
Hee Tae.

1091
00:48:21,810 --> 00:48:23,078
[Thumbs up]
Yes.

1092
00:48:23,078 --> 00:48:25,046
Yes.

1093
00:48:25,046 --> 00:48:26,703
[Corners of his mouth lift]

1094
00:48:29,150 --> 00:48:32,821
[The head chef has been watching all along]

1095
00:48:32,821 --> 00:48:33,913
- Hee Tae.
- Yeah.

1096
00:48:33,913 --> 00:48:36,891
Later, head out with Lucrezia and serve gelato.

1097
00:48:36,891 --> 00:48:39,260
- Huh?
- Serve it.

1098
00:48:39,260 --> 00:48:42,263
[Gelato?]
Serve the gelato.

1099
00:48:45,233 --> 00:48:47,702
Would you like gelato?

1100
00:48:47,702 --> 00:48:49,371
Chocolate and hazelnuts.

1101
00:48:49,371 --> 00:48:51,648
[Lucrezia's job is serving gelato]

1102
00:48:52,941 --> 00:48:58,012
Their cart is kind of famous as a signature.

1103
00:48:58,880 --> 00:49:02,751
[A new task for the day-one rookie]

1104
00:49:02,751 --> 00:49:04,652
- That's the hardest part.
- Gosh, even gelato.

1105
00:49:04,652 --> 00:49:07,721
They're piling a lot on day one.

1106
00:49:08,656 --> 00:49:10,724
Ready?

1107
00:49:11,493 --> 00:49:13,228
Seriously?

1108
00:49:13,228 --> 00:49:14,963
Yes, you're really coming with me.

1109
00:49:14,963 --> 00:49:17,365
It's going to be amazing.

1110
00:49:17,365 --> 00:49:19,801
Honestly, I was happy,

1111
00:49:19,801 --> 00:49:25,206
because handing the gelato service
to someone else is really rare here.

1112
00:49:25,206 --> 00:49:28,943
I asked Sorem, and he said
he's never done the gelato service.

1113
00:49:28,943 --> 00:49:30,412
- Really?
- Yeah.

1114
00:49:30,412 --> 00:49:32,013
- That's a sign of trust, isn't it?
- He'd be measured against him a lot.

1115
00:49:32,013 --> 00:49:34,815
[Six months for Sorem, one day for him!]
I was like, "Why me?"

1116
00:49:35,984 --> 00:49:40,723
[Stunning handmade gelato]

1117
00:49:42,323 --> 00:49:44,492
What toppings do you like with your gelato?

1118
00:49:44,492 --> 00:49:47,629
- They bring the gelato to you on the spot?
- An orange liquor.

1119
00:49:47,629 --> 00:49:49,464
San Marzano is an herbal liquor.

1120
00:49:49,464 --> 00:49:51,733
[Tableside gelato cart is a house tradition]
That's the real deal.

1121
00:49:51,733 --> 00:49:53,068
Right.

1122
00:49:53,902 --> 00:49:56,438
Toppings on the spot?

1123
00:49:56,438 --> 00:49:59,140
[Any topping the guest wants]
That's pretty cool.

1124
00:49:59,140 --> 00:50:01,943
Guests don't just eat what's served.

1125
00:50:01,943 --> 00:50:04,946
We let them pick their own toppings,

1126
00:50:04,946 --> 00:50:08,683
so it feels like a little game.

1127
00:50:08,683 --> 00:50:11,286
If there are six at a table,
all six order something different.

1128
00:50:11,286 --> 00:50:13,321
[Half the fun is your own combo]

1129
00:50:13,321 --> 00:50:15,857
[Everything was great. Gelato was the best.]
[Try the gelato. Best I've ever had.]

1130
00:50:15,857 --> 00:50:17,400
[Cherry on top is the gelato. A feast.]
They all love it.

1131
00:50:17,400 --> 00:50:18,418
- They do.
- They love it.

1132
00:50:18,418 --> 00:50:20,829
Those older folks talk like little kids,
they love it so much.

1133
00:50:20,829 --> 00:50:22,230
Right.

1134
00:50:22,230 --> 00:50:23,752
Exactly.

1135
00:50:24,833 --> 00:50:27,702
When it's dessert time,
everyone turns into a kid.

1136
00:50:27,702 --> 00:50:30,572
You should do something like this
with the gelato.

1137
00:50:30,572 --> 00:50:32,507
Turkish style.

1138
00:50:32,507 --> 00:50:34,042
- Flip it around.
- Like fake-them-out moves?

1139
00:50:34,042 --> 00:50:35,109
Fake-them-out?

1140
00:50:35,109 --> 00:50:37,245
- Here, they'd straight up chuck it.
- A fight would break out.

1141
00:50:37,245 --> 00:50:38,880
[Boss Giancarlo would lose it]

1142
00:50:38,880 --> 00:50:40,260
Right.

1143
00:50:40,260 --> 00:50:42,984
[Skip the Turkish moves, keep it Italian]
That kind of thing would be fun, though.

1144
00:50:42,984 --> 00:50:44,319
[Ever served gelato before?]
Gelato?

1145
00:50:44,319 --> 00:50:46,120
I've never served gelato.

1146
00:50:46,120 --> 00:50:49,023
I should try. Never done it.

1147
00:50:49,757 --> 00:50:52,227
[Just day one undercover]

1148
00:50:52,227 --> 00:50:55,129
[New challenge]

1149
00:50:55,129 --> 00:50:56,464
[Gelato cart rolls out]
Ready?

1150
00:50:56,464 --> 00:50:58,700
- I'll show you how it's done.
- Yes.

1151
00:50:58,700 --> 00:50:59,801
Do you talk to guests in English?

1152
00:50:59,801 --> 00:51:01,970
No, Italian.

1153
00:51:01,970 --> 00:51:03,538
[Italian?]

1154
00:51:03,538 --> 00:51:06,140
- He has to do it in Italian now.
- That's so hard.

1155
00:51:06,140 --> 00:51:07,442
[Heart racing]

1156
00:51:07,442 --> 00:51:10,344
He was really nervous.

1157
00:51:11,079 --> 00:51:15,717
[First time facing guests, double nerves]

1158
00:51:15,717 --> 00:51:17,085
[Bustling]

1159
00:51:17,085 --> 00:51:19,053
The place is always like that.

1160
00:51:19,053 --> 00:51:21,756
[Parma's restaurant is always packed]
There's always a crowd.

1161
00:51:21,756 --> 00:51:23,725
[Out with the gelato cart]

1162
00:51:23,725 --> 00:51:25,927
[Rookie Hee Tae enters]
Hello, everyone.

1163
00:51:25,927 --> 00:51:28,630
- Hello, everyone.
- Gelato!

1164
00:51:28,630 --> 00:51:32,700
The kids are excited. It's gelato time.

1165
00:51:32,700 --> 00:51:35,336
[Stiff]

1166
00:51:35,336 --> 00:51:37,071
I must have been so nervous.

1167
00:51:37,071 --> 00:51:39,374
[Kid's thrilled, Hee Tae is wound tight]

1168
00:51:39,374 --> 00:51:42,944
[And no wonder]

1169
00:51:42,944 --> 00:51:44,979
[Italian over here...]

1170
00:51:44,979 --> 00:51:48,249
[Italian over there...]

1171
00:51:48,249 --> 00:51:51,786
[Eyes glaze over from the Italian flood]
The two liquors, San Marzano and warm eggnog.

1172
00:51:51,786 --> 00:51:53,855
He's like...

1173
00:51:53,855 --> 00:51:56,190
- That was the hardest part for me.
- Brutal.

1174
00:51:56,190 --> 00:52:00,361
You have to keep talking
with the guests the whole time.

1175
00:52:00,361 --> 00:52:02,697
[Gelato service was harder than pasta]
The hardest part.

1176
00:52:02,697 --> 00:52:05,500
[Senior Lu demonstrates first]
For gelato toppings...

1177
00:52:05,500 --> 00:52:07,869
[Topping 1: melted chocolate]
We have melted chocolate,

1178
00:52:07,869 --> 00:52:10,038
[Topping 2: caramel hazelnut]
caramel hazelnut,

1179
00:52:10,038 --> 00:52:12,040
[Topping 3: chocolate balls]
chocolate balls,

1180
00:52:12,040 --> 00:52:14,293
[Topping 4: herb, fruit distillate]
San Marzano

1181
00:52:14,293 --> 00:52:15,380
[Topping 5: warm zabaione]
and warm zabaione.

1182
00:52:15,380 --> 00:52:17,712
- Sabayon?
- Sabayon.

1183
00:52:17,712 --> 00:52:20,048
So what's sabayon, exactly? Zabaione?

1184
00:52:20,048 --> 00:52:22,216
It's one of Italy's traditional desserts.

1185
00:52:22,216 --> 00:52:24,519
You crack in eggs,

1186
00:52:24,519 --> 00:52:26,988
add some alcohol,

1187
00:52:26,988 --> 00:52:29,023
[Egg yolks, wine, sugar]

1188
00:52:29,023 --> 00:52:30,525
and whisk it as it cooks.

1189
00:52:30,525 --> 00:52:34,158
[Whisk fast over heat]

1190
00:52:35,430 --> 00:52:37,999
[Zabaione, done]
And then you eat that.

1191
00:52:37,999 --> 00:52:39,613
- Made with eggs.
- It's got alcohol in it.

1192
00:52:39,613 --> 00:52:41,069
[A sauce that pairs with desserts]
Think of it as a dessert cream.

1193
00:52:41,069 --> 00:52:42,670
I bet the zabaione is the most popular.

1194
00:52:42,670 --> 00:52:44,739
- It's the top pick.
- Right?

1195
00:52:44,739 --> 00:52:48,032
Here, even the zabaione is made live.

1196
00:52:48,977 --> 00:52:51,679
[Warm and fluffy]

1197
00:52:51,679 --> 00:52:53,314
[First gelato guest's topping order]

1198
00:52:53,314 --> 00:52:55,750
[Chocolate balls, melted chocolate]
Of course.

1199
00:52:55,750 --> 00:52:58,152
[Looks politely at Senior Lu]

1200
00:52:58,152 --> 00:53:00,287
What I do is this.

1201
00:53:00,922 --> 00:53:03,758
This is my first time scooping like this.

1202
00:53:03,758 --> 00:53:05,593
I scoop it like this.

1203
00:53:05,593 --> 00:53:08,830
- I help myself with this.
- So you scrape it down like that.

1204
00:53:08,830 --> 00:53:10,498
I help myself with this.

1205
00:53:10,498 --> 00:53:12,834
This is the texture you get

1206
00:53:12,834 --> 00:53:16,004
right when ice cream melts
smoothly in your mouth.

1207
00:53:16,004 --> 00:53:18,439
- Right before it melts.
- Yes, exactly.

1208
00:53:18,439 --> 00:53:21,571
Served on the spot, how good must this be?

1209
00:53:27,782 --> 00:53:31,719
[Scoops it right in front of the guest]

1210
00:53:31,719 --> 00:53:34,555
[Topping 1: chocolate]

1211
00:53:34,555 --> 00:53:35,690
[Topping 2: chocolate balls]

1212
00:53:35,690 --> 00:53:38,393
- That has to be incredible.
- It can't be anything but good.

1213
00:53:38,393 --> 00:53:39,861
[Good already, and now chocolate too]

1214
00:53:39,861 --> 00:53:42,162
Here you go.

1215
00:53:42,930 --> 00:53:43,998
[Verdict from the little guest?]

1216
00:53:43,998 --> 00:53:47,095
[Bite]

1217
00:53:47,802 --> 00:53:49,337
- It's good.
- Good?

1218
00:53:49,337 --> 00:53:52,306
- Kids love ice cream.
- Right.

1219
00:53:52,940 --> 00:53:54,375
He's so excited.

1220
00:53:54,375 --> 00:53:57,311
[A Dad smile]

1221
00:53:57,311 --> 00:53:59,580
And what about you?

1222
00:53:59,580 --> 00:54:01,916
- Zabaione.
- Zabaione.

1223
00:54:01,916 --> 00:54:03,851
Okay. Want to give it a shot?

1224
00:54:03,851 --> 00:54:05,086
- Should I try?
- Yeah.

1225
00:54:05,086 --> 00:54:07,522
Try it!

1226
00:54:07,522 --> 00:54:08,823
[Straight into the real thing]

1227
00:54:08,823 --> 00:54:11,358
Like this?

1228
00:54:11,959 --> 00:54:13,394
Everyone's watching.

1229
00:54:13,394 --> 00:54:14,829
This is so much pressure.

1230
00:54:14,829 --> 00:54:17,247
[You got this!]
Everyone's looking right now.

1231
00:54:18,366 --> 00:54:20,501
Try it!

1232
00:54:20,501 --> 00:54:22,470
Like this?

1233
00:54:22,470 --> 00:54:25,639
Good. Use the other spoon to help.

1234
00:54:26,274 --> 00:54:28,676
[Scrape]

1235
00:54:28,676 --> 00:54:32,180
- Scoop from the side if you want, it's softer.
- Yes.

1236
00:54:32,180 --> 00:54:33,762
The softer spot.

1237
00:54:34,716 --> 00:54:36,718
- The sides melt first.
- Right.

1238
00:54:36,718 --> 00:54:38,298
So you scrape from the outside.

1239
00:54:38,298 --> 00:54:40,187
- Start where it's melting.
- Right.

1240
00:54:41,589 --> 00:54:43,291
Okay.

1241
00:54:43,291 --> 00:54:45,727
- Her topping is zabaione.
- Zabaione.

1242
00:54:45,727 --> 00:54:48,262
Pour in about a ladle's worth.

1243
00:54:48,262 --> 00:54:51,566
Done, go.

1244
00:54:51,566 --> 00:54:53,935
[Carefully]

1245
00:54:53,935 --> 00:54:56,437
Don't be scared.

1246
00:54:56,437 --> 00:54:58,573
Good.

1247
00:54:58,573 --> 00:55:00,007
[Hee Tae's first gelato, done]

1248
00:55:00,007 --> 00:55:02,009
I want some too.

1249
00:55:06,114 --> 00:55:08,148
Always delicious.

1250
00:55:10,518 --> 00:55:11,753
[Next guest]

1251
00:55:11,753 --> 00:55:13,755
I'm going to have chocolate and hazelnut.

1252
00:55:13,755 --> 00:55:15,022
[Got it]
Chocolate and hazelnut.

1253
00:55:15,022 --> 00:55:16,924
Do it, please.

1254
00:55:16,924 --> 00:55:18,861
Remember, scrape from the top.

1255
00:55:18,861 --> 00:55:21,529
Otherwise, whoop, it all falls off.

1256
00:55:22,363 --> 00:55:25,833
[Earlier: gelato collapse from center digging]
You have to use it evenly throughout.

1257
00:55:25,833 --> 00:55:27,347
If you dig one side,

1258
00:55:27,347 --> 00:55:29,437
- it piles up on the other.
- Right, it leans to one side.

1259
00:55:29,437 --> 00:55:31,025
Help yourself with this.

1260
00:55:31,025 --> 00:55:33,574
[This time, scrape it right]
Scoop it slowly.

1261
00:55:33,574 --> 00:55:35,709
Okay.

1262
00:55:36,310 --> 00:55:39,580
[The other side is melting]

1263
00:55:39,580 --> 00:55:40,815
Why don't you scoop the other side?

1264
00:55:40,815 --> 00:55:42,884
[Dripping]
I can't watch, I'm dying here.

1265
00:55:42,884 --> 00:55:44,886
But from over there, you can't see the back.

1266
00:55:44,886 --> 00:55:49,156
You can just rotate it.

1267
00:55:50,024 --> 00:55:52,426
- Hold on a sec.
- Okay.

1268
00:55:52,426 --> 00:55:54,862
- Hold on a sec.
- Okay.

1269
00:55:54,862 --> 00:55:58,833
There's a hole forming in the gelato.

1270
00:55:58,833 --> 00:56:00,234
Yes.

1271
00:56:00,234 --> 00:56:03,641
[Warned, but the center kept caving in]

1272
00:56:03,641 --> 00:56:04,664
Yes.

1273
00:56:04,664 --> 00:56:06,674
- Take some on this side.
- Yes.

1274
00:56:06,674 --> 00:56:08,176
[Lucrezia ends up reshaping the gelato]

1275
00:56:08,176 --> 00:56:10,878
- Okay.
- Yes.

1276
00:56:10,878 --> 00:56:13,380
That was harder than I expected.

1277
00:56:14,315 --> 00:56:17,318
[Still, Hee Tae handles the topping]

1278
00:56:17,318 --> 00:56:20,555
- Chocolate and hazelnuts.
- Thank you.

1279
00:56:20,555 --> 00:56:23,023
Thank you.

1280
00:56:23,858 --> 00:56:25,703
[A guest suddenly lifts a camera]

1281
00:56:30,965 --> 00:56:32,900
[Real social media post]
[Great food, laughs, good people]

1282
00:56:32,900 --> 00:56:35,102
She posted it!

1283
00:56:37,071 --> 00:56:39,207
[Restaurant mascot in one day?]

1284
00:56:39,207 --> 00:56:41,876
I had no idea.

1285
00:56:41,876 --> 00:56:44,953
[First gelato service done]
- For now, it's okay. - Okay.

1286
00:56:45,947 --> 00:56:47,849
- That was fantastic.
- Thank you.

1287
00:56:47,849 --> 00:56:49,750
You're welcome.

1288
00:56:50,451 --> 00:56:53,421
The gelato job was my hardest part today.

1289
00:56:53,421 --> 00:56:56,991
Scooping the gelato is tricky.

1290
00:56:56,991 --> 00:57:02,429
Pulling a scoop from that mound
takes a technique, and Lu has it down.

1291
00:57:03,564 --> 00:57:07,067
I was fumbling like this.

1292
00:57:08,669 --> 00:57:12,440
[The pro, Lucrezia]
Down, down, a turn, then down.

1293
00:57:12,440 --> 00:57:14,842
Lu makes it look so cool.

1294
00:57:14,842 --> 00:57:19,647
The trick is scraping
from the melted part first.

1295
00:57:19,647 --> 00:57:25,219
You're supposed to serve it nice and dense,
but I couldn't.

1296
00:57:25,219 --> 00:57:28,823
[A bummer]
There's nowhere to practice.

1297
00:57:28,823 --> 00:57:30,125
[Hee Tae heads back to the kitchen]

1298
00:57:30,125 --> 00:57:32,559
Could you translate?

1299
00:57:33,794 --> 00:57:35,377
[Thumbs up]
Nice work.

1300
00:57:35,377 --> 00:57:36,330
Thanks.

1301
00:57:36,330 --> 00:57:37,565
Really?

1302
00:57:37,565 --> 00:57:39,133
[Head chef praises Hee Tae]

1303
00:57:39,133 --> 00:57:43,404
I can see you listen and watch closely.

1304
00:57:43,404 --> 00:57:45,606
You're taking it in and doing great.

1305
00:57:45,606 --> 00:57:46,674
- Thank you.
- Classic him.

1306
00:57:46,674 --> 00:57:48,109
Nice work.

1307
00:57:48,109 --> 00:57:50,378
[Proud]
You can tell.

1308
00:57:50,378 --> 00:57:52,588
[Diners finish up and head out]
- Thank you. - Thank you.

1309
00:57:52,588 --> 00:57:53,614
- Thanks again.
- Thank you.

1310
00:57:53,614 --> 00:57:55,832
- It was a wonderful time.
- Thank you.

1311
00:57:56,559 --> 00:57:58,185
[Deep clean mode on]
So they wipe it all down again.

1312
00:57:58,185 --> 00:58:00,922
After lunch and dinner,
they clean everything from top to bottom.

1313
00:58:00,922 --> 00:58:02,723
I see.

1314
00:58:03,424 --> 00:58:04,992
- Hee Tae.
- Yes.

1315
00:58:04,992 --> 00:58:08,596
After we close tomorrow night...

1316
00:58:08,596 --> 00:58:10,164
It's his birthday tomorrow.

1317
00:58:10,164 --> 00:58:12,300
- His birthday.
- We're going for drinks.

1318
00:58:12,300 --> 00:58:14,060
[Work outing?]
- We're going for drinks. - Really?

1319
00:58:14,060 --> 00:58:16,370
To party!

1320
00:58:16,370 --> 00:58:18,906
- I thought it was a joke at first.
- Really?

1321
00:58:18,906 --> 00:58:21,842
- He never goes to work outings.
- Right.

1322
00:58:21,842 --> 00:58:24,045
- You never go.
- He never shows up.

1323
00:58:24,045 --> 00:58:25,746
He almost never comes to other shows' outings.

1324
00:58:25,746 --> 00:58:28,783
He really hates them.

1325
00:58:28,783 --> 00:58:30,484
- We're going for drinks.
- Really?

1326
00:58:30,484 --> 00:58:32,286
[A sudden outing invite for the hater]
To party!

1327
00:58:32,286 --> 00:58:34,121
[You're coming, right?]
Yes.

1328
00:58:35,122 --> 00:58:36,891
- Yes.
- Okay.

1329
00:58:36,891 --> 00:58:38,159
Yes, yes.

1330
00:58:38,159 --> 00:58:41,162
[Little did Hee Tae know]

1331
00:58:41,162 --> 00:58:43,230
I didn't know it was that kind of outing.

1332
00:58:43,230 --> 00:58:44,257
- A work outing?
- Did you hit the club?

1333
00:58:44,257 --> 00:58:46,596
[Outing location: beyond expectations]
What? At a club?

1334
00:58:48,369 --> 00:58:50,538
[Flashy lights wrap around Hee Tae]
- So awkward. - Look at his face.

1335
00:58:50,538 --> 00:58:52,305
Look at that face.

1336
00:58:52,974 --> 00:58:54,033
So awkward.

1337
00:58:54,033 --> 00:58:57,211
He looks really uncomfortable.

1338
00:58:57,211 --> 00:58:59,347
[With bosses he met two days ago]

1339
00:58:59,347 --> 00:59:01,349
[And me, the rookie?]

1340
00:59:01,349 --> 00:59:03,884
[Losing it]

1341
00:59:03,884 --> 00:59:05,619
It's a new experience.

1342
00:59:05,619 --> 00:59:08,322
- Let's dance later.
- Dancing too?

1343
00:59:08,322 --> 00:59:09,924
[Dancing?]

1344
00:59:09,924 --> 00:59:12,026
This is my first time at a place like this.

1345
00:59:12,026 --> 00:59:13,427
It was such a shock.

1346
00:59:13,427 --> 00:59:16,885
[What's in store for him
at this crazy team dinner?]

1347
00:59:17,898 --> 00:59:19,633
[Not Jung Ji Sun, but Sunny, day 1]

1348
00:59:19,633 --> 00:59:21,902
In Chengdu, China, will Chef Jung Ji Sun

1349
00:59:21,902 --> 00:59:25,048
[Chengdu, a city hotter by night]
set the bar for rookies?

1350
00:59:25,773 --> 00:59:29,710
[Dinner service: a brief lull in the kitchen]

1351
00:59:29,710 --> 00:59:31,946
Sunny, you can sit down for a minute.

1352
00:59:31,946 --> 00:59:33,902
I'm fine.

1353
00:59:37,485 --> 00:59:41,856
[Sunny keeps tidying without a break]

1354
00:59:41,856 --> 00:59:44,347
Cleaning up neatly.

1355
00:59:48,195 --> 00:59:52,199
[Watching the hardworking rookie]

1356
00:59:52,199 --> 00:59:55,503
[Hey, look at that]

1357
00:59:55,503 --> 00:59:58,474
[Then talks to the male boss about something]

1358
00:59:59,440 --> 01:00:00,941
Sunny.

1359
01:00:00,941 --> 01:00:02,543
What's wrong?

1360
01:00:02,543 --> 01:00:04,879
[Why is he calling me?]

1361
01:00:04,879 --> 01:00:07,048
You need to learn how to hold the wok first.

1362
01:00:08,149 --> 01:00:10,546
You need to learn how to hold the wok first.

1363
01:00:11,886 --> 01:00:13,382
It's about handling the wok.

1364
01:00:14,294 --> 01:00:15,877
- How do I do it?
- Shall we try it?

1365
01:00:15,877 --> 01:00:16,899
Right away?

1366
01:00:16,899 --> 01:00:19,612
[From Prep station to Wok station?]
- I was so surprised. - What?

1367
01:00:19,612 --> 01:00:22,211
[Who is the chef that's been eyeing Sunny?]

1368
01:00:25,350 --> 01:00:28,566
[Wok station's oldest chef, Yang Tang Chun]
Oh, the most senior chef.

1369
01:00:28,566 --> 01:00:31,494
[First time at the Wok station?]
So he's basically the head chef there?

1370
01:00:31,494 --> 01:00:33,938
[Selected by the Wok station senior!]
That's right.

1371
01:00:33,938 --> 01:00:35,964
- Since she's working so hard...
- He's being kind.

1372
01:00:35,964 --> 01:00:37,977
He's giving her a chance
because she's diligent.

1373
01:00:37,977 --> 01:00:40,678
[An unexpected opportunity]

1374
01:00:41,503 --> 01:00:43,574
[Wok skills]
Wok skills seem like they'd be really tough.

1375
01:00:43,574 --> 01:00:45,360
It must be incredibly hot.

1376
01:00:46,128 --> 01:00:48,262
[1:1 lessons from the Wok senior!]
He's the head chef.

1377
01:00:48,262 --> 01:00:50,742
One-on-one with the head chef.

1378
01:00:50,742 --> 01:00:54,150
There's a wok hook on the burner rim.
You have to hook it there.

1379
01:00:54,150 --> 01:00:55,862
[Peeking]

1380
01:00:55,862 --> 01:00:59,314
Hook your thumb on the handle like this,
then grip and pull.

1381
01:01:00,358 --> 01:01:01,910
Pull it.

1382
01:01:01,910 --> 01:01:03,606
Pull and then push.

1383
01:01:03,606 --> 01:01:05,222
Pull and then push.

1384
01:01:06,022 --> 01:01:09,564
[Practicing wok skills with salt]
Salt. They practice wok skills with salt.

1385
01:01:10,214 --> 01:01:12,400
Now, you try holding the wok.

1386
01:01:13,296 --> 01:01:15,622
[The Queen of Chinese
Cuisine starts with salt wok skills]

1387
01:01:15,622 --> 01:01:17,125
How will she do?

1388
01:01:17,750 --> 01:01:19,588
[To see the rumored Kitchen junior]

1389
01:01:19,588 --> 01:01:22,230
[A crowd gathers...]
- Everyone is watching. - So much pressure.

1390
01:01:22,230 --> 01:01:24,566
- That's really pressuring.
- Cold dish people came too.

1391
01:01:24,566 --> 01:01:27,270
- But she needs to show off her skills here.
- You're right.

1392
01:01:27,270 --> 01:01:29,250
- Right on the first try.
- Exactly.

1393
01:01:29,884 --> 01:01:32,717
[Standing boldly in front of the wok]
Like this?

1394
01:01:32,717 --> 01:01:33,830
Here she goes.

1395
01:01:33,830 --> 01:01:36,070
[It's just salt, not even food...]

1396
01:01:36,070 --> 01:01:37,851
Is this right?

1397
01:01:37,851 --> 01:01:39,958
Chef Jung Ji Sun is the
Queen of Chinese Cuisine.

1398
01:01:39,958 --> 01:01:41,638
She'll succeed right away.

1399
01:01:41,638 --> 01:01:44,418
Okay, let's see.

1400
01:01:44,418 --> 01:01:48,395
[Sunny's first wok toss?]

1401
01:01:50,006 --> 01:01:51,414
[Wait, that's it?]

1402
01:01:51,414 --> 01:01:52,854
[Huh?]
Hold on.

1403
01:01:52,854 --> 01:01:55,766
[Why isn't it tossing up?]
- Wait. - What happened?

1404
01:01:55,766 --> 01:01:57,428
- You did that on purpose, right?
- Wait.

1405
01:01:57,428 --> 01:01:59,058
- You're acting.
- It's a concept.

1406
01:01:59,058 --> 01:02:00,536
- Of course she's acting.
- It's an act.

1407
01:02:00,536 --> 01:02:03,158
Wow, she's a good actress.
She's good at acting undercover.

1408
01:02:03,158 --> 01:02:04,486
Was she acting?

1409
01:02:04,486 --> 01:02:06,550
I should learn how to do that.

1410
01:02:06,550 --> 01:02:09,366
[Slightly frustrated]
Oh, man.

1411
01:02:09,366 --> 01:02:12,246
[What happened?]

1412
01:02:12,246 --> 01:02:14,614
[It's not easy, is it?]

1413
01:02:15,430 --> 01:02:17,686
[The salt won't budge]

1414
01:02:17,686 --> 01:02:19,190
[Rattling]
It's not moving at all.

1415
01:02:19,190 --> 01:02:21,014
[Rattling]

1416
01:02:21,014 --> 01:02:23,102
[The salt still won't budge]
It's not moving at all.

1417
01:02:23,102 --> 01:02:25,090
- Pulling it doesn't work here.
- What's going on?

1418
01:02:25,090 --> 01:02:27,292
[Serious]

1419
01:02:28,566 --> 01:02:30,054
Take it slow. Slowly.

1420
01:02:30,054 --> 01:02:33,314
It's hard to get it right the first time.

1421
01:02:33,974 --> 01:02:36,688
[Silence...]

1422
01:02:36,688 --> 01:02:39,193
[Totally flustered]
It's hard.

1423
01:02:40,678 --> 01:02:43,206
Wow, it's really heavy.

1424
01:02:43,206 --> 01:02:45,030
- Oh, so it was heavy.
- It's really heavy.

1425
01:02:45,030 --> 01:02:46,768
That weighs over 5kg.

1426
01:02:46,768 --> 01:02:49,238
But you have to be able to lift this...

1427
01:02:49,238 --> 01:02:52,417
You must master the wok to
reach the Wok station in five days.

1428
01:02:52,417 --> 01:02:53,673
What are you going to do?

1429
01:02:53,673 --> 01:02:55,702
[A sudden crisis]

1430
01:02:55,702 --> 01:02:57,176
"Oh, this might not work."

1431
01:02:57,176 --> 01:03:00,150
That's all I could think about.

1432
01:03:00,150 --> 01:03:02,537
It's totally different from my usual wok.

1433
01:03:03,265 --> 01:03:06,198
[The wok Chef Jung Ji Sun usually uses...]

1434
01:03:06,198 --> 01:03:10,485
[A single-handle wok with one long handle]

1435
01:03:10,485 --> 01:03:12,688
[Here they use double-handle woks]
You have to pull it.

1436
01:03:12,688 --> 01:03:14,626
You have to lift it like this.

1437
01:03:14,626 --> 01:03:15,820
It's totally different.

1438
01:03:15,820 --> 01:03:17,902
[Since it has handles on both sides]

1439
01:03:17,902 --> 01:03:20,996
[Even the way you hold it is different]
Having a handle versus not having one.

1440
01:03:20,996 --> 01:03:25,246
[Single vs. double-handle woks]
It feels heavier without the long handle.

1441
01:03:25,246 --> 01:03:27,188
It's a completely different feeling.

1442
01:03:27,188 --> 01:03:28,902
- Totally different.
- Really?

1443
01:03:28,902 --> 01:03:30,470
So, the thing is...

1444
01:03:30,470 --> 01:03:33,862
[Single-handle woks are pushed and pulled]
Don't you usually push it like this?

1445
01:03:33,862 --> 01:03:36,302
- I mean...
- Because the grip is different.

1446
01:03:36,302 --> 01:03:38,778
Double-handle woks move in a figure "8."

1447
01:03:38,778 --> 01:03:40,363
- A figure "8?"
- Figure "8?"

1448
01:03:40,363 --> 01:03:41,718
- That's hard.
- A figure "8."

1449
01:03:41,718 --> 01:03:44,358
- A figure eight up and down?
- Yes, yes.

1450
01:03:44,358 --> 01:03:46,498
We usually use single-handle woks.

1451
01:03:46,498 --> 01:03:49,878
[Sichuan/Beijing use double-handle woks]
In Sichuan and Beijing, they use those.

1452
01:03:49,878 --> 01:03:53,638
[For large-scale cooking]
That's more for long-simmering dishes.

1453
01:03:53,638 --> 01:03:56,947
[Guangdong/Shanghai use single-handle woks]
Guangdong and Shanghai are much faster.

1454
01:03:56,947 --> 01:03:59,321
[For quick a la carte dishes]
It's about infusing a smoky flavor.

1455
01:03:59,321 --> 01:04:01,014
So they use single-handle woks a lot.

1456
01:04:01,014 --> 01:04:03,174
Since it's a double-handle pan...

1457
01:04:03,174 --> 01:04:05,745
- I don't know where to apply the force.
- I see.

1458
01:04:05,745 --> 01:04:06,871
Should I do it like this?

1459
01:04:06,871 --> 01:04:08,630
[Is this right?]

1460
01:04:09,910 --> 01:04:12,294
[Confused]

1461
01:04:13,734 --> 01:04:17,430
I can't get a good grip on this.

1462
01:04:17,430 --> 01:04:20,262
[Sunny has to use muscles she's not used to]

1463
01:04:20,885 --> 01:04:25,510
[Thinking Sunny is just a beginner,
the head of the Wok station explains]

1464
01:04:25,510 --> 01:04:28,089
- Wrap it with a rag like this.
- Like this?

1465
01:04:30,006 --> 01:04:32,854
[She gives it another shot]

1466
01:04:36,790 --> 01:04:39,238
[It's supposed to bounce up like this...]

1467
01:04:39,238 --> 01:04:42,454
[It won't budge]

1468
01:04:43,062 --> 01:04:45,670
[It's not as easy as it looks...]

1469
01:04:45,670 --> 01:04:49,350
[Getting nervous too]
- Everyone... - This is so much pressure.

1470
01:04:49,350 --> 01:04:52,038
You have to do all the motions at once!

1471
01:04:52,038 --> 01:04:53,462
[Hnggh!]

1472
01:04:53,462 --> 01:04:56,518
[Feeling like a complete novice]
Try it slowly.

1473
01:04:56,518 --> 01:04:58,358
She really became a kitchen junior.

1474
01:04:58,358 --> 01:05:00,078
I bet no one suspected a thing.

1475
01:05:00,078 --> 01:05:02,055
- You're right, no one...
- No one suspected her.

1476
01:05:02,055 --> 01:05:03,811
I'm sure they didn't.

1477
01:05:05,942 --> 01:05:08,148
You must balance the strength of both hands.

1478
01:05:08,148 --> 01:05:10,662
[Watch closely, Sunny]
Look.

1479
01:05:10,662 --> 01:05:12,732
[The salt bounces perfectly]

1480
01:05:12,732 --> 01:05:16,822
Chinese stoves have that rack,
so you just have to utilize it.

1481
01:05:16,822 --> 01:05:19,512
It's about technique rather than strength.

1482
01:05:19,512 --> 01:05:22,038
[Right...]
Try to get a feel for it.

1483
01:05:22,038 --> 01:05:23,702
[Trying once more]

1484
01:05:27,698 --> 01:05:29,158
Wow.

1485
01:05:29,926 --> 01:05:32,182
It's not that I'm bad at using a wok,

1486
01:05:32,182 --> 01:05:34,148
but this wok... just wouldn't move.

1487
01:05:34,148 --> 01:05:37,126
It's so big, and I can't lift it with one hand.

1488
01:05:37,126 --> 01:05:38,981
It's quite difficult.

1489
01:05:39,607 --> 01:05:42,902
If you keep practicing, you'll get the knack.

1490
01:05:42,902 --> 01:05:45,622
If you can toss a wok,
you can work at the Wok station.

1491
01:05:45,622 --> 01:05:49,204
In our case, learning to use the wok
usually takes over a month.

1492
01:05:49,204 --> 01:05:50,895
It takes over a month?

1493
01:05:50,895 --> 01:05:52,939
It's like that because she just started.

1494
01:05:52,939 --> 01:05:54,806
It's all part of the process.

1495
01:05:54,806 --> 01:05:56,694
She has to take it slow.

1496
01:05:56,694 --> 01:05:58,158
She must take it slow.

1497
01:05:58,158 --> 01:06:00,438
- Getting the knack of this is so important.
- It's hard.

1498
01:06:00,438 --> 01:06:02,694
How can she learn the knack in five days?

1499
01:06:02,694 --> 01:06:05,622
- It's not about strength.
- But she's a boxer.

1500
01:06:05,622 --> 01:06:07,142
She's a former boxer, that's right.

1501
01:06:07,142 --> 01:06:10,069
[The ex-baseball player is asking to get hit]
So she's only got strength.

1502
01:06:14,054 --> 01:06:16,742
[Her hand won't stop the wok motion...]

1503
01:06:16,742 --> 01:06:20,390
No matter how strong you are,
it's useless if you don't know how to apply it.

1504
01:06:20,390 --> 01:06:23,270
The knack of applying force is everything.

1505
01:06:23,270 --> 01:06:25,078
I understand.

1506
01:06:25,782 --> 01:06:28,694
[A method totally different from
what she's done for 24 years...]

1507
01:06:28,694 --> 01:06:31,302
[Will she be able to master it in 5 days?]

1508
01:06:31,990 --> 01:06:34,718
[Meanwhile, at the restaurant]
The food here is quite good.

1509
01:06:35,328 --> 01:06:38,134
[One by one, the customers finish their meals]

1510
01:06:38,134 --> 01:06:41,421
[And leave]

1511
01:06:41,421 --> 01:06:42,918
[8:50 PM (10 minutes before closing)]

1512
01:06:42,918 --> 01:06:46,358
All the customers leave by 9:00 PM here.

1513
01:06:46,358 --> 01:06:50,134
- In Italy, they're just eating.
- It starts at 9.

1514
01:06:52,582 --> 01:06:54,086
Let's start cleaning!

1515
01:06:54,086 --> 01:06:55,648
So that's how they clean.

1516
01:06:55,648 --> 01:06:58,406
[The kitchen starts tidying up too]
That's right, that's right.

1517
01:06:58,406 --> 01:07:02,129
[Working hard]
Just hold it tight and push it!

1518
01:07:05,142 --> 01:07:09,078
[A massive kitchen
where everyone must pitch in]

1519
01:07:10,454 --> 01:07:14,182
[The current junior (former owner-chef)
scrubbing every corner]

1520
01:07:14,182 --> 01:07:16,868
[Full of passion]

1521
01:07:17,888 --> 01:07:22,683
[Prep and Wok station seniors
are also busy cleaning]

1522
01:07:24,638 --> 01:07:26,214
[Shoo, shoo]

1523
01:07:26,214 --> 01:07:28,454
[Quickly]

1524
01:07:29,622 --> 01:07:32,614
Okay, we're done.

1525
01:07:32,614 --> 01:07:34,624
[Day 1 business ends]
- See you tomorrow. - See you.

1526
01:07:34,624 --> 01:07:37,197
- Good job today.
- Good job.

1527
01:07:38,038 --> 01:07:40,422
[After a long first day]

1528
01:07:41,206 --> 01:07:42,454
[Morning returns to Chengdu]

1529
01:07:42,454 --> 01:07:45,132
- I've never seen this kind of place...
- I know.

1530
01:07:45,806 --> 01:07:46,856
You can see it now.

1531
01:07:46,856 --> 01:07:49,190
- Never seen a place like this.
- What's going on suddenly?

1532
01:07:49,190 --> 01:07:50,448
Just enjoy the view for now.

1533
01:07:50,448 --> 01:07:52,968
- You've been to places like this.
- I've never seen it before.

1534
01:07:52,968 --> 01:07:54,431
[7:30 AM]

1535
01:07:54,431 --> 01:07:56,393
[Going to work this early?]
She's leaving early.

1536
01:07:57,366 --> 01:08:00,070
[Glancing]

1537
01:08:03,606 --> 01:08:07,382
[Why did Sunny come out so early?]

1538
01:08:08,366 --> 01:08:11,051
Oh! That person is eating something!
Where did they buy that?

1539
01:08:11,051 --> 01:08:13,320
[In Chengdu]
Curious about their breakfast?

1540
01:08:13,320 --> 01:08:15,748
So I went out early to eat breakfast.

1541
01:08:15,748 --> 01:08:18,953
[Chengdu locals start the day with a warm meal]
It's a chef thing.

1542
01:08:18,953 --> 01:08:21,815
[Well-developed breakfast culture]
Visitors are curious about what locals eat.

1543
01:08:21,815 --> 01:08:23,585
It looks delicious.

1544
01:08:23,585 --> 01:08:25,584
Over here. Ni hao.

1545
01:08:25,584 --> 01:08:26,839
Table for four, please.

1546
01:08:26,839 --> 01:08:29,126
[Breakfast Fairy Sunny
gets out early for a meal]

1547
01:08:29,126 --> 01:08:32,787
[Scanning the menu]
Dumplings, they have dumplings.

1548
01:08:33,910 --> 01:08:37,030
[Starting to order]
- One order of jiucai dumplings. - Small?

1549
01:08:37,030 --> 01:08:39,243
[Adding to the order!]
Yes, a small one.

1550
01:08:39,998 --> 01:08:42,694
[Is that all?]

1551
01:08:42,694 --> 01:08:46,102
[Adding even more!]
And one Sour Vegetable and Pork Noodles.

1552
01:08:46,102 --> 01:08:48,950
[Three dishes for one person]
- A small one? - Yes, small.

1553
01:08:48,950 --> 01:08:51,846
[She finishes ordering and waits, but...]

1554
01:08:52,630 --> 01:08:55,558
[Sunny suddenly leaves?]
Huh? Why is she leaving in such a hurry?

1555
01:08:56,358 --> 01:08:59,249
[Where is she going before the food is out?]

1556
01:08:59,249 --> 01:09:01,414
[The Breakfast Fairy visits another restaurant]
Ni hao.

1557
01:09:01,414 --> 01:09:04,150
[She already ordered breakfast...]
Wait, breakfast...

1558
01:09:04,150 --> 01:09:06,381
[Scanning the second menu]
Soy sauce meat steamed buns.

1559
01:09:07,830 --> 01:09:09,606
- What would you like?
- This and this.

1560
01:09:09,606 --> 01:09:11,750
Give me one order of shaomai, too.

1561
01:09:11,750 --> 01:09:13,526
[Suddenly holding a bag of breakfast food]

1562
01:09:14,854 --> 01:09:18,950
[Returning with full hands before the feast]

1563
01:09:19,419 --> 01:09:21,451
[Unboxing the breakfast bag]
This is...

1564
01:09:21,451 --> 01:09:25,067
I learned when I first went to school in China.

1565
01:09:25,067 --> 01:09:28,555
[Dumpling filled with glutinous rice]
Glutinous rice shaomai.

1566
01:09:28,555 --> 01:09:30,875
[The food arrives]

1567
01:09:30,875 --> 01:09:32,455
Oh, my.

1568
01:09:33,102 --> 01:09:35,723
[Wonton]
This looks delicious.

1569
01:09:35,723 --> 01:09:36,827
[Sour Vegetable and Pork Noodles]

1570
01:09:36,827 --> 01:09:38,475
It looks so good.

1571
01:09:38,475 --> 01:09:41,691
[Dumplings]
Wait, this is so much food.

1572
01:09:41,691 --> 01:09:44,040
Wow, there are so many in here!

1573
01:09:44,715 --> 01:09:45,867
Is this one different?

1574
01:09:45,867 --> 01:09:48,142
[It's a new dish]
It's called jiucai.

1575
01:09:48,817 --> 01:09:50,395
[I'll stop here...]
It looks delicious.

1576
01:09:50,395 --> 01:09:51,627
- It's chives.
- I'm hungry.

1577
01:09:51,627 --> 01:09:55,631
Whenever I come to China,
I usually visit about three restaurants.

1578
01:09:56,680 --> 01:09:58,136
Three restaurants for one meal?

1579
01:09:58,136 --> 01:10:00,320
- Yes.
- Three?

1580
01:10:00,320 --> 01:10:01,848
[Witness to her food tours]
Actually...

1581
01:10:01,848 --> 01:10:04,264
- Ji Sun actually...
- You visit three places for breakfast?

1582
01:10:04,264 --> 01:10:06,408
If the crew says they aren't ready yet,

1583
01:10:06,408 --> 01:10:08,680
she just tells them,
"I'll be right back and go eat."

1584
01:10:08,680 --> 01:10:10,984
- You do it for research, right?
- Yes, for research.

1585
01:10:10,984 --> 01:10:14,476
[Breakfast Fairy's obsession with taste]
She's truly passionate about food.

1586
01:10:15,624 --> 01:10:18,600
[Heading to work after a hearty breakfast]

1587
01:10:18,600 --> 01:10:19,702
She's late, she's late!

1588
01:10:19,702 --> 01:10:21,240
I was taking it too easy.

1589
01:10:21,240 --> 01:10:22,820
[Hurrying to work]

1590
01:10:22,820 --> 01:10:24,880
Good morning.

1591
01:10:24,880 --> 01:10:27,650
[Ten minutes before morning assembly]
Morning assembly.

1592
01:10:29,334 --> 01:10:33,480
[The staff members come out one by one]

1593
01:10:33,480 --> 01:10:34,760
[Sitting in small groups]

1594
01:10:34,760 --> 01:10:37,650
Why is "Squid Game" being mentioned here?

1595
01:10:37,650 --> 01:10:40,450
[9:00 AM]
Is someone going to die? How many?

1596
01:10:40,450 --> 01:10:41,560
- After a day?
- Exactly.

1597
01:10:41,560 --> 01:10:44,198
- They must disappear.
- Why do they keep mentioning "Squid Game?"

1598
01:10:44,198 --> 01:10:46,770
Let's line up in two rows here too.

1599
01:10:46,770 --> 01:10:48,720
[09:00 AM]
- Good morning. - Good morning.

1600
01:10:48,720 --> 01:10:50,100
Doing this every day is...

1601
01:10:50,100 --> 01:10:51,842
[Swoosh]
- We do it every day. - Really?

1602
01:10:51,842 --> 01:10:53,380
[The owner begins the roll call]
- It's like school. - Yi Qiong.

1603
01:10:53,380 --> 01:10:55,540
Lin Ji Dong, Zhang Chun Yuan, Fu Jian Wei.

1604
01:10:55,540 --> 01:10:56,640
- Cai Jun.
- Dao.

1605
01:10:56,640 --> 01:10:57,750
- Jiang Qi Chang.
- Dao.

1606
01:10:57,750 --> 01:10:58,930
- Fu Nan.
- Dao.

1607
01:10:58,930 --> 01:11:01,360
[Staring intently]
Liu Xin Jie, Liu Gui Hua, Guo Yu Hua.

1608
01:11:01,360 --> 01:11:03,670
Mao Zheng, Peng Di.

1609
01:11:03,670 --> 01:11:06,660
Cai Yan Dao, Zhang Qiang.

1610
01:11:06,660 --> 01:11:08,120
- Zhao Xiu Gang.
- Dao.

1611
01:11:08,120 --> 01:11:09,940
- Xu Jian Kai.
- Dao.

1612
01:11:11,482 --> 01:11:14,249
[The senior chefs' names are ending]
Guo Yu Hua, Mao Zheng. Peng Di.

1613
01:11:14,249 --> 01:11:15,617
Dao.

1614
01:11:15,617 --> 01:11:16,755
[Swoosh]
Sunny?

1615
01:11:16,755 --> 01:11:18,593
- Why didn't he call her?
- He didn't call me.

1616
01:11:18,593 --> 01:11:20,450
Why isn't he calling her name all of a sudden?

1617
01:11:20,450 --> 01:11:23,880
[Why aren't you calling our Sunny?]
Today's lunch reservations include...

1618
01:11:23,880 --> 01:11:25,750
There are six tables...

1619
01:11:25,750 --> 01:11:27,160
Is she eliminated?

1620
01:11:27,160 --> 01:11:28,718
Is she eliminated?

1621
01:11:28,718 --> 01:11:30,340
[Player 10 Sunny: Failed]
Was she just eliminated from "Squid Game?"

1622
01:11:30,340 --> 01:11:32,870
Maybe it's because she ate too much breakfast.

1623
01:11:32,870 --> 01:11:33,970
No...

1624
01:11:33,970 --> 01:11:36,310
I think he cut her after
seeing her wok skills yesterday.

1625
01:11:36,310 --> 01:11:38,020
Right, she's gone after the wok session.

1626
01:11:38,020 --> 01:11:40,943
I think she was eliminated
after the wok cooking.

1627
01:11:41,720 --> 01:11:46,600
[The owner was busy with the assembly...]
Whether there are customers or not...

1628
01:11:46,600 --> 01:11:49,780
[He finally notices Sunny]
You shouldn't let your guard down.

1629
01:11:49,780 --> 01:11:52,520
Oh... is there someone I didn't call?

1630
01:11:52,520 --> 01:11:55,510
[Noticing]
I didn't write the name down.

1631
01:11:55,510 --> 01:11:58,550
Oh, he forgot the name.

1632
01:11:58,550 --> 01:12:01,030
Sunny, I'm sorry.

1633
01:12:01,030 --> 01:12:02,870
The thing is...

1634
01:12:02,870 --> 01:12:04,500
Today is April 1st.

1635
01:12:04,500 --> 01:12:07,436
I didn't write Sunny in the April column.

1636
01:12:07,436 --> 01:12:10,240
He said he was supposed to rewrite it
for the new month but forgot...

1637
01:12:10,240 --> 01:12:13,190
- It's a new month.
- The list hasn't been updated.

1638
01:12:13,190 --> 01:12:14,550
- That can happen.
- Right.

1639
01:12:14,550 --> 01:12:15,750
I won't nag you anymore.

1640
01:12:15,750 --> 01:12:16,980
Let's hurry up and get ready.

1641
01:12:16,980 --> 01:12:19,110
- Let's do the chant.
- Be elegant.

1642
01:12:19,110 --> 01:12:21,380
Be elegant, work properly.

1643
01:12:21,380 --> 01:12:24,366
Service and customers come first!

1644
01:12:27,250 --> 01:12:29,024
He didn't know

1645
01:12:29,024 --> 01:12:31,400
because I wasn't on the attendance sheet.

1646
01:12:31,400 --> 01:12:33,400
[Left out without a name call]

1647
01:12:33,400 --> 01:12:35,953
Ji Sun...

1648
01:12:35,953 --> 01:12:38,992
I was going to speak up about my name.

1649
01:12:38,992 --> 01:12:41,626
I was going to say it at the very end.

1650
01:12:41,626 --> 01:12:42,925
That I'm here...

1651
01:12:42,925 --> 01:12:44,660
- Seriously.
- You actually care about that.

1652
01:12:44,660 --> 01:12:46,600
- You're taking it to heart.
- Of course.

1653
01:12:46,600 --> 01:12:49,026
It's disappointing, you know.

1654
01:12:49,026 --> 01:12:50,425
[After the morning assembly...]

1655
01:12:50,425 --> 01:12:52,930
Today is April 1st.

1656
01:12:52,930 --> 01:12:55,720
I called Sunny's name before,
but I realized she wasn't on the list.

1657
01:12:55,720 --> 01:12:58,400
I keep forgetting her name.

1658
01:12:58,400 --> 01:13:00,260
- Sunny.
- Sunny.

1659
01:13:00,260 --> 01:13:02,290
[Even the usually cold-headed owner]

1660
01:13:02,290 --> 01:13:04,530
Sunny, Sunny.

1661
01:13:04,530 --> 01:13:05,750
- Sunny.
- He's trying.

1662
01:13:05,750 --> 01:13:08,545
[The owner keeps calling Sunny's name]
He's cute.

1663
01:13:08,920 --> 01:13:10,960
[9:20 AM]

1664
01:13:11,860 --> 01:13:17,854
[The kitchen is busy preparing for business]

1665
01:13:19,596 --> 01:13:24,370
[Day 2 Preparation]
This card gets you a 100-yuan discount.

1666
01:13:24,370 --> 01:13:26,790
[Day 2 Preparation]
The plan...

1667
01:13:26,790 --> 01:13:29,600
First, I shouldn't say, "I'll do this" first.

1668
01:13:29,600 --> 01:13:31,600
I should just do what they give me.

1669
01:13:31,600 --> 01:13:34,000
I'll try that first.

1670
01:13:34,000 --> 01:13:36,777
[Day 2 Strategy: Stay natural undercover]
Let's just do what I'm told.

1671
01:13:37,730 --> 01:13:40,054
[Starting with chopping tomatoes]
- Tomatoes. - Tomatoes.

1672
01:13:41,300 --> 01:13:42,920
Chinese cuisine uses a lot of tomatoes.

1673
01:13:42,920 --> 01:13:44,500
Tomato and egg stir-fry.

1674
01:13:44,500 --> 01:13:45,817
Oh, that looks delicious.

1675
01:13:45,817 --> 01:13:47,650
[Main ingredient for tomato and egg stir-fry]

1676
01:13:47,650 --> 01:13:50,301
Tomato and egg stir-fry is so good.

1677
01:13:51,030 --> 01:13:53,750
[Slice, slice]

1678
01:13:53,750 --> 01:13:57,024
[Her usual habits naturally come out]

1679
01:13:58,160 --> 01:14:00,704
First, cut this part off.

1680
01:14:01,320 --> 01:14:05,380
[Prep station No. 2 Liu Dai Yu shows her first]
- Throw this away. - Throw it away. And then...

1681
01:14:05,380 --> 01:14:07,540
[Slice]

1682
01:14:07,540 --> 01:14:10,514
Just dice it.

1683
01:14:12,482 --> 01:14:15,620
[Low difficulty: Prepping tomatoes]
- Dice them? - Yes. Just dice it like this.

1684
01:14:15,620 --> 01:14:17,680
[Sunny's turn]

1685
01:14:17,680 --> 01:14:19,590
First, I'll remove the stems.

1686
01:14:19,590 --> 01:14:21,320
Did you peel the skin already?

1687
01:14:21,320 --> 01:14:22,390
Yes, I did.

1688
01:14:23,684 --> 01:14:27,654
[Dicing the tomatoes]

1689
01:14:30,294 --> 01:14:32,944
[Satisfied]
Good. You can do it like this.

1690
01:14:39,927 --> 01:14:43,497
[Senior Liu leaves after giving instructions]

1691
01:14:43,497 --> 01:14:45,851
[Chop, chop, chop]

1692
01:14:45,851 --> 01:14:48,027
- You're doing it slowly on purpose, right?
- Exactly.

1693
01:14:48,027 --> 01:14:49,093
I'm going slow on purpose.

1694
01:14:49,093 --> 01:14:50,297
- Because...
- You're still...

1695
01:14:50,297 --> 01:14:53,373
I know how fast Ji Sun's knife work really is.

1696
01:14:53,373 --> 01:14:54,717
Exactly.

1697
01:14:55,657 --> 01:14:57,387
[Spots Sunny]

1698
01:14:57,387 --> 01:14:59,407
[Is she doing okay?]

1699
01:15:00,077 --> 01:15:02,967
[Prep Station Chief Tang Wei
comes to check the progress]

1700
01:15:03,607 --> 01:15:07,597
[Let's see...]

1701
01:15:08,857 --> 01:15:11,327
[She slices so skillfully that
before she knows it...]

1702
01:15:11,327 --> 01:15:13,367
[A huge pile]

1703
01:15:14,237 --> 01:15:16,717
[Satisfied]

1704
01:15:18,127 --> 01:15:21,964
[Cleaning up as she goes]
She's cleaning the board and tidying up.

1705
01:15:21,964 --> 01:15:23,247
Did you have to keep doing that?

1706
01:15:23,247 --> 01:15:24,767
- Like that?
- You have to scrape it like that.

1707
01:15:24,767 --> 01:15:26,647
Did they teach you that there?

1708
01:15:26,647 --> 01:15:27,977
Did they show you how to do that?

1709
01:15:27,977 --> 01:15:29,887
- No...
- I don't think they did.

1710
01:15:29,887 --> 01:15:31,447
- That's just...
- It's a habit.

1711
01:15:31,447 --> 01:15:33,296
- Right.
- She's doing it out of habit.

1712
01:15:34,537 --> 01:15:36,907
[Scrape]

1713
01:15:36,907 --> 01:15:38,807
[Wait... what?]

1714
01:15:38,807 --> 01:15:40,297
[Scrape...]

1715
01:15:40,297 --> 01:15:43,287
[Starts dicing tofu without a break]
- After tomatoes, it's tofu. - Tofu.

1716
01:15:43,287 --> 01:15:47,661
Just try to keep the spacing even.

1717
01:15:47,661 --> 01:15:50,822
[Task understood]

1718
01:15:50,822 --> 01:15:52,157
[Slicing the tofu]
For Mapo Tofu?

1719
01:15:52,157 --> 01:15:55,718
The tofu is still warm since it just came out.

1720
01:15:57,166 --> 01:15:59,567
[Prep Station Chief Tang Wei]
Right. Just slice it like this.

1721
01:15:59,567 --> 01:16:01,327
[Immediate pass]
Good.

1722
01:16:01,327 --> 01:16:03,117
[Slice]

1723
01:16:05,447 --> 01:16:08,527
It's going to be obvious
that she's good at this.

1724
01:16:08,527 --> 01:16:10,557
You can't hide your knife work.

1725
01:16:10,557 --> 01:16:14,927
Keeping the spacing
consistent isn't easy for beginners.

1726
01:16:16,807 --> 01:16:19,197
[Tofu is done]

1727
01:16:19,947 --> 01:16:22,317
[She's fast]

1728
01:16:22,967 --> 01:16:24,697
[Looking around]

1729
01:16:24,697 --> 01:16:27,607
[Looking around]

1730
01:16:27,607 --> 01:16:30,733
- Why?
- Is there any more work...?

1731
01:16:31,386 --> 01:16:33,807
- What?
- I asked if there's more work...

1732
01:16:33,807 --> 01:16:35,417
Any more work?

1733
01:16:35,417 --> 01:16:37,147
- You want Sunny to do it?
- Yeah.

1734
01:16:37,147 --> 01:16:40,004
We're going to slice more chili peppers!

1735
01:16:40,004 --> 01:16:41,948
[Is that so?]

1736
01:16:41,948 --> 01:16:44,587
[Now it's time for chili peppers]
Slicing chili peppers diagonally.

1737
01:16:44,587 --> 01:16:47,177
[With a massive amount...]
What is this? Look at that.

1738
01:16:47,177 --> 01:16:49,630
[More chili peppers found]
- Everything is in bulk. - Exactly.

1739
01:16:50,317 --> 01:16:52,767
[Panic]
They basically use sacks as a unit.

1740
01:16:52,767 --> 01:16:53,837
Yeah.

1741
01:16:53,837 --> 01:16:55,547
[Refill time]

1742
01:16:57,017 --> 01:17:00,007
[Another pile]

1743
01:17:04,137 --> 01:17:05,897
[Glancing]
Here comes Number Three.

1744
01:17:05,897 --> 01:17:09,207
I'll give some of this to Sunny.

1745
01:17:09,207 --> 01:17:11,577
[Piling up]
- Our MZ... - He keeps bringing things.

1746
01:17:11,577 --> 01:17:14,287
- That's a lot.
- Yes.

1747
01:17:14,287 --> 01:17:16,567
[Pupil earthquake]

1748
01:17:17,407 --> 01:17:21,007
[Just slice it for now]

1749
01:17:22,107 --> 01:17:24,853
Are the chili peppers all done?

1750
01:17:29,327 --> 01:17:31,407
[Stops]
What is she doing now?

1751
01:17:32,686 --> 01:17:35,327
She's slicing green onions.

1752
01:17:35,327 --> 01:17:38,247
[Slicing something else already...]
- You'll get used to it. - Yes.

1753
01:17:38,247 --> 01:17:40,196
She should keep slicing.

1754
01:17:41,947 --> 01:17:43,837
[Hahaha]

1755
01:17:45,677 --> 01:17:48,364
[A 24-year veteran chef slicing with ease...]
Wow, look at that...

1756
01:17:48,364 --> 01:17:50,280
It must be pretty obvious.

1757
01:17:52,167 --> 01:17:53,527
[Let's see]

1758
01:17:54,363 --> 01:17:55,947
[Slicing green onions is quite hard...]

1759
01:17:55,947 --> 01:17:58,347
Here it comes. Let's see the green onions.

1760
01:17:58,347 --> 01:18:00,367
Oh?

1761
01:18:00,367 --> 01:18:03,257
- That's it. Slice it like that.
- She got praised.

1762
01:18:03,257 --> 01:18:05,767
[Thumbs up]

1763
01:18:05,767 --> 01:18:09,348
You have to use both hands. Both hands.

1764
01:18:09,348 --> 01:18:11,958
[Our Kitchen junior is the best]
You have to use both hands.

1765
01:18:12,812 --> 01:18:16,157
[Winning the prep chief's heart on day two]
Everyone's getting a thumbs-up.

1766
01:18:16,157 --> 01:18:17,768
You have to give a double thumbs-up.

1767
01:18:17,768 --> 01:18:22,007
Wait, leave that alone. Let Sunny do it.

1768
01:18:22,007 --> 01:18:23,997
She's so good they keep giving her more.

1769
01:18:23,997 --> 01:18:25,677
- They keep piling it on me.
- They must think she's a machine.

1770
01:18:25,677 --> 01:18:27,307
They keep giving her things.

1771
01:18:27,307 --> 01:18:30,217
[Likes being recognized]
If you're good, they give you more...

1772
01:18:30,217 --> 01:18:34,036
Wait, leave that alone. Let Sunny do it.

1773
01:18:36,537 --> 01:18:38,047
Wow.

1774
01:18:40,287 --> 01:18:43,097
[Gaining the prep station chief's trust]

1775
01:18:43,967 --> 01:18:46,907
[Sunny even takes over
the senior chef's ingredients]

1776
01:18:48,347 --> 01:18:50,792
[Trapped in knife work hell...]
You'll chop the bell peppers.

1777
01:18:51,687 --> 01:18:54,157
[Becoming the prep station's rookie...]
Chop the green onions.

1778
01:18:54,797 --> 01:18:57,474
[Our Kitchen junior is doing great]

1779
01:18:57,474 --> 01:18:58,900
They were giving me so many tasks today,

1780
01:18:58,900 --> 01:19:01,167
- as if I'm a regular employee.
- But you are an employee.

1781
01:19:01,167 --> 01:19:04,456
Why do they keep giving me more work?

1782
01:19:04,456 --> 01:19:05,529
They're leaving it all to me?

1783
01:19:05,529 --> 01:19:08,907
I was flustered
when they asked me to do this...

1784
01:19:08,907 --> 01:19:10,920
But I also felt a bit proud.

1785
01:19:11,517 --> 01:19:13,757
First flustered, then a bit proud.

1786
01:19:13,757 --> 01:19:16,667
- They gave it to you because you're good.
- It means you're good.

1787
01:19:16,667 --> 01:19:20,007
[The prep station chief hands over
the next ingredient]

1788
01:19:24,167 --> 01:19:27,247
[A sigh-inducing ingredient?]

1789
01:19:27,247 --> 01:19:28,427
What is it? What is it?

1790
01:19:28,427 --> 01:19:31,147
- Oh, frogs.
- Oh, here they are. Frogs.

1791
01:19:31,147 --> 01:19:34,567
[Dizzying]
Ugh...

1792
01:19:34,567 --> 01:19:36,347
[Argh!]

1793
01:19:36,347 --> 01:19:38,367
Okay.

1794
01:19:38,367 --> 01:19:39,847
Okay.

1795
01:19:39,847 --> 01:19:41,756
Don't worry. It's okay.

1796
01:19:41,756 --> 01:19:42,789
Okay.

1797
01:19:42,789 --> 01:19:44,747
[(Not) Okay...]

1798
01:19:44,747 --> 01:19:47,917
[There, there, our Kitchen junior]

1799
01:19:47,917 --> 01:19:49,497
They give me too many frogs.

1800
01:19:49,497 --> 01:19:51,867
They give them to me morning and night.

1801
01:19:51,867 --> 01:19:53,887
[Q. Are there any ingredients you want?]

1802
01:19:53,887 --> 01:19:55,074
Does it matter?

1803
01:19:55,074 --> 01:19:57,192
As long as it's not frogs.

1804
01:19:57,192 --> 01:19:58,347
[I'll do anything but frogs]

1805
01:19:58,347 --> 01:20:00,077
- Anything but frogs.
- Because they move.

1806
01:20:00,077 --> 01:20:02,171
You prep them every day?

1807
01:20:04,727 --> 01:20:05,947
[Sniffle]

1808
01:20:05,947 --> 01:20:08,367
[But since we've met before...]

1809
01:20:08,367 --> 01:20:10,007
[Chop]
People eat a lot of frogs here.

1810
01:20:10,007 --> 01:20:12,087
[Chop]
Frogs are a popular menu item.

1811
01:20:12,087 --> 01:20:14,827
[Power cutting]

1812
01:20:15,417 --> 01:20:17,599
[It's flying away!]
- Oh my. - Oh my goodness.

1813
01:20:17,599 --> 01:20:20,223
[Frog escapes]
It's angry, it's angry!

1814
01:20:20,223 --> 01:20:22,407
[Former boxer's arm strength]

1815
01:20:22,407 --> 01:20:24,727
It's okay. You can just throw it away.

1816
01:20:25,896 --> 01:20:28,287
[Prep station No.2 Liu Dai Yu]
She's less scared than yesterday.

1817
01:20:28,287 --> 01:20:30,959
[Prep station Chief Tang Wei]
She's not even nervous.

1818
01:20:30,959 --> 01:20:32,111
That's right.

1819
01:20:32,111 --> 01:20:34,895
[Relatively calm]

1820
01:20:35,503 --> 01:20:38,935
[Prep station Chief Tang Wei: Getting better]
She's getting better every day.

1821
01:20:39,919 --> 01:20:42,127
[Thinking...]

1822
01:20:42,127 --> 01:20:44,461
Once you finish this, I'll show you how to prep

1823
01:20:44,461 --> 01:20:46,331
- more difficult ingredients.
- Yes, sir.

1824
01:20:46,331 --> 01:20:48,783
[Resigned...]
He'll show her something new after this.

1825
01:20:48,783 --> 01:20:49,947
It never ends.

1826
01:20:49,947 --> 01:20:51,311
[Endless knife work hell...]

1827
01:20:51,311 --> 01:20:54,095
[Sighs]

1828
01:20:54,095 --> 01:20:57,279
[No match for 500 servings of ingredients]

1829
01:20:57,279 --> 01:21:00,063
[Finished prepping a mountain of frogs]
Okay.

1830
01:21:00,063 --> 01:21:03,375
[To Sunny, who is cleaning up the frogs]

1831
01:21:03,375 --> 01:21:04,559
[Sliding in...]

1832
01:21:04,559 --> 01:21:05,999
What now?

1833
01:21:05,999 --> 01:21:08,095
[Next ingredient is coming]
What is it this time?

1834
01:21:08,095 --> 01:21:09,459
What is it?

1835
01:21:10,159 --> 01:21:11,467
[Scarier than frogs?]
What is it?

1836
01:21:11,467 --> 01:21:13,657
- It's not bugs, is it?
- What is it?

1837
01:21:13,657 --> 01:21:15,151
[What's the next ingredient?]

1838
01:21:15,151 --> 01:21:17,103
[Chicken?]

1839
01:21:17,103 --> 01:21:18,207
- Chicken.
- Chicken.

1840
01:21:18,207 --> 01:21:20,022
- Why is it so big?
- Look at those legs.

1841
01:21:20,022 --> 01:21:21,199
The chicken is huge.

1842
01:21:21,199 --> 01:21:23,358
[As big as a cleaver]
That's a chicken, not a turkey?

1843
01:21:23,358 --> 01:21:24,943
[Doubting his eyes]
Yes.

1844
01:21:24,943 --> 01:21:26,557
- It's really big.
- It's massive.

1845
01:21:26,557 --> 01:21:29,855
We'll prep the parts for Gongbao Jiding.

1846
01:21:29,855 --> 01:21:32,431
- Oh, Gongbao Jiding!
- That's right.

1847
01:21:32,431 --> 01:21:33,951
Gongbao Jiding.

1848
01:21:33,951 --> 01:21:36,495
[Diced chicken with]
Chicken and various other ingredients

1849
01:21:36,495 --> 01:21:39,823
[stir-fried with chili, veg, and peanuts]
are cut into perfect cubes.

1850
01:21:39,823 --> 01:21:44,447
[The ultimate addictive Sichuan dish]

1851
01:21:45,871 --> 01:21:47,647
[Gongbao Jiding, familiar to us all]

1852
01:21:47,647 --> 01:21:50,383
I love Gongbao Jiding.

1853
01:21:50,383 --> 01:21:52,271
- Oh, it looks delicious.
- That looks good.

1854
01:21:52,271 --> 01:21:53,930
Savory and salty.

1855
01:21:55,199 --> 01:21:57,519
[Prep station Chief's demonstration]

1856
01:21:58,287 --> 01:22:01,759
There's a big bone on this side.

1857
01:22:01,759 --> 01:22:03,855
[Clean deboning is key]
A big bone.

1858
01:22:03,855 --> 01:22:06,244
- It's really hard for beginners.
- You cut it like this.

1859
01:22:06,244 --> 01:22:07,663
- It's not easy.
- With the knife...

1860
01:22:07,663 --> 01:22:09,817
Cut the joint with the knife and push.

1861
01:22:09,817 --> 01:22:12,847
[Bone pops out]
If you do this, the bone comes out.

1862
01:22:12,847 --> 01:22:14,591
You have to be careful here.

1863
01:22:14,591 --> 01:22:17,679
There's a small piece of bone right behind it.

1864
01:22:17,679 --> 01:22:21,220
You can see a small piece of bone.

1865
01:22:21,220 --> 01:22:23,894
Similarly, push it with the knife.

1866
01:22:23,894 --> 01:22:27,162
[Pushing the bone with a cleaver]
Push it with the knife.

1867
01:22:29,327 --> 01:22:32,355
Cut off the remaining bone at the bottom.

1868
01:22:33,071 --> 01:22:36,831
[Deboning: harder than simple chopping]

1869
01:22:36,831 --> 01:22:38,511
Even remove the skin.

1870
01:22:38,511 --> 01:22:40,077
See? Now only the meat is left.

1871
01:22:40,077 --> 01:22:42,329
Every single piece of bone is gone.

1872
01:22:42,329 --> 01:22:44,095
- It's all meat now.
- Yes.

1873
01:22:44,095 --> 01:22:46,831
[Smirk]

1874
01:22:47,471 --> 01:22:50,407
[Chicken prep is basic at culinary school]
That's a basic skill at school.

1875
01:22:50,407 --> 01:22:54,841
If there's a drumstick on top,
you know the part attached to it?

1876
01:22:54,841 --> 01:22:56,187
The thigh meat.

1877
01:22:56,187 --> 01:22:59,711
It comes with the thigh meat,
so you have to cut that first.

1878
01:22:59,711 --> 01:23:02,064
[Already knows it well]
The prep work is similar.

1879
01:23:03,279 --> 01:23:05,817
[Confident]

1880
01:23:05,817 --> 01:23:10,575
[But to Tang Wei, Sunny is a novice]
If you cut the joint part like this,

1881
01:23:10,575 --> 01:23:13,263
[Explaining enthusiastically]
you just have to slice it gently.

1882
01:23:13,263 --> 01:23:16,658
[Listening intently]

1883
01:23:16,658 --> 01:23:18,159
[Now it's Sunny's turn]
Give it a try.

1884
01:23:18,159 --> 01:23:19,656
Will she succeed?

1885
01:23:21,775 --> 01:23:23,647
[Skilfully cracking the bone]

1886
01:23:24,479 --> 01:23:27,583
[One bone deboned in an instant]

1887
01:23:27,583 --> 01:23:28,991
Very good.

1888
01:23:28,991 --> 01:23:30,911
As expected.

1889
01:23:30,911 --> 01:23:32,495
[Impressed twice]
Nice.

1890
01:23:34,367 --> 01:23:37,231
[The second one is also a breeze]
That's it. Do it like that.

1891
01:23:37,231 --> 01:23:40,607
[She's... too good?]

1892
01:23:40,607 --> 01:23:42,863
[Forgetting her undercover identity]

1893
01:23:42,863 --> 01:23:44,847
[Successfully deboned the last bone]

1894
01:23:44,847 --> 01:23:46,335
Good.

1895
01:23:46,335 --> 01:23:48,098
- Good.
- But anyway, this...

1896
01:23:48,098 --> 01:23:49,730
[Surprised by her skill]
Since she did it so smoothly,

1897
01:23:49,730 --> 01:23:50,857
he must have been surprised.

1898
01:23:50,857 --> 01:23:52,255
Is there anything else to prep?

1899
01:23:52,255 --> 01:23:54,895
[Relieved]
No more.

1900
01:23:54,895 --> 01:23:56,407
[Finally free]

1901
01:23:58,322 --> 01:24:00,075
[Or not!]
Now we're going to slice fish.

1902
01:24:00,075 --> 01:24:01,227
[What?]

1903
01:24:01,227 --> 01:24:02,383
Fish?

1904
01:24:02,383 --> 01:24:04,079
There's more?

1905
01:24:04,079 --> 01:24:06,031
Since there are 160 items.

1906
01:24:06,031 --> 01:24:08,493
[Ready to slice everything on earth]
Since there are 160 menu items.

1907
01:24:08,493 --> 01:24:09,677
Fish?

1908
01:24:09,677 --> 01:24:11,023
[Clenching teeth]
- Yes. - Okay.

1909
01:24:11,023 --> 01:24:13,423
[Knife work never ends]
She's clenching her teeth.

1910
01:24:14,057 --> 01:24:15,663
They don't give her a moment to rest.

1911
01:24:15,663 --> 01:24:17,298
[And so, Sunny...]
Keeps going and going.

1912
01:24:18,335 --> 01:24:21,071
I guess the first day was easy.

1913
01:24:21,071 --> 01:24:22,399
She's filleting the fish.

1914
01:24:22,399 --> 01:24:24,874
Even fish for the soup...

1915
01:24:27,583 --> 01:24:30,687
[Grandma visits as Sunny levels up]
The owner is here.

1916
01:24:30,687 --> 01:24:32,911
[Peek]

1917
01:24:32,911 --> 01:24:34,807
- It's a bit thick.
- It's thick?

1918
01:24:34,807 --> 01:24:35,947
The top part is a bit thick.

1919
01:24:35,947 --> 01:24:38,175
- Make it thinner.
- Make it thinner.

1920
01:24:38,175 --> 01:24:39,947
- Tilt the knife.
- Grandma is here.

1921
01:24:39,947 --> 01:24:41,867
- Tilt the knife more.
- Tilt it, tilt it more.

1922
01:24:41,867 --> 01:24:43,439
Since everyone is chiming in...

1923
01:24:43,439 --> 01:24:44,607
[Ugh...]
The knife...

1924
01:24:44,607 --> 01:24:47,711
- Tilt the knife...
- Tilt the knife...

1925
01:24:47,711 --> 01:24:50,431
[A dizzying surround-sound lecture...]

1926
01:24:50,431 --> 01:24:52,175
Man, this is so distracting.

1927
01:24:52,175 --> 01:24:54,863
[Brainwashed]
- Tilt the knife. - Yes, tilt the knife.

1928
01:24:54,863 --> 01:24:58,217
[All eyes are on her...]

1929
01:24:58,217 --> 01:25:00,647
Grandma is right.
The bottom part is a bit thick.

1930
01:25:00,647 --> 01:25:02,271
Even the owner is giving feedback.

1931
01:25:02,271 --> 01:25:04,751
[Tilt his body]

1932
01:25:04,751 --> 01:25:06,127
[Exit]

1933
01:25:06,847 --> 01:25:08,895
[Trying again]
Make the top part thinner.

1934
01:25:08,895 --> 01:25:10,599
That's it!

1935
01:25:12,641 --> 01:25:14,335
[The knife is tilted almost to the floor]

1936
01:25:14,335 --> 01:25:17,817
Wow, she's really filleting it now.

1937
01:25:17,817 --> 01:25:20,623
[Our Kitchen junior]
She's a fast learner, right?

1938
01:25:20,623 --> 01:25:22,351
Yes, she learns quickly.

1939
01:25:22,351 --> 01:25:24,457
Right, right.

1940
01:25:24,457 --> 01:25:27,277
[Sunny wins over Grandma and the Prep station]
She learns fast.

1941
01:25:27,277 --> 01:25:29,055
As expected.

1942
01:25:29,055 --> 01:25:31,375
[Time flies by]

1943
01:25:31,983 --> 01:25:34,751
[11:00 AM, lunch service begins]

1944
01:25:35,597 --> 01:25:37,855
[The kitchen is ready for service]

1945
01:25:37,855 --> 01:25:40,191
[Preparing to welcome guests]

1946
01:25:43,023 --> 01:25:46,047
[Prep No.3 Xu Jian Kai gives her chopsticks]
- Here. - Okay.

1947
01:25:46,047 --> 01:25:47,599
[Service start]
Essential chopsticks.

1948
01:25:47,599 --> 01:25:49,177
[Why?]
Chopsticks.

1949
01:25:49,177 --> 01:25:50,271
Why?

1950
01:25:50,271 --> 01:25:52,948
[A weapon for the battlefield]
- For plating. - Yeah.

1951
01:25:53,567 --> 01:25:56,143
[Thanks to the chic Prep station Senior chef]

1952
01:25:56,143 --> 01:25:59,067
[Chopsticks for plating are ready]

1953
01:25:59,067 --> 01:26:04,192
Ask that Kitchen junior over there.

1954
01:26:05,599 --> 01:26:07,391
The Kitchen junior?

1955
01:26:07,391 --> 01:26:09,807
We call him the Kitchen junior.
He's very young.

1956
01:26:09,807 --> 01:26:13,679
I think he's 21.

1957
01:26:13,679 --> 01:26:15,167
Who? That guy?

1958
01:26:15,167 --> 01:26:16,799
He's 21?

1959
01:26:16,799 --> 01:26:18,303
21.

1960
01:26:18,303 --> 01:26:20,255
[Drawing the MZ line]
He's really young.

1961
01:26:20,255 --> 01:26:22,187
Our MZ.

1962
01:26:22,965 --> 01:26:24,254
He's a young junior.

1963
01:26:24,254 --> 01:26:27,349
[A chic senior
whose age is less than a 24-year career]

1964
01:26:27,349 --> 01:26:29,311
[Sunny's 21-year-old senior appears]
There he is.

1965
01:26:29,311 --> 01:26:31,711
[This guy...]

1966
01:26:32,687 --> 01:26:34,495
[Striding over Startled!]

1967
01:26:34,495 --> 01:26:37,295
Are you 21?

1968
01:26:37,295 --> 01:26:39,263
- How old are you?
- I'm 22 this year.

1969
01:26:39,263 --> 01:26:41,135
22.

1970
01:26:41,775 --> 01:26:43,871
How old do you think I am?

1971
01:26:43,871 --> 01:26:45,983
- Wait a second.
- Suddenly asking about age?

1972
01:26:45,983 --> 01:26:47,718
Why are you suddenly asking age?

1973
01:26:47,718 --> 01:26:48,991
- Why age?
- I just want to ask.

1974
01:26:48,991 --> 01:26:50,369
How old do you think I am?

1975
01:26:50,369 --> 01:26:52,415
I think you're over 30.

1976
01:26:52,415 --> 01:26:53,999
I'm 44.

1977
01:26:53,999 --> 01:26:55,199
[Eyes widening]
You're 44?

1978
01:26:55,199 --> 01:26:56,751
- I'm over 40.
- So you're 45.

1979
01:26:56,751 --> 01:26:59,519
[No, 44!]
Not 45.

1980
01:26:59,519 --> 01:27:01,903
- She's 44.
- Yes, 44.

1981
01:27:01,903 --> 01:27:03,007
44?

1982
01:27:03,007 --> 01:27:04,479
You're two years older than me.

1983
01:27:04,479 --> 01:27:06,607
[A senior two years younger]
44?

1984
01:27:06,607 --> 01:27:07,787
She says she's 44.

1985
01:27:07,787 --> 01:27:09,549
[Prep Chief 42, Sunny 44, Senior 22]
Really?

1986
01:27:09,549 --> 01:27:12,007
I'm the oldest one here.

1987
01:27:12,007 --> 01:27:14,407
You don't look 44 at all.

1988
01:27:14,407 --> 01:27:16,175
[Buzzing over Sunny's youthful looks]
- 44. - She's in her 40s.

1989
01:27:16,175 --> 01:27:17,583
She's 44.

1990
01:27:17,583 --> 01:27:19,215
She doesn't look it at all.

1991
01:27:19,215 --> 01:27:20,398
[Grateful]

1992
01:27:21,343 --> 01:27:24,736
Guess how old Sunny is!

1993
01:27:24,736 --> 01:27:26,623
[Asking and answering himself...]
She's 44.

1994
01:27:26,623 --> 01:27:29,023
It's all they're talking about in the kitchen.

1995
01:27:29,023 --> 01:27:30,447
How old do you think she is?

1996
01:27:30,447 --> 01:27:32,095
How old is she?

1997
01:27:32,095 --> 01:27:36,293
[Prep Chief's bulletin: Sunny is 44!]
She's 44.

1998
01:27:37,391 --> 01:27:39,343
She looks so young, though.

1999
01:27:39,343 --> 01:27:42,086
[The Prep Chief continues...]
She does look young.

2000
01:27:42,086 --> 01:27:44,709
[Emergency Bulletin #2]
Sunny is 44.

2001
01:27:44,709 --> 01:27:46,511
[Emergency Bulletin #3]
- 44. - Her age is a hot topic.

2002
01:27:46,511 --> 01:27:48,176
[Is it her baby face?]
He must be in shock.

2003
01:27:48,176 --> 01:27:49,636
[Emergency Bulletin #4]
Sunny is 44.

2004
01:27:49,636 --> 01:27:53,420
[Sunny's info he wants to spread]

2005
01:27:54,815 --> 01:27:57,663
[Meanwhile, outside? Two guests enter]
Guests?

2006
01:27:57,663 --> 01:27:59,455
[Following them]
Customers are coming in now.

2007
01:27:59,455 --> 01:28:01,189
[A large family appears]
Hello.

2008
01:28:01,189 --> 01:28:03,717
- Is this all one family?
- It's not just one or two people.

2009
01:28:03,717 --> 01:28:06,141
It's always five or six.

2010
01:28:07,087 --> 01:28:09,327
[Like a banquet hall]
The tables are all so big.

2011
01:28:09,327 --> 01:28:12,879
[Crowded with group guests]
A lot of large families come here to eat.

2012
01:28:12,879 --> 01:28:15,695
[Beep beep]

2013
01:28:15,695 --> 01:28:17,897
[Order sheets keep coming out]

2014
01:28:18,635 --> 01:28:19,995
It's starting now.

2015
01:28:19,995 --> 01:28:22,383
[Orders signaling the start of service]

2016
01:28:22,383 --> 01:28:23,962
Please prepare the dishes!

2017
01:28:23,962 --> 01:28:26,447
Table two. Start cooking!

2018
01:28:26,447 --> 01:28:28,031
[Orders flood in with the crowd]
One stir-fried tea tree mushroom.

2019
01:28:28,031 --> 01:28:30,177
One grass carp, prepped.

2020
01:28:30,177 --> 01:28:31,577
One grass carp, prepped.

2021
01:28:31,577 --> 01:28:34,031
[It's finally starting]

2022
01:28:37,439 --> 01:28:39,311
[Flames erupt from the burners]

2023
01:28:41,759 --> 01:28:43,967
[Ingredients on the fire for the guests]

2024
01:28:43,967 --> 01:28:46,191
That looks delicious.

2025
01:28:46,191 --> 01:28:48,173
They're using good ingredients.

2026
01:28:56,044 --> 01:28:57,100
[Wok station]

2027
01:28:57,100 --> 01:28:58,923
[Prep team takes their spots]

2028
01:28:58,923 --> 01:28:59,997
Sir!

2029
01:28:59,997 --> 01:29:02,431
[Prep station No. 2]
If you finish the prep work in advance,

2030
01:29:02,431 --> 01:29:03,715
then the Wok station can just...

2031
01:29:03,715 --> 01:29:05,206
- That's right.
- do their thing.

2032
01:29:05,206 --> 01:29:06,927
[Sunny quickly stands behind her senior]

2033
01:29:08,063 --> 01:29:11,359
[Cleaning the counter]

2034
01:29:11,359 --> 01:29:14,111
She's working so hard.

2035
01:29:14,111 --> 01:29:15,263
[Clean]

2036
01:29:16,607 --> 01:29:18,991
[Plating the dish in a bowl]

2037
01:29:19,951 --> 01:29:22,815
[Replacing bowls for the senior chef]

2038
01:29:24,527 --> 01:29:28,703
If you're quick on the uptake like this,
it makes you look good.

2039
01:29:28,703 --> 01:29:29,804
How do you read this?

2040
01:29:29,804 --> 01:29:31,212
[Chili oil steamed fish]
Feiteng Yu.

2041
01:29:31,212 --> 01:29:33,777
[Learning names in between!]
- Feiteng Yu. - Fei...

2042
01:29:33,777 --> 01:29:35,935
- It must be hard to memorize the names.
- I know.

2043
01:29:35,935 --> 01:29:37,023
Fei...

2044
01:29:37,023 --> 01:29:39,583
It's hard.

2045
01:29:39,583 --> 01:29:41,023
[Hands busy while memorizing names]

2046
01:29:41,023 --> 01:29:44,292
[Chili oil steamed fish]
Fish dish.

2047
01:29:45,727 --> 01:29:49,519
[Prep No. 3 coolly approaches Sunny]

2048
01:29:50,137 --> 01:29:52,674
[Scanning the 22-year-old senior's moves]

2049
01:29:52,674 --> 01:29:54,047
[Sprinkling huajiao and red chili]

2050
01:29:54,047 --> 01:29:56,735
That's the aroma. Those are the spices.

2051
01:29:56,735 --> 01:29:59,199
[Plenty of minced garlic]

2052
01:29:59,199 --> 01:30:01,359
[A heap of green onions]

2053
01:30:01,359 --> 01:30:03,999
[Focusing on not missing a single step]

2054
01:30:03,999 --> 01:30:05,711
[And]

2055
01:30:05,711 --> 01:30:07,759
[The highlight of Feiteng Yu]

2056
01:30:07,759 --> 01:30:08,847
[Plenty of dried chilies]

2057
01:30:08,847 --> 01:30:11,551
[Sichuan is all about chilies!]
There are so many types of chilies.

2058
01:30:11,551 --> 01:30:14,047
[Sizzling Sichuan flavors in the wok]
The scale of the chili oil is different.

2059
01:30:14,047 --> 01:30:16,511
It looks so delicious just by looking at it.

2060
01:30:16,511 --> 01:30:18,111
[Over the Wok station's shoulder]

2061
01:30:18,111 --> 01:30:20,943
[Observing the wok skills]

2062
01:30:20,943 --> 01:30:23,375
[Super-focused]
You're watching very intently.

2063
01:30:23,375 --> 01:30:25,592
[Spicy and numbing boiled chili oil]

2064
01:30:28,382 --> 01:30:30,031
[Sichuan flavors coating the tender fish]

2065
01:30:30,031 --> 01:30:31,711
That looks delicious.

2066
01:30:31,711 --> 01:30:33,387
[Steamed Fish with Chili Oil]
Chili oil...

2067
01:30:33,387 --> 01:30:35,855
Pour it over for the scallion aroma,
it's game over.

2068
01:30:35,855 --> 01:30:38,415
[Wiping the plates immediately]

2069
01:30:39,775 --> 01:30:41,497
Wipe it later.

2070
01:30:41,497 --> 01:30:44,271
I haven't finished pouring the oil yet.

2071
01:30:44,271 --> 01:30:46,987
[Instantly disciplined
by her Prep station senior]

2072
01:30:46,987 --> 01:30:49,954
[A senior is a senior!]

2073
01:30:51,343 --> 01:30:55,455
[Waiting for the Steamed Fish with Chili Oil
to be fully plated]

2074
01:30:55,455 --> 01:30:57,535
[Wiping the plate clean]

2075
01:30:58,735 --> 01:31:03,519
[Delivering the dish to the server
as she learned on the first day]

2076
01:31:04,319 --> 01:31:06,347
[Returning to her post]

2077
01:31:07,311 --> 01:31:10,347
[Another Steamed Fish with Chili Oil
added in the meantime]

2078
01:31:11,167 --> 01:31:14,415
[Plating it beautifully as she was taught]

2079
01:31:14,415 --> 01:31:15,917
[And then?]

2080
01:31:16,623 --> 01:31:19,471
[Sunny picks up the minced garlic
to top the dish]

2081
01:31:21,935 --> 01:31:23,519
[Urgent]
What's his deal?

2082
01:31:23,519 --> 01:31:25,983
- Seasoning first before the minced garlic.
- The seasoning.

2083
01:31:25,983 --> 01:31:29,791
[Prep No. 3 teaching the unfamiliar Sunny]
- The order is important. - Seasoning first.

2084
01:31:29,791 --> 01:31:31,487
You don't need to put in too much.

2085
01:31:31,487 --> 01:31:33,999
If you add too much,
the aroma will be too strong.

2086
01:31:33,999 --> 01:31:35,151
This much?

2087
01:31:35,151 --> 01:31:36,799
- Is this enough?
- Yes, that's perfect.

2088
01:31:36,799 --> 01:31:39,453
All the flavors seem very strong here.

2089
01:31:39,453 --> 01:31:41,759
That's right. There are many types of spices.

2090
01:31:41,759 --> 01:31:46,015
[Sunny handles the next ingredients
perfectly on her own]

2091
01:31:47,135 --> 01:31:50,639
[Swiftly]

2092
01:31:50,639 --> 01:31:54,111
[She's learning diligently]

2093
01:31:54,111 --> 01:31:55,764
Should I take this over?

2094
01:31:56,907 --> 01:32:01,815
[The diligent and quick (24-year veteran)
Kitchen junior, Sunny]

2095
01:32:05,519 --> 01:32:08,306
[A fish catches Sunny's eye]
What kind of fish is that?

2096
01:32:08,306 --> 01:32:09,844
What dish is this?

2097
01:32:09,844 --> 01:32:12,127
- Braised Freshwater Fish with Agastache.
- Agastache?

2098
01:32:12,127 --> 01:32:14,523
[Agastache?]
What is Agastache?

2099
01:32:14,523 --> 01:32:17,148
[Agastache removes the fishy smell]
- It's this. - Ah, Agastache.

2100
01:32:17,148 --> 01:32:20,191
[Prep No. 3 shows Sunny what she needs]
Freshwater fish with Agastache.

2101
01:32:20,191 --> 01:32:21,519
[Tapping]

2102
01:32:21,519 --> 01:32:23,167
Is that stir-fried seafood and mushrooms?

2103
01:32:23,167 --> 01:32:24,578
What's that one?

2104
01:32:24,578 --> 01:32:28,536
[Sunny asks more questions]
It's the fried chicken feet you asked about.

2105
01:32:29,471 --> 01:32:32,687
[Braised Freshwater Fish with Agastache done]
This looks delicious.

2106
01:32:32,687 --> 01:32:34,943
Wow, it's beautiful.

2107
01:32:34,943 --> 01:32:38,943
[Piled high with spicy-sweet sauce]
- I want to try this. - Just put it on rice...

2108
01:32:38,943 --> 01:32:40,591
It's game over.

2109
01:32:40,591 --> 01:32:42,591
Is this how I should serve it?

2110
01:32:44,463 --> 01:32:47,647
[Her go-to person for questions]

2111
01:32:47,647 --> 01:32:49,407
Jian Kai, Jian Kai, like this?

2112
01:32:49,407 --> 01:32:50,537
[When Sunny asks for help]

2113
01:32:50,537 --> 01:32:52,383
[The sweet 22-year-old MZ Senior comes over]

2114
01:32:52,383 --> 01:32:54,639
Yes, that's how you do it.

2115
01:32:54,639 --> 01:32:57,272
[Reliable]
You can learn slowly. Take your time.

2116
01:32:57,272 --> 01:32:58,690
It was nice to see her asking questions.

2117
01:32:58,690 --> 01:33:03,199
I thought Sunny was very courageous.

2118
01:33:03,199 --> 01:33:04,303
Courage?

2119
01:33:04,303 --> 01:33:06,244
- Courageous.
- That's how it goes at first.

2120
01:33:06,244 --> 01:33:10,095
[Praise from a senior 22 years her junior]
That's how it goes at first.

2121
01:33:10,095 --> 01:33:12,355
How could your senior
give you a review like that?

2122
01:33:12,355 --> 01:33:13,487
What do you think, Ji Sun?

2123
01:33:13,487 --> 01:33:15,567
[Seething]
I'm a bit annoyed to be evaluated.

2124
01:33:15,567 --> 01:33:17,876
First of all, you hate being evaluated.

2125
01:33:17,876 --> 01:33:19,327
No matter what kind of evaluation it is.

2126
01:33:19,327 --> 01:33:21,531
He's cute.

2127
01:33:22,575 --> 01:33:25,615
[Awkward silence]

2128
01:33:25,615 --> 01:33:27,468
He's got something in his ear?

2129
01:33:27,468 --> 01:33:28,623
What's in his ear?

2130
01:33:28,623 --> 01:33:30,182
Yeah, he's MZ.

2131
01:33:30,182 --> 01:33:31,887
[Listening to music with an earbud!]
Music.

2132
01:33:31,887 --> 01:33:33,007
- He works to music?
- Music?

2133
01:33:33,007 --> 01:33:34,479
He works while listening to music?

2134
01:33:34,479 --> 01:33:36,711
[Earbud in all morning]
Music and phone calls.

2135
01:33:36,711 --> 01:33:37,791
Oh, really?

2136
01:33:37,791 --> 01:33:40,335
He's very free-spirited.

2137
01:33:40,335 --> 01:33:42,367
Is he the owner's son or something?

2138
01:33:42,367 --> 01:33:43,538
- In his ear...
- No.

2139
01:33:43,538 --> 01:33:45,807
- It's not easy.
- Earbuds at work are common these days.

2140
01:33:45,807 --> 01:33:46,911
What's your take on that?

2141
01:33:46,911 --> 01:33:49,137
- Me?
- Yeah, you're Gen MZ.

2142
01:33:52,687 --> 01:33:54,479
[Owner Kwon]
It's not allowed in the kitchen.

2143
01:33:54,479 --> 01:33:55,919
[Exactly]
Oh, it's not allowed?

2144
01:33:55,919 --> 01:33:57,368
The kitchen is dangerous.

2145
01:33:57,368 --> 01:33:59,055
You must keep your ears open at all times.

2146
01:33:59,055 --> 01:34:01,407
- I agree with that.
- Exactly.

2147
01:34:01,407 --> 01:34:05,135
[Always be careful]
[Lips sealed tight]

2148
01:34:05,135 --> 01:34:06,575
If you get on Ji Sun's bad side...

2149
01:34:06,575 --> 01:34:09,147
It's over. You're on Ji Sun's bad side now.

2150
01:34:09,147 --> 01:34:10,687
One stir-fried kidney bean dish!

2151
01:34:10,687 --> 01:34:11,763
Where is it?

2152
01:34:11,763 --> 01:34:14,127
[Need to prepare the ingredients]
- The kidney beans. - It's over there.

2153
01:34:14,127 --> 01:34:17,263
Does Sunny know how to prep this? Teach her.

2154
01:34:17,263 --> 01:34:19,455
Try prepping the kidney beans.

2155
01:34:19,455 --> 01:34:21,691
- Kidney beans.
- Yes.

2156
01:34:22,523 --> 01:34:23,816
Is this it?

2157
01:34:23,816 --> 01:34:26,095
[Sunny already knows where the ingredients are]
That's right.

2158
01:34:26,095 --> 01:34:27,471
Kidney beans!

2159
01:34:27,471 --> 01:34:30,047
Yes. Now coat them in starch and fry them.

2160
01:34:30,047 --> 01:34:32,241
[Coating the beans in starch]
Fry these?

2161
01:34:35,727 --> 01:34:38,447
Hold the sieve and shake it.

2162
01:34:38,447 --> 01:34:40,671
[Learning new tasks with ease]
Starch, starch...

2163
01:34:40,671 --> 01:34:42,495
- Yes.
- On the boiled kidney beans.

2164
01:34:42,495 --> 01:34:44,587
[Sunny preps the kidney beans]
Starch, then fry?

2165
01:34:44,587 --> 01:34:46,742
[Drop!]

2166
01:34:48,079 --> 01:34:50,351
[Coat in starch and fry until golden]

2167
01:34:51,743 --> 01:34:56,383
[Quickly stir-fry with vegetables
for a sweet and savory flavor]

2168
01:34:56,383 --> 01:34:58,899
[Stir-fried kidney beans]
This was actually really delicious.

2169
01:34:58,899 --> 01:35:01,557
There's no way that's not good.

2170
01:35:04,319 --> 01:35:06,863
[Stir-fried kidney beans ready]
Kidney beans.

2171
01:35:06,863 --> 01:35:08,327
[Glance]

2172
01:35:09,055 --> 01:35:10,095
[Glance]

2173
01:35:12,975 --> 01:35:14,879
[She's not spying]

2174
01:35:14,879 --> 01:35:18,566
I was curious about
what was happening at the Wok station.

2175
01:35:19,295 --> 01:35:20,567
[Slide]

2176
01:35:21,199 --> 01:35:25,167
[Observing the Senior's wok skills]

2177
01:35:25,167 --> 01:35:27,487
Because you need to get to that position.

2178
01:35:27,487 --> 01:35:29,935
I wanted to see how the Senior handled the wok.

2179
01:35:29,935 --> 01:35:32,991
This wok is much tougher than I thought.

2180
01:35:32,991 --> 01:35:35,467
[Sunny studies the wok whenever she can]
Couldn't look away.

2181
01:35:35,467 --> 01:35:38,399
I kept thinking I had to find a way.

2182
01:35:38,399 --> 01:35:39,663
So I watched his positioning.

2183
01:35:39,663 --> 01:35:41,263
The basics are similar.

2184
01:35:41,263 --> 01:35:43,359
[When the Wok station Senior reaches up?]
Right.

2185
01:35:43,359 --> 01:35:45,247
[Sunny follows along]

2186
01:35:45,999 --> 01:35:47,871
[She's so diligent...]
She kept watching him.

2187
01:35:47,871 --> 01:35:49,823
Observing with hawk-like eyes.

2188
01:35:49,823 --> 01:35:52,911
[Her neck is busy keeping up]

2189
01:35:52,911 --> 01:35:55,199
[What dish is that?]

2190
01:35:55,199 --> 01:35:57,535
[Swish, swish]

2191
01:35:58,559 --> 01:36:00,623
That's Gongbao Pork.

2192
01:36:00,623 --> 01:36:02,207
[A classic Sichuan dish]
Gongbao Pork.

2193
01:36:02,207 --> 01:36:03,871
This one doesn't use chicken.

2194
01:36:03,871 --> 01:36:05,750
- This version uses pork.
- Yes.

2195
01:36:05,750 --> 01:36:07,795
[If it's chicken, Gongbao Jiding]
'Ji' is chicken.

2196
01:36:07,795 --> 01:36:10,882
[If it's shrimp, Gongbao Shrimp]
- Look so good. - It's just "Yuk" means pork.

2197
01:36:10,882 --> 01:36:12,671
[Infusing oil with garlic and ginger]

2198
01:36:13,375 --> 01:36:16,319
[Red peppers and huajiao turn up the heat]

2199
01:36:17,375 --> 01:36:20,527
[Lightly frying the diced pork in oil]

2200
01:36:20,527 --> 01:36:22,911
[Adding the key ingredients:
peanuts and celery]

2201
01:36:22,911 --> 01:36:26,639
[Wok technique to quickly sauté everything]
Like that, over high heat.

2202
01:36:27,247 --> 01:36:30,628
[I need to get back to that wok...]

2203
01:36:30,628 --> 01:36:32,847
[Stir-frying over high heat
with powerful wok movements]

2204
01:36:32,847 --> 01:36:34,607
[Torture...]
It's bound to be delicious.

2205
01:36:34,607 --> 01:36:35,996
[Gongbao Pork is complete]

2206
01:36:35,996 --> 01:36:38,143
It's surprisingly good when eaten with peanuts.

2207
01:36:38,143 --> 01:36:39,743
Oh, it looks so good.

2208
01:36:39,743 --> 01:36:41,087
- Chinese food...
- Right.

2209
01:36:41,087 --> 01:36:42,591
I'd probably order everything.

2210
01:36:42,591 --> 01:36:44,143
Gongbao Pork.

2211
01:36:44,143 --> 01:36:46,143
[The dish finished at the Wok station]

2212
01:36:46,143 --> 01:36:48,703
[is served on the guest's table]

2213
01:36:52,079 --> 01:36:56,431
[A parade of various dishes
heading to the tables]

2214
01:36:56,431 --> 01:36:58,237
That looks amazing.

2215
01:36:58,237 --> 01:36:59,343
[Tender and juicy]

2216
01:37:00,479 --> 01:37:04,927
The meatballs are good. Try some.

2217
01:37:05,615 --> 01:37:07,951
[Munch munch]

2218
01:37:07,951 --> 01:37:12,747
I think it suits my palate.

2219
01:37:12,747 --> 01:37:15,503
[Drinking straight from the bowl]
Even the elders come here to eat,

2220
01:37:15,503 --> 01:37:18,319
[Satisfied smile]
which means...

2221
01:37:18,319 --> 01:37:20,600
[The father and daughter duo
also have their mouths full]

2222
01:37:21,295 --> 01:37:25,647
The scorched rice was so good,
I ate a lot of it.

2223
01:37:25,647 --> 01:37:26,959
Tell him to try some.

2224
01:37:26,959 --> 01:37:30,439
[A taste that captivates even a child]
Let him try it after it cools down.

2225
01:37:32,219 --> 01:37:33,663
She's eating so well.

2226
01:37:33,663 --> 01:37:36,687
The food here is a real rice thief.

2227
01:37:36,687 --> 01:37:37,837
[A rice cooker on the table]

2228
01:37:37,837 --> 01:37:40,479
- They brought out the whole rice cooker.
- The whole rice cooker?

2229
01:37:40,479 --> 01:37:41,887
[The generosity of the mainland]

2230
01:37:41,887 --> 01:37:44,527
[Generous portions]
They give the cooker so they can scoop it.

2231
01:37:44,527 --> 01:37:45,627
[Refills are a must here]
Looks delicious.

2232
01:37:45,627 --> 01:37:47,103
They started with rice this morning.

2233
01:37:47,103 --> 01:37:50,543
[One rice cooker per table]
So it's one rice cooker per table?

2234
01:37:50,543 --> 01:37:54,943
[While the guests enjoy their lunch
with extra helpings of rice]

2235
01:37:54,943 --> 01:37:57,901
[A large family birthday party]
Wow, look at all those plates stacked up.

2236
01:37:57,901 --> 01:38:00,111
It's my first time seeing the dining hall.

2237
01:38:00,111 --> 01:38:02,063
[Teasing]
Chef, you're not a chef anymore, right?

2238
01:38:02,063 --> 01:38:03,871
No, I'm not.

2239
01:38:03,871 --> 01:38:07,679
[Birthday party turns the hall into a banquet]
It really is a party banquet hall.

2240
01:38:07,679 --> 01:38:09,855
[When will I be able to serve my own dishes?]

2241
01:38:10,511 --> 01:38:13,359
[Charging in!]
There really are so many.

2242
01:38:13,359 --> 01:38:15,887
[Moving deeper toward another Wok station...]

2243
01:38:15,887 --> 01:38:17,887
[Infiltration]

2244
01:38:18,863 --> 01:38:22,143
[The kitchen of the grand hall is still hectic]

2245
01:38:25,103 --> 01:38:26,271
[Dishes keep pouring out]

2246
01:38:26,271 --> 01:38:28,271
The dishes are endless. Just endless.

2247
01:38:28,271 --> 01:38:29,967
Since there are 160 menu items.

2248
01:38:29,967 --> 01:38:31,866
I know, right?

2249
01:38:32,671 --> 01:38:36,575
[I want to focus so I can
move up to the wok station...]

2250
01:38:37,631 --> 01:38:39,535
[Sliding in]

2251
01:38:39,535 --> 01:38:41,916
- Should I take this out?
- Yes, you can take it out.

2252
01:38:42,575 --> 01:38:44,543
[Delivering finished dishes with ease]

2253
01:38:44,543 --> 01:38:47,055
[Wiping plates with ease]

2254
01:38:47,055 --> 01:38:49,207
[Organizing tableware with ease]

2255
01:38:50,157 --> 01:38:55,311
[Sunny stays busy during the rush]

2256
01:38:55,897 --> 01:38:59,599
[Grandma watches Sunny working hard]

2257
01:38:59,599 --> 01:39:01,510
Where is it? Bring it here.

2258
01:39:01,510 --> 01:39:04,687
Who is she looking for?

2259
01:39:04,687 --> 01:39:06,641
I think it's seasoned meat.

2260
01:39:06,641 --> 01:39:08,247
[Meat?]
It's not a person she's looking for.

2261
01:39:08,247 --> 01:39:10,187
[What is that?]
What is she looking for?

2262
01:39:10,187 --> 01:39:12,159
[Here it is...]
What is this?

2263
01:39:12,159 --> 01:39:14,399
I should let her taste it later.

2264
01:39:14,399 --> 01:39:16,863
[I'll give Sunny a taste of this]
I'll give her a taste.

2265
01:39:16,863 --> 01:39:19,615
[This meat is for Sunny to taste]

2266
01:39:19,615 --> 01:39:21,763
What kind of meat is this?

2267
01:39:23,071 --> 01:39:25,151
[Gulping in anticipation]
Oh, it looks delicious.

2268
01:39:25,151 --> 01:39:27,487
It looks a bit different from the meat I know.

2269
01:39:27,487 --> 01:39:28,591
[Hehe...]

2270
01:39:28,591 --> 01:39:30,943
[Full of chilies and huajiao for a kick!]

2271
01:39:30,943 --> 01:39:33,828
Add the rest...

2272
01:39:35,215 --> 01:39:37,695
[Stir-frying quickly over high heat]

2273
01:39:37,695 --> 01:39:40,111
Stir-fry it over high heat.

2274
01:39:40,747 --> 01:39:43,919
[Ready for Sunny to taste]
What exactly is this dish?

2275
01:39:43,919 --> 01:39:45,467
Sunny, try some.

2276
01:39:46,367 --> 01:39:47,791
[She takes it for now...]

2277
01:39:47,791 --> 01:39:49,327
[What kind of dish is it?]
This is...

2278
01:39:49,327 --> 01:39:50,831
It's rabbit meat.

2279
01:39:50,831 --> 01:39:53,695
- Oh, rabbit meat?
- Yes, rabbit meat.

2280
01:39:53,695 --> 01:39:56,047
[I see!]
- This is rabbit meat? - Rabbit.

2281
01:39:56,047 --> 01:39:59,375
[Stir-fried rabbit with green chilies]
- Looks good. - How will that taste?

2282
01:39:59,375 --> 01:40:00,717
Chopsticks.

2283
01:40:00,717 --> 01:40:02,307
[Speaking Korean]
Rabbit, okay.

2284
01:40:02,307 --> 01:40:04,687
[Rabbit meat isn't common in Korea...]
- Rabbit meat. - Yes.

2285
01:40:04,687 --> 01:40:07,327
[Grandma's special treat]

2286
01:40:08,191 --> 01:40:10,794
[Sunny hesitates for a moment...]

2287
01:40:12,031 --> 01:40:14,383
[She ate it!]

2288
01:40:14,383 --> 01:40:16,317
[How does the rabbit dish taste?]

2289
01:40:17,135 --> 01:40:20,617
[Curious about her reaction]

2290
01:40:20,617 --> 01:40:21,743
[Nodding silently...]

2291
01:40:21,743 --> 01:40:23,287
[Hard to tell]

2292
01:40:23,983 --> 01:40:25,823
[Grandma goes to check her reaction]

2293
01:40:25,823 --> 01:40:27,135
- It's delicious.
- Is it salty?

2294
01:40:27,135 --> 01:40:29,104
- Is it good?
- It's similar to chicken.

2295
01:40:29,104 --> 01:40:31,023
[Beaming]
The meat is tender, right?

2296
01:40:31,023 --> 01:40:33,413
It's delicious.

2297
01:40:33,413 --> 01:40:34,897
[The texture is like]
Chicken breast.

2298
01:40:34,897 --> 01:40:37,064
[Analyzing the taste?]
Things like rabbit or frog...

2299
01:40:37,064 --> 01:40:39,487
Some people might think they smell.

2300
01:40:39,487 --> 01:40:42,239
But they used a very strong mala scent.

2301
01:40:42,239 --> 01:40:43,695
The rabbit meat didn't smell much.

2302
01:40:43,695 --> 01:40:45,919
The mala flavor at the end was nice.

2303
01:40:45,919 --> 01:40:47,759
It tasted good.

2304
01:40:47,759 --> 01:40:51,919
The reason she asked us to bring that over
was to show that it's their signature dish.

2305
01:40:51,919 --> 01:40:53,551
- Yeah.
- Right, that must be it.

2306
01:40:53,551 --> 01:40:55,967
This rabbit meat is very fresh.

2307
01:40:55,967 --> 01:40:57,663
Yes, it's fresh.

2308
01:40:57,663 --> 01:41:02,721
The most important thing
is checking the freshness.

2309
01:41:02,721 --> 01:41:04,406
Follow me.

2310
01:41:05,398 --> 01:41:06,847
Come here.

2311
01:41:06,847 --> 01:41:08,799
I have something to show you.

2312
01:41:08,799 --> 01:41:11,231
[Granny leads Sunny somewhere]

2313
01:41:12,223 --> 01:41:14,783
[What does Granny want to show Sunny?]

2314
01:41:14,783 --> 01:41:16,645
Did you make this yourself?

2315
01:41:16,645 --> 01:41:18,773
- Did you make this yourself?
- Granny made it herself.

2316
01:41:18,773 --> 01:41:20,351
Oh, really?

2317
01:41:20,351 --> 01:41:21,869
- What is it?
- What's this?

2318
01:41:21,869 --> 01:41:23,167
[Sichuan sausage!]
Ham, sausage.

2319
01:41:23,167 --> 01:41:24,575
Sausage.

2320
01:41:24,575 --> 01:41:26,191
She made the ham herself?

2321
01:41:26,191 --> 01:41:29,359
[Sichuan sausage by the 82-year-old chef]
It looks delicious.

2322
01:41:29,359 --> 01:41:30,936
Sichuan sausage. I've never seen this.

2323
01:41:30,936 --> 01:41:31,937
First time seeing this.

2324
01:41:47,237 --> 01:41:49,271
[To eat on New Year's]
They say every household makes it.

2325
01:41:49,271 --> 01:41:52,662
But every family has a different method.

2326
01:41:53,506 --> 01:41:56,475
[Granny's passion remains at 82]
I'll cut some for you to taste.

2327
01:41:56,475 --> 01:41:58,091
Thank you.

2328
01:41:58,091 --> 01:41:59,403
- Is it pork?
- Yes, it's pork.

2329
01:41:59,403 --> 01:42:00,875
Pork.

2330
01:42:02,363 --> 01:42:05,320
[How does Sichuan sausage taste?]
- I eat it like this, right? - Yes.

2331
01:42:10,107 --> 01:42:13,062
[Sunny is amazed by the mala aroma]
There was a subtle scent of mala.

2332
01:42:13,062 --> 01:42:14,467
- I need to take a photo.
- This one.

2333
01:42:14,467 --> 01:42:16,683
A mala sausage product might be coming soon.

2334
01:42:16,683 --> 01:42:19,637
[Capturing Granny's craftsmanship in a photo]

2335
01:42:19,637 --> 01:42:22,155
[Role model: the 82-year-old chef]
Still active in the kitchen.

2336
01:42:22,155 --> 01:42:24,769
- She was very passionate.
- I know.

2337
01:42:24,769 --> 01:42:28,067
[Day 2 at Granny's kitchen in Chengdu,
Sunny is still hovering on the sidelines!]

2338
01:42:28,067 --> 01:42:29,642
- We can't tell yet.
- Right.

2339
01:42:29,642 --> 01:42:32,667
- It's only the second day, just the beginning.
- True.

2340
01:42:32,667 --> 01:42:34,971
Let's see who gets promoted first.

2341
01:42:34,971 --> 01:42:36,635
I think he'll be the first to move up.

2342
01:42:36,635 --> 01:42:37,899
[Poker face]
Oh, really?

2343
01:42:37,899 --> 01:42:39,339
- No.
- We can't tell yet.

2344
01:42:39,339 --> 01:42:41,976
We don't know. We can't tell yet.

2345
01:42:43,373 --> 01:42:44,685
Can anyone do better than this?

2346
01:42:44,685 --> 01:42:46,053
I thought it was perfect.

2347
01:42:46,053 --> 01:42:48,269
[The undercover Kitchen junior trio
is done adjusting]

2348
01:42:49,453 --> 01:42:51,085
It was so much easier.

2349
01:42:52,237 --> 01:42:54,109
I'm just going to watch you tonight.

2350
01:42:54,109 --> 01:42:55,273
You can do it alone.

2351
01:42:55,273 --> 01:42:58,393
[A promotion opportunity for them?]
You're going to do it alone.

2352
01:42:58,393 --> 01:43:01,725
[To those who showed their hidden talents]

2353
01:43:02,669 --> 01:43:04,301
Do you want to compete with No.3?

2354
01:43:04,301 --> 01:43:05,869
[A definite OK]
Okay.

2355
01:43:05,869 --> 01:43:07,093
Okay.

2356
01:43:07,093 --> 01:43:11,949
[A chance to escape being a Kitchen junior?]

2357
01:43:13,453 --> 01:43:18,285
[A battle of taste!]
["Tortelli Blind Test"]

2358
01:43:18,285 --> 01:43:20,957
[6-year fresh pasta veteran Lucrezia]

2359
01:43:20,957 --> 01:43:23,493
[2-day fresh pasta novice Hee Tae]

2360
01:43:23,493 --> 01:43:28,157
[Who will make the most perfect fresh pasta?]

2361
01:43:28,925 --> 01:43:31,021
I'll have to work really hard.

2362
01:43:31,021 --> 01:43:34,189
I can't afford to be embarrassed.

2363
01:43:34,189 --> 01:43:36,829
[Lucrezia vs. Hee Tae!]
What can I do to help with the main dish?

2364
01:43:36,829 --> 01:43:38,717
Is there a way?

2365
01:43:38,717 --> 01:43:42,013
[Will Hee Tae get promoted?]

2366
01:43:42,013 --> 01:43:43,139
[Meanwhile...]

2367
01:43:43,139 --> 01:43:45,643
I'm telling you, doing it like this is bad.

2368
01:43:45,643 --> 01:43:49,805
[A request to stop cooking?]
You're doing it wrong, give it to me.

2369
01:43:49,805 --> 01:43:50,897
Kwon.

2370
01:43:50,897 --> 01:43:53,333
Come with me for a second.

2371
01:43:53,333 --> 01:43:56,773
[An emergency call from the Senior Chef?]

2372
01:43:56,773 --> 01:43:59,680
[What's happening to Sung Jun...?]
Oh, my goodness.

2373
01:44:01,837 --> 01:44:04,397
[A promotion?]

2374
01:44:04,397 --> 01:44:06,013
Oh, no.

2375
01:44:06,013 --> 01:44:08,317
[Staying behind?]

2376
01:44:08,317 --> 01:44:10,253
[Only 3 days left!]

2377
01:44:10,253 --> 01:44:12,029
[Who will be the first to be promoted?]
